var questions_series65 = [{"id":"series65-qb-reg-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an \"agent\" is:","choices":{"A":"Any employee of a broker-dealer","B":"A person who represents a broker-dealer in securities transactions","C":"The owner of a broker-dealer","D":"A compliance officer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under state law (USA), an agent is an individual who represents a broker-dealer or issuer in effecting or attempting to effect securities transactions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-series7-ch2-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A debenture is:","choices":{"A":"A bond secured by real estate","B":"An unsecured bond backed by the issuer's creditworthiness","C":"A bond secured by equipment","D":"A subordinated mortgage bond"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A debenture is an unsecured bond backed only by the issuer's full faith and credit, not by any specific collateral. This is a fundamental definition frequently tested on the Series 7 exam. Debentures carry more risk than secured bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-001","section":"Economics","stem":"Which of the following is a LEADING economic indicator?","choices":{"A":"Unemployment rate","B":"Building permits","C":"Consumer Price Index (CPI)","D":"Prime rate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Building permits are a leading indicator because they predict future construction activity - construction begins months after permits are issued. The unemployment rate, CPI, and prime rate are all lagging indicators that confirm trends after they occur. Leading indicators help advisers anticipate economic changes before they happen.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-002","section":"Economics","stem":"A recession is technically defined as:","choices":{"A":"One quarter of negative GDP growth","B":"Two consecutive quarters of negative GDP growth","C":"Six consecutive quarters of negative GDP growth","D":"Any period of rising unemployment above 5%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A recession is technically defined as two consecutive quarters of declining GDP (Gross Domestic Product). Six consecutive quarters of declining GDP would constitute a depression. While rising unemployment often accompanies recessions, the technical definition is based on GDP. Investment advisers should understand this distinction for client communications during economic downturns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-003","section":"Economics","stem":"During the peak phase of the business cycle, an investment adviser would most likely recommend that a risk-averse client:","choices":{"A":"Increase exposure to cyclical stocks","B":"Take on additional leverage to maximize returns","C":"Consider reducing equity exposure and shifting toward defensive sectors","D":"Invest heavily in high-yield bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"At the peak, the economy is at its highest point but also at greatest risk of turning down. For a risk-averse client, an adviser should consider reducing equity exposure and shifting toward defensive sectors (utilities, consumer staples, healthcare) that hold up better during downturns. Increasing cyclical stocks or leverage would increase risk, and high-yield bonds typically underperform when economic conditions deteriorate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-004","section":"Economics","stem":"The Federal Reserve's dual mandate includes which of the following objectives?","choices":{"A":"Balanced federal budget and low taxes","B":"Maximum employment and price stability","C":"Strong dollar and trade surplus","D":"High stock prices and low interest rates"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Congress gave the Federal Reserve a dual mandate: maximum employment and price stability (controlling inflation at around 2%). The Fed does not control fiscal policy (budgets, taxes), trade policy, or stock prices. Understanding the dual mandate helps advisers anticipate Fed actions - the Fed may raise rates to fight inflation even if it risks higher unemployment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["monetary-policy"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-005","section":"Economics","stem":"If the Federal Reserve wants to STIMULATE economic growth, it would most likely:","choices":{"A":"Raise the federal funds rate and sell government securities","B":"Lower the federal funds rate and buy government securities","C":"Increase reserve requirements and raise the discount rate","D":"Reduce government spending and raise taxes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To stimulate the economy (expansionary policy), the Fed lowers the federal funds rate and buys government securities. Buying securities injects money into the economy, increasing the money supply and lowering rates. Raising rates, selling securities, or increasing reserve requirements would be contractionary. Government spending and taxes are fiscal policy, controlled by Congress - not the Fed.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-006","section":"Economics","stem":"The Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) is primarily responsible for:","choices":{"A":"Regulating broker-dealers and investment advisers","B":"Setting monetary policy, including the federal funds rate target","C":"Approving new securities offerings and IPOs","D":"Enforcing securities laws and prosecuting fraud"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The FOMC is the monetary policymaking body of the Federal Reserve System. It meets eight times per year to set the target federal funds rate and determine open market operations. The SEC (not the FOMC) regulates broker-dealers and advisers, approves securities offerings, and enforces securities laws. Advisers should follow FOMC meetings closely as their decisions directly impact client portfolios.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["monetary-policy","frb"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-007","section":"Economics","stem":"During a recession, which fiscal policy action would be most appropriate?","choices":{"A":"Increase taxes and reduce government spending","B":"Decrease taxes and increase government spending","C":"Keep taxes and spending unchanged","D":"Raise interest rates and sell government securities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During a recession, expansionary fiscal policy is appropriate: decreasing taxes (putting more money in consumers' pockets) and increasing government spending to stimulate economic activity. Increasing taxes and reducing spending would be contractionary and worsen the recession. Raising interest rates and selling securities is monetary policy (controlled by the Fed), not fiscal policy.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-008","section":"Economics","stem":"What is the difference between the annual budget deficit and the national debt?","choices":{"A":"They are the same thing, just measured differently","B":"The deficit is one year's shortfall; the debt is the cumulative total of all deficits","C":"The debt is controlled by the Fed; the deficit is controlled by Congress","D":"The deficit includes interest payments; the debt does not"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The annual budget deficit is the shortfall in one year (spending minus revenue). The national debt is the cumulative total of all past deficits minus any surpluses - the total amount the government owes. Think of it like a credit card: the deficit is this year's balance, while the debt is the total outstanding balance. Both are controlled by Congress through fiscal policy.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-009","section":"Economics","stem":"Which statement about fiscal policy is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"It is controlled by the Federal Reserve","B":"It can be implemented quickly through FOMC meetings","C":"It involves government taxation and spending decisions made by Congress","D":"It primarily affects the money supply through open market operations"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fiscal policy involves government taxation and spending decisions made by Congress and the President. The Federal Reserve controls monetary policy (not fiscal). Fiscal policy is slow to implement because it requires legislation - unlike monetary policy, which can be adjusted quickly at FOMC meetings. Open market operations are a monetary policy tool, not fiscal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-010","section":"Economics","stem":"Which investment is MOST negatively affected by unexpected inflation?","choices":{"A":"Common stocks","B":"Real estate","C":"Long-term fixed-rate bonds","D":"Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Long-term fixed-rate bonds are most hurt by unexpected inflation because their fixed interest payments lose purchasing power over time. The longer the duration, the greater the impact. TIPS are specifically designed to protect against inflation. Real estate typically benefits as a hard asset whose value rises with prices. Common stocks have mixed results - companies may pass costs to consumers, providing some protection.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-011","section":"Economics","stem":"An investor earns a 7% return on her portfolio while inflation is 2.5%. What is her approximate real rate of return?","choices":{"A":"2.5%","B":"4.5%","C":"7%","D":"9.5%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Real return equals nominal return minus inflation: 7% - 2.5% = 4.5%. This represents the actual increase in purchasing power. Investment advisers should always discuss returns in real terms to help clients understand their true wealth accumulation. A 7% nominal return sounds good, but if inflation were 7%, the real return would be zero - no actual increase in purchasing power.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-012","section":"Economics","stem":"The Consumer Price Index (CPI) is published by:","choices":{"A":"The Federal Reserve","B":"The Bureau of Labor Statistics","C":"The Securities and Exchange Commission","D":"The Department of the Treasury"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) publishes the CPI monthly. The CPI measures price changes for a basket of consumer goods and services and is the most widely used measure of inflation. The Fed uses CPI data to inform monetary policy decisions, but does not publish it. The SEC regulates securities markets, and Treasury manages government finances - neither publishes inflation data.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-014","section":"Economics","stem":"An inverted yield curve, where short-term rates exceed long-term rates, is considered a signal of:","choices":{"A":"Strong economic growth ahead","B":"Rising inflation expectations","C":"A potential recession ahead","D":"A healthy banking sector"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An inverted yield curve has historically been a reliable predictor of recession. It occurs when investors expect the Fed to cut short-term rates in the future due to economic weakness - so they lock in current long-term rates, pushing long-term rates below short-term rates. Every U.S. recession since 1970 has been preceded by an inverted yield curve, making it an important indicator for investment advisers to monitor.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-016","section":"Economics","stem":"Which of the following would benefit from a STRENGTHENING U.S. dollar?","choices":{"A":"U.S. companies that export products to Europe","B":"U.S. importers buying goods from Asia","C":"U.S. investors holding European stocks","D":"U.S. manufacturers competing with foreign imports"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A strengthening dollar means U.S. importers can buy more foreign goods with fewer dollars, reducing their costs. U.S. exporters are hurt because their products become more expensive for foreign buyers. U.S. investors holding foreign stocks see their returns reduced when converting back to stronger dollars. U.S. manufacturers competing with imports face cheaper foreign competition.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch1-018","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor buys shares of a Japanese company. The stock price increases 8% in yen, but the yen falls 12% against the dollar. What is the approximate return in dollar terms?","choices":{"A":"Positive 20%","B":"Positive 8%","C":"Negative 4%","D":"Negative 12%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Currency movements affect returns on foreign investments. While the stock gained 8% in yen, the 12% decline of the yen against the dollar more than offset this gain. The approximate dollar return is 8% - 12% = -4%. This illustrates currency risk: even positive foreign stock returns can become negative in dollar terms if the foreign currency weakens sufficiently against the dollar.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-001","section":"Risk Return","stem":"On a company's balance sheet, which equation must always be true?","choices":{"A":"Assets = Liabilities - Shareholders' Equity","B":"Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity","C":"Assets + Liabilities = Shareholders' Equity","D":"Assets - Liabilities = Net Income"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The fundamental accounting equation is Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity. This equation must always balance on every balance sheet. Assets represent what the company owns, liabilities represent what it owes to creditors, and shareholders' equity represents the owners' residual claim. Net income appears on the income statement, not the balance sheet equation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-002","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which financial statement shows a company's profitability over a specific period?","choices":{"A":"Balance sheet","B":"Income statement","C":"Statement of shareholders' equity","D":"Notes to financial statements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The income statement (also called the profit & loss statement) shows revenues, expenses, and net income over a specific period such as a quarter or year. The balance sheet shows the financial position at a single point in time. Investment advisers analyze the income statement to understand profitability trends and margin performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-003","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A company reports strong net income but negative cash flow from operations. This situation most likely indicates:","choices":{"A":"The company is about to go bankrupt","B":"The financial statements contain fraud","C":"Customers may be paying slowly or inventory is building up","D":"The company has too much debt"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When net income is positive but operating cash flow is negative, it often indicates that receivables and/or inventory are growing faster than sales - customers aren't paying quickly, or products aren't selling. This is a quality of earnings concern that advisers should investigate further. It doesn't automatically indicate fraud or bankruptcy, but warrants closer analysis.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-004","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Under accrual basis accounting, when is revenue recorded?","choices":{"A":"When cash is received","B":"When the invoice is sent","C":"When revenue is earned","D":"At the end of the fiscal year"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under accrual accounting, revenue is recorded when it is earned, regardless of when cash is received. For example, if goods are delivered in December but payment is received in January, revenue is recorded in December. This matching principle provides a more accurate picture of business performance and is required by GAAP for public companies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-005","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An auditor's \"unqualified opinion\" on financial statements means:","choices":{"A":"The auditor found significant errors","B":"The financial statements are fairly presented in accordance with GAAP","C":"The auditor could not complete the audit","D":"The company may not be able to continue operating"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An unqualified opinion (also called a \"clean opinion\") is the best type of audit opinion. It means the auditor believes the financial statements are fairly presented in accordance with GAAP, with no material misstatements. This gives investors confidence in the reliability of the financial information. A going concern opinion would indicate potential operating issues.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-006","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE regarding GAAP and IFRS?","choices":{"A":"GAAP is set by the IASB while IFRS is set by FASB","B":"GAAP allows LIFO inventory while IFRS prohibits it","C":"IFRS is rules-based while GAAP is principles-based","D":"Both GAAP and IFRS are required for all U.S. public companies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"GAAP allows the LIFO (Last-In, First-Out) inventory method, while IFRS prohibits it. GAAP is set by FASB and is rules-based, while IFRS is set by IASB and is principles-based. U.S. public companies are required to use GAAP, not IFRS. This distinction can affect financial ratios when comparing U.S. and international companies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which SEC filing must be filed within 4 business days of a material event?","choices":{"A":"Form 10-K","B":"Form 10-Q","C":"Form 8-K","D":"Form 4"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Form 8-K (Current Report) must be filed within 4 business days of a material event, such as a CEO resignation, merger announcement, or bankruptcy filing. This ensures timely disclosure of significant developments to investors. Form 4 (insider transactions) has a 2-business-day deadline, while 10-K and 10-Q have longer filing periods.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-008","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which document contains detailed executive compensation information?","choices":{"A":"Form 10-K","B":"Proxy Statement (DEF 14A)","C":"Form 10-Q","D":"Form 8-K"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Proxy Statement (DEF 14A) is sent to shareholders before the annual meeting and contains detailed executive compensation information, including salary, bonuses, stock awards, and perquisites for top executives. It also includes board member information and matters requiring shareholder votes. While the 10-K contains some compensation information, the proxy provides the comprehensive breakdown.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-009","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Form 4 filings report:","choices":{"A":"Quarterly financial results","B":"Annual audited financial statements","C":"Insider stock purchases and sales","D":"Material events affecting the company"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Form 4 reports transactions by company insiders - directors, officers, and beneficial owners of more than 10% of the company's stock. It must be filed within 2 business days of the transaction. Investment advisers monitor Form 4 filings to track insider buying and selling activity, which may provide insights into management's confidence in the company.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-010","section":"Risk Return","stem":"What is the formula for the current ratio?","choices":{"A":"Current Liabilities / Current Assets","B":"Current Assets / Current Liabilities","C":"(Current Assets - Inventory) / Current Liabilities","D":"Total Assets / Total Liabilities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The current ratio formula is Current Assets / Current Liabilities. It measures a company's ability to pay short-term obligations with short-term assets. A ratio greater than 1.0 indicates the company has more current assets than current liabilities. The formula with inventory subtracted is the quick ratio, which is more conservative.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-011","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The quick ratio differs from the current ratio because the quick ratio:","choices":{"A":"Uses long-term assets instead of current assets","B":"Excludes inventory from current assets","C":"Includes long-term debt in the calculation","D":"Uses market values instead of book values"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The quick ratio (also called acid-test ratio) excludes inventory from current assets because inventory may not sell quickly or may lose value. The formula is (Current Assets - Inventory) / Current Liabilities. This makes it a more conservative measure of liquidity than the current ratio, which includes inventory.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-012","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A company has a PEG ratio of 0.8. This suggests the stock may be:","choices":{"A":"Overvalued relative to its growth rate","B":"Undervalued relative to its growth rate","C":"Fairly valued","D":"Too risky to invest in"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A PEG ratio below 1.0 suggests the stock may be undervalued relative to its growth rate. The PEG ratio divides the P/E ratio by the expected earnings growth rate. A PEG of 0.8 means the P/E is lower than the growth rate would justify, potentially indicating a buying opportunity. However, advisers should consider other factors as well.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-013","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Using the Rule of 72, approximately how many years will it take for an investment to double at a 6% annual return?","choices":{"A":"6 years","B":"12 years","C":"18 years","D":"72 years"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using the Rule of 72: Years to double = 72 / 6 = 12 years. This is a quick approximation for calculating the time needed to double an investment. The Rule of 72 is useful for mental math and client conversations. At 6%, an investment will approximately double in 12 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-014","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which statement about compounding is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Annual compounding produces higher returns than monthly compounding at the same stated rate","B":"Monthly compounding produces higher returns than annual compounding at the same stated rate","C":"Compounding frequency does not affect the effective return","D":"Compounding only applies to savings accounts, not investments"},"answer":"B","explanation":"More frequent compounding (monthly vs. annual) produces higher effective returns at the same stated (nominal) rate. With monthly compounding, interest is calculated and added to principal 12 times per year instead of once, allowing subsequent interest to be earned on that added interest. This is why effective annual rate (EAR) is higher than the stated rate when compounding is more frequent than annual.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-015","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An annuity due differs from an ordinary annuity because an annuity due has:","choices":{"A":"Payments at the end of each period","B":"Payments at the beginning of each period","C":"Variable payment amounts","D":"Payments that continue indefinitely"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An annuity due has payments at the beginning of each period, while an ordinary annuity has payments at the end of each period. Because annuity due payments occur earlier, each payment has more time to compound, making an annuity due worth more than an otherwise identical ordinary annuity. Examples of annuity due include rent and insurance premiums, typically due at the start of each period.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-016","section":"Risk Return","stem":"If an investment has a positive Net Present Value (NPV), an investor should:","choices":{"A":"Reject the investment","B":"Accept the investment","C":"Wait for more information","D":"Only accept if IRR is also negative"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A positive NPV means the present value of expected cash inflows exceeds the initial investment cost at the required rate of return. This indicates the investment adds value and exceeds the required return, so it should be accepted. A positive NPV and an IRR above the required return always occur together for conventional cash flows.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-017","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is best defined as:","choices":{"A":"The discount rate that makes NPV equal to zero","B":"The average annual return over the investment period","C":"The risk-free rate plus a risk premium","D":"The maximum return an investment can achieve"},"answer":"A","explanation":"IRR is defined as the discount rate that makes the Net Present Value (NPV) equal to zero. It represents the expected compound annual rate of return on an investment. If IRR exceeds the required return (hurdle rate), the investment should be accepted. IRR is similar to yield to maturity (YTM) for bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-018","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A company requires a 12% return on investments. An opportunity has an IRR of 15%. The company should:","choices":{"A":"Reject because 15% is too high","B":"Accept because IRR exceeds the required return","C":"Reject because the hurdle rate is only 12%","D":"Request a lower IRR before accepting"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When IRR (15%) exceeds the hurdle rate/required return (12%), the investment earns more than the minimum acceptable return and should be accepted. The 12% is the minimum threshold, not a maximum. An IRR of 15% means the project returns 3 percentage points more than required, adding value for shareholders.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-019","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Investment returns for the past five years are: 5%, 8%, 12%, 3%, and 7%. What is the mean (average) return?","choices":{"A":"5%","B":"7%","C":"8%","D":"12%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The mean is calculated by summing all values and dividing by the number of values: (5 + 8 + 12 + 3 + 7) / 5 = 35 / 5 = 7%. The mean represents the arithmetic average return over the five-year period.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-020","section":"Risk Return","stem":"When analyzing income data that includes some very high earners, which measure of central tendency is most appropriate?","choices":{"A":"Mean","B":"Median","C":"Mode","D":"Standard deviation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The median is most appropriate when data contains outliers or is skewed, such as income data with some very high earners. The median is not affected by extreme values, while the mean would be pulled up by the high earners, giving a misleading picture of \"typical\" income. Standard deviation measures dispersion, not central tendency.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch2-021","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A mutual fund has a mean annual return of 10% with a standard deviation of 12%. In approximately what range would 68% of annual returns fall?","choices":{"A":"0% to 20%","B":"-2% to 22%","C":"-14% to 34%","D":"10% to 22%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"According to the 68-95-99.7 rule (Empirical Rule), approximately 68% of values in a normal distribution fall within one standard deviation of the mean. With a mean of 10% and standard deviation of 12%, the range is 10% +/- 12%, or -2% to 22%. This helps investors understand the typical variability of returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-001","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which of the following risks CANNOT be reduced through diversification?","choices":{"A":"Business risk","B":"Default risk","C":"Market risk","D":"Financial risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Market risk is a systematic risk that cannot be reduced through diversification because it affects the entire market. Even a portfolio of 1,000 stocks would decline during a market crash. Business risk, default risk, and financial risk are unsystematic (company-specific) risks that can be diversified away by holding many different securities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-003","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The PRIME acronym for systematic risks includes all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Purchasing power risk","B":"Regulatory risk (company-specific)","C":"Interest rate risk","D":"Market risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"PRIME stands for Purchasing power, Reinvestment, Interest rate, Market, and Exchange rate risks - all systematic risks that cannot be diversified away. Company-specific regulatory risk (such as a new regulation affecting one company) is an unsystematic risk that can be reduced through diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-004","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Business risk is best described as:","choices":{"A":"The risk that the overall market will decline","B":"The risk related to a company's operations and competitive position","C":"The risk that interest rates will rise","D":"The risk that inflation will erode returns"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Business risk is an unsystematic risk related to a specific company's operations, management quality, competition, and industry position. It includes factors like product failures, management decisions, and labor issues. Unlike market risk (systematic), business risk can be reduced through diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-005","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Financial risk is primarily associated with:","choices":{"A":"Inflation eroding purchasing power","B":"A company's use of debt in its capital structure","C":"Political changes affecting regulations","D":"Currency fluctuations in foreign markets"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Financial risk arises from a company's use of debt (leverage) in its capital structure. Companies with high debt have higher financial risk because they must make interest payments regardless of profitability, increasing the risk of financial distress or bankruptcy. This is an unsystematic risk that can be diversified away.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-006","section":"Risk Return","stem":"How many uncorrelated stocks are typically needed to eliminate most unsystematic risk?","choices":{"A":"5-10 stocks","B":"20-30 stocks","C":"100-200 stocks","D":"500+ stocks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Research shows that approximately 20-30 uncorrelated stocks can eliminate most unsystematic (company-specific) risk. Beyond that number, additional diversification provides diminishing benefits. The remaining risk after proper diversification is systematic (market) risk, which cannot be eliminated through diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-007","section":"Risk Return","stem":"When interest rates rise, bond prices generally:","choices":{"A":"Rise","B":"Fall","C":"Stay the same","D":"Become more volatile but move randomly"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bond prices and interest rates have an inverse relationship. When interest rates rise, newly issued bonds offer higher yields, making existing bonds with lower coupon rates less attractive. Their prices must fall until their effective yields are competitive with new issues. This inverse relationship is fundamental to fixed-income investing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["systematic-risk","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-008","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which bond would have the HIGHEST interest rate risk?","choices":{"A":"5-year Treasury note with 4% coupon","B":"30-year Treasury bond with 5% coupon","C":"2-year corporate bond with 6% coupon","D":"10-year municipal bond with 3% coupon"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The 30-year Treasury bond has the highest interest rate risk because it has the longest maturity. Longer-term bonds are more sensitive to interest rate changes because investors are locked into a rate for more years. The coupon rate is a secondary factor - among these choices, the 30-year maturity dominates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-009","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Reinvestment risk is HIGHEST when:","choices":{"A":"Interest rates are rising","B":"Interest rates are falling","C":"Interest rates are stable","D":"A bond is trading at a discount"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Reinvestment risk is highest when interest rates are falling because income received from investments (coupon payments, maturing bonds) must be reinvested at lower rates than previously available. This is the opposite of interest rate risk - when prices rise (rates fall), reinvestment risk increases.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-010","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which investment provides the BEST protection against inflation risk?","choices":{"A":"Long-term corporate bonds","B":"Money market funds","C":"Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS)","D":"Certificates of deposit (CDs)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"TIPS are specifically designed to protect against inflation. Their principal adjusts based on the Consumer Price Index (CPI), so as prices rise, the TIPS principal and interest payments increase. Long-term corporate bonds, money market funds, and CDs all pay fixed amounts that lose purchasing power as inflation rises.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-011","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A U.S. investor owns European stocks. If the euro weakens against the dollar, the investor's dollar returns will:","choices":{"A":"Increase due to currency gains","B":"Decrease due to currency losses","C":"Not be affected by currency movements","D":"Only decrease if the stocks also decline"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the euro weakens against the dollar, European investments are worth fewer dollars when converted back to the investor's home currency. Even if the underlying European stocks gain in euro terms, the U.S. investor may experience lower or negative returns due to currency losses.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-012","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor earns a 6% return on a bond portfolio while inflation is 2.5%. The investor's real return is approximately:","choices":{"A":"2.5%","B":"3.5%","C":"6%","D":"8.5%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Real return equals nominal return minus inflation: 6% - 2.5% = 3.5%. The real return represents the actual increase in purchasing power. While the investor earned 6% nominally, only 3.5% represents true wealth accumulation after accounting for rising prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-013","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which investment would typically have the HIGHEST liquidity risk?","choices":{"A":"S&P 500 ETF","B":"Treasury bills","C":"Private equity fund","D":"Money market fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Private equity funds have the highest liquidity risk because they have lock-up periods (often 7-10 years), no active secondary market, and investors cannot easily exit their positions. S&P 500 ETFs, Treasury bills, and money market funds are all highly liquid with active markets and easy redemption.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-014","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Opportunity cost in investing refers to:","choices":{"A":"The commission paid to buy a security","B":"The potential returns given up by choosing one investment over another","C":"The risk that an investment will lose value","D":"The cost of borrowing money to invest"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Opportunity cost is the potential benefit or return that is lost when choosing one investment alternative over another. It represents the \"cost\" of the path not taken. For example, if you hold cash earning 2% while stocks return 10%, your opportunity cost is 8%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-015","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor demands higher expected returns from illiquid investments. This additional return is called:","choices":{"A":"Market premium","B":"Liquidity premium","C":"Risk-free rate","D":"Opportunity cost"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The liquidity premium is the additional return investors require to compensate for holding illiquid investments. Since illiquid investments tie up capital and may be difficult to sell at fair prices, investors demand higher returns compared to similar but more liquid investments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-016","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Standard deviation measures:","choices":{"A":"Systematic risk only","B":"Unsystematic risk only","C":"Total risk (systematic plus unsystematic)","D":"Manager performance relative to benchmark"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Standard deviation measures total risk, which includes both systematic (market) risk and unsystematic (company-specific) risk. It shows how much returns vary from the average. Beta measures only systematic risk, while alpha measures manager performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-017","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A positive alpha indicates that:","choices":{"A":"The investment has more systematic risk than the market","B":"The investment is more volatile than expected","C":"The manager has added value by outperforming expectations","D":"The investment has negative correlation with the market"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Alpha measures the difference between actual returns and expected returns given the level of risk (beta). A positive alpha means the investment outperformed what CAPM predicted based on its systematic risk - the manager added value through security selection or market timing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch3-018","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"According to Modern Portfolio Theory, diversification benefits are GREATEST when portfolio assets have:","choices":{"A":"High positive correlation","B":"Zero correlation","C":"Negative correlation","D":"Beta greater than 1.0"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Diversification benefits are greatest when assets have negative correlation - when one zigs, the other zags. Negative correlation means assets move in opposite directions, providing maximum risk reduction. Zero correlation provides good diversification, positive correlation provides less benefit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-001","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Treasury bills differ from other money market instruments because they:","choices":{"A":"Pay interest semi-annually","B":"Are sold at a discount and mature at par value","C":"Have maturities of 10-30 years","D":"Are issued by corporations"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Treasury bills are sold at a discount to face value and mature at par. The difference between purchase price and par value represents the investor's return. Unlike notes and bonds, T-bills do not pay periodic interest payments. They are issued by the U.S. Treasury, not corporations, and have short-term maturities (4-52 weeks).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-002","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Commercial paper is:","choices":{"A":"Long-term secured corporate bonds","B":"Short-term unsecured corporate debt","C":"Government-issued securities","D":"Bank certificates of deposit"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Commercial paper is short-term unsecured promissory notes issued by corporations to meet working capital needs. Maturities range from 1 to 270 days (most commonly 30-90 days). It is unsecured, meaning it is backed only by the issuing corporation's creditworthiness, not by collateral.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-003","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Money market mutual funds:","choices":{"A":"Are insured by the FDIC up to $250,000","B":"Always maintain a $1.00 NAV by law","C":"Are NOT FDIC insured but seek to maintain a $1.00 NAV","D":"Invest primarily in long-term bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Money market funds are NOT insured by the FDIC. They seek to maintain a stable $1.00 per share NAV but are not legally required to do so. In rare cases, a fund may \"break the buck\" (fall below $1.00). They invest in short-term money market instruments, not long-term bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Interest on U.S. Treasury securities is:","choices":{"A":"Exempt from all taxes","B":"Subject to federal tax only, exempt from state and local taxes","C":"Subject to state tax only, exempt from federal tax","D":"Subject to both federal and state taxes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Interest on U.S. Treasury securities is subject to federal income tax but exempt from state and local income taxes. This tax advantage makes Treasuries particularly attractive for investors in high-tax states like California and New York.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-005","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which Treasury security provides protection against inflation?","choices":{"A":"Treasury bills","B":"Treasury notes","C":"Treasury STRIPS","D":"Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS)"},"answer":"D","explanation":"TIPS (Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities) provide direct inflation protection because their principal adjusts based on changes in the Consumer Price Index (CPI). As inflation rises, the principal increases, and interest is paid on the adjusted principal. At maturity, investors receive the greater of the adjusted or original principal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Treasury STRIPS have which combination of interest rate risk and reinvestment risk?","choices":{"A":"Low interest rate risk, high reinvestment risk","B":"High interest rate risk, high reinvestment risk","C":"Maximum interest rate risk, zero reinvestment risk","D":"Zero interest rate risk, maximum reinvestment risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"STRIPS are zero-coupon bonds with maximum interest rate risk (duration equals maturity) because all cash flow occurs at maturity. However, they have zero reinvestment risk since there are no interim payments to reinvest. A 20-year STRIP has a duration of 20 years - meaning approximately 20% price change for each 1% rate change.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["government-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which agency's securities are backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government?","choices":{"A":"Fannie Mae (FNMA)","B":"Freddie Mac (FHLMC)","C":"Ginnie Mae (GNMA)","D":"Federal Home Loan Banks (FHLB)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ginnie Mae (Government National Mortgage Association) is the only mortgage-related agency whose securities are fully backed by the U.S. government. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac are government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) with implied but not explicit government guarantees. They were placed in conservatorship in 2008.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Prepayment risk is HIGHEST when:","choices":{"A":"Interest rates are rising","B":"Interest rates are falling","C":"Interest rates are stable","D":"The economy is in recession"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Prepayment risk is highest when interest rates are falling because homeowners refinance their mortgages to take advantage of lower rates. This returns principal to MBS investors sooner than expected, forcing them to reinvest at lower rates. This is similar to call risk on callable bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Collateralized Mortgage Obligations (CMOs) are designed to:","choices":{"A":"Eliminate prepayment risk entirely","B":"Redistribute prepayment risk among different tranches","C":"Provide higher yields than Treasury securities","D":"Guarantee principal repayment by the government"},"answer":"B","explanation":"CMOs do not eliminate prepayment risk - they redistribute it among different tranches. Some tranches (like PAC tranches) have more predictable cash flows, while others (like companion tranches) absorb prepayment variability and have higher uncertainty. This allows investors to select tranches matching their risk preferences.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-011","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A callable bond primarily benefits:","choices":{"A":"The bondholder because they receive a call premium","B":"The issuer because they can refinance at lower rates","C":"Both parties equally","D":"Neither party - it's a neutral feature"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A callable bond primarily benefits the issuer because they can call (redeem) the bonds and refinance at lower interest rates when rates decline. This limits the bondholder's potential gains and creates reinvestment risk - the investor must reinvest at lower rates. While a call premium may be paid, this doesn't offset the loss of the higher-yielding investment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-012","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following represents the cutoff between investment grade and high-yield (junk) bonds?","choices":{"A":"AAA/Aaa","B":"A/A2","C":"BBB-/Baa3","D":"BB+/Ba1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"BBB-/Baa3 is the lowest investment-grade rating. Anything below (BB+/Ba1 and lower) is considered high-yield or \"junk\" bonds. Many institutional investors are restricted to investment-grade securities only, making the BBB-/Baa3 level a critical threshold.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-013","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"The interest on municipal bonds is generally:","choices":{"A":"Subject to federal income tax only","B":"Subject to state income tax only","C":"Exempt from federal income tax","D":"Subject to both federal and state taxes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Municipal bond interest is generally exempt from federal income tax. This tax advantage makes munis particularly attractive for investors in higher tax brackets. Additionally, if the bond was issued in the investor's state of residence, the interest may also be exempt from state and local taxes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-014","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor in the 35% tax bracket is considering a municipal bond yielding 4%. What is the tax-equivalent yield?","choices":{"A":"4.00%","B":"5.25%","C":"6.15%","D":"7.00%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax-equivalent yield = Municipal yield / (1 - tax rate) = 4% / (1 - 0.35) = 4% / 0.65 = 6.15%. This means a taxable bond would need to yield 6.15% to provide the same after-tax return as a 4% municipal bond for an investor in the 35% tax bracket.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-015","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"General obligation bonds are backed by:","choices":{"A":"Revenue from a specific project","B":"The full faith, credit, and taxing power of the issuer","C":"Federal government guarantees","D":"Corporate parent company guarantees"},"answer":"B","explanation":"General obligation (GO) bonds are backed by the full faith, credit, and taxing power of the issuing municipality. The issuer can raise taxes to pay bondholders. Revenue bonds, in contrast, are backed only by revenues from a specific project and carry no taxing authority behind them.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-016","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond with a 5% coupon trading at a discount will have:","choices":{"A":"Current yield lower than 5%","B":"Yield to maturity lower than current yield","C":"Yield to maturity higher than current yield","D":"All yields equal to 5%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a discount bond, the yield relationships are: Nominal yield < Current yield < Yield to maturity. The YTM is highest because it includes the capital gain from the discount (buying below par and receiving par at maturity) in addition to coupon income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-017","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"If a bond has a duration of 7 years and interest rates rise by 1%, the bond's price will approximately:","choices":{"A":"Rise by 7%","B":"Fall by 7%","C":"Rise by 1%","D":"Fall by 1%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Duration approximates the percentage price change for a 1% change in interest rates. With a duration of 7 years, a 1% rate increase would cause approximately a 7% price decline. The inverse relationship means rising rates cause falling prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch4-018","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which bond would have the HIGHEST duration?","choices":{"A":"10-year bond with 8% coupon","B":"10-year bond with 4% coupon","C":"5-year bond with 4% coupon","D":"5-year bond with 8% coupon"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Duration is highest for bonds with longer maturities and lower coupons. The 10-year bond with 4% coupon has both the longest maturity and lowest coupon among the choices, giving it the highest duration and greatest sensitivity to interest rate changes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-001","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Cumulative voting most benefits:","choices":{"A":"The company's management","B":"Majority shareholders","C":"Minority shareholders","D":"The board of directors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Cumulative voting allows shareholders to concentrate all their votes on fewer candidates, which benefits minority shareholders by giving them a better chance of electing at least one director. Under statutory voting, minority shareholders have virtually no chance of electing any directors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-002","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"In a 3-for-1 stock split, an investor holding 100 shares at $60 per share would have:","choices":{"A":"100 shares at $180 per share","B":"300 shares at $60 per share","C":"300 shares at $20 per share","D":"33 shares at $180 per share"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a 3-for-1 forward split, the number of shares triples (100 x 3 = 300) and the price per share is divided by 3 ($60 / 3 = $20). Total value remains unchanged at $6,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-003","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor purchases stock on Wednesday. The ex-dividend date is Thursday. Will the investor receive the upcoming dividend?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because settlement occurs before the record date","B":"Yes, because purchases on the ex-date qualify for dividends","C":"No, because the stock was purchased after the declaration date","D":"No, because ex-dividend purchases do not qualify for dividends"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The investor purchased the stock on Wednesday, one day BEFORE the ex-dividend date (Thursday). With T+1 settlement, the trade will settle on Thursday, which is the ex-date. However, since the purchase was made before the ex-date, the investor is entitled to receive the dividend.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-004","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"What is the primary advantage of cumulative preferred stock over non-cumulative preferred stock for investors?","choices":{"A":"Higher dividend rate","B":"Voting rights on major corporate decisions","C":"Unpaid dividends accumulate and must be paid before common dividends","D":"Priority over bonds in corporate liquidation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Cumulative preferred stock accumulates any unpaid dividends as \"dividends in arrears,\" which must be paid in full before any dividends can be paid to common stockholders. Non-cumulative preferred forfeits missed dividends, making it riskier for investors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-005","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A corporation would most likely call its preferred stock when:","choices":{"A":"Interest rates have increased significantly","B":"Interest rates have decreased significantly","C":"The common stock price has increased","D":"The company's credit rating has been downgraded"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Corporations call preferred stock when interest rates decline. By calling high-rate preferred and issuing new preferred at lower rates, the company reduces its dividend expense. When rates rise, there's no incentive to call - the existing preferred has an attractive (low) rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-006","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Convertible preferred stock typically has a lower dividend rate than non-convertible preferred because:","choices":{"A":"It has lower credit quality","B":"The conversion feature adds value to the security","C":"It has no liquidation preference","D":"It cannot accumulate dividends in arrears"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Convertible preferred offers the valuable option to convert to common stock, providing upside potential if the common stock appreciates. Investors accept a lower dividend in exchange for this conversion privilege. The conversion feature is an embedded option with economic value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-007","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"In a corporate liquidation, common stockholders:","choices":{"A":"Are paid first as owners of the company","B":"Are paid after secured creditors but before bondholders","C":"Are paid after all creditors and preferred stockholders","D":"Have no claim on any corporate assets"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Common stockholders have a residual claim and are paid last in liquidation - after secured creditors, unsecured creditors, subordinated debt holders, and preferred stockholders. In many bankruptcies, common shareholders receive nothing because assets are exhausted paying higher-priority claims.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-008","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Preemptive rights allow shareholders to:","choices":{"A":"Force the company to repurchase their shares at fair value","B":"Purchase additional shares before the public to maintain their ownership percentage","C":"Receive dividends before other shareholders","D":"Vote on all matters affecting the company"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Preemptive rights give existing shareholders the first opportunity to purchase new shares in proportion to their current holdings. This prevents dilution of their ownership percentage when the company issues additional shares.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["rights-warrants"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-009","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following matters do common shareholders typically NOT vote on?","choices":{"A":"Election of the board of directors","B":"Declaration and amount of dividends","C":"Approval of a merger with another company","D":"Authorization of additional shares of stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Common shareholders do not vote on dividend declarations - that is the responsibility of the board of directors. Shareholders vote on director elections, major corporate changes like mergers, and authorizing additional shares, but dividend policy is determined by the board.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-010","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"The dividend discount model (DDM) is most appropriate for valuing:","choices":{"A":"High-growth technology companies that don't pay dividends","B":"Mature companies that pay stable, growing dividends","C":"Distressed companies with negative earnings","D":"Start-up companies with unpredictable cash flows"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The DDM is best suited for mature, stable companies that pay consistent and growing dividends, such as utilities and blue-chip stocks. It cannot be used for companies that don't pay dividends, have erratic dividend policies, or negative earnings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-011","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company has a stock price of $50, EPS of $2.50, and expected earnings growth of 10%. What is the PEG ratio?","choices":{"A":"0.5","B":"2.0","C":"5.0","D":"20.0"},"answer":"B","explanation":"First calculate P/E: $50 / $2.50 = 20. Then PEG = P/E / Growth Rate = 20 / 10 = 2.0. A PEG of 2.0 suggests the stock may be fully valued or overvalued relative to its growth rate, since a PEG above 1.0 indicates the price may be high for the expected growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-012","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Using the Gordon Growth Model, what is the value of a stock that currently pays a $3.00 dividend, has a required return of 11%, and an expected growth rate of 5%?","choices":{"A":"$30.00","B":"$50.00","C":"$52.50","D":"$60.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Gordon Growth Model formula is: Value = D1 / (r - g). First, find D1 = $3.00 x 1.05 = $3.15. Then: Value = $3.15 / (0.11 - 0.05) = $3.15 / 0.06 = $52.50. The model uses next year's expected dividend (D1), not the current dividend.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-013","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor holding ADRs of a German company would be exposed to:","choices":{"A":"Only U.S. market risk since ADRs trade in dollars","B":"Only German market risk since the underlying shares are German","C":"Both German market risk and currency exchange risk","D":"Neither U.S. nor German market risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ADR investors face both the risk of the underlying foreign stock (German market risk) and currency risk. If the euro weakens against the dollar, the ADR value decreases even if the German stock price remains unchanged. ADRs do not eliminate foreign exposure - they simply make it easier to access.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-014","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"To qualify as a REIT, a company must distribute what percentage of taxable income to shareholders annually?","choices":{"A":"At least 50%","B":"At least 75%","C":"At least 90%","D":"Exactly 100%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"REITs must distribute at least 90% of their taxable income to shareholders as dividends. This requirement is the primary reason REITs offer high dividend yields but also limits retained earnings for growth, often requiring external financing for expansion.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch5-015","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Warrants differ from stock rights in that warrants typically:","choices":{"A":"Have shorter expiration periods and are priced below market","B":"Have longer terms and exercise prices set above the current market price","C":"Are issued only to protect shareholders from dilution","D":"Can only be exercised on the expiration date"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Warrants are long-term instruments (often years) with exercise prices typically set above the current market price when issued. Rights are short-term (weeks), issued to existing shareholders at prices below market to prevent dilution. Warrants are more speculative due to their leverage and time value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["rights-warrants"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-001","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"The Net Asset Value (NAV) of a mutual fund is calculated:","choices":{"A":"Continuously throughout the trading day","B":"Once daily after the market closes","C":"Once weekly on Fridays","D":"Only when shares are redeemed"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mutual fund NAV is calculated at least once daily after the market closes (4:00 PM ET). All buy and sell orders for that day are executed at that day's closing NAV. This is called \"forward pricing.\"","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-002","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor places an order to purchase mutual fund shares at 2:30 PM Eastern Time. At what price will the shares be purchased?","choices":{"A":"The NAV at the time the order was placed","B":"The NAV at the previous day's close","C":"The NAV calculated at 4:00 PM that day","D":"The average of the day's high and low NAV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Since the order was placed before 4:00 PM ET, it will be executed at that day's closing NAV (forward pricing). If the order had been placed after 4:00 PM, it would receive the next day's NAV.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-003","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which type of mutual fund uses passive management and typically has the lowest expense ratio?","choices":{"A":"Growth fund","B":"Sector fund","C":"Index fund","D":"Balanced fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Index funds use passive management to replicate a benchmark index rather than actively selecting securities. Because they don't require active portfolio managers and analysts, they have much lower expense ratios than actively managed funds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-004","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A mutual fund with a 12b-1 fee of 0.50% can describe itself as:","choices":{"A":"A no-load fund","B":"A low-load fund","C":"Neither no-load nor low-load","D":"A pure no-load fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A fund may not call itself \"no-load\" if its 12b-1 fees exceed 0.25%. With a 0.50% 12b-1 fee, this fund cannot accurately describe itself as either no-load or pure no-load.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-005","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor with $90,000 to invest notices that a $100,000 breakpoint would reduce the sales charge from 4.5% to 4.0%. A registered representative should:","choices":{"A":"Process the $90,000 investment at the 4.5% load","B":"Recommend investing only $50,000 to reduce risk","C":"Inform the investor about the Letter of Intent option","D":"Suggest a Class C share purchase instead"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The representative should inform the investor about a Letter of Intent (LOI), which allows the customer to receive the lower 4.0% breakpoint if they commit to investing $100,000 within 13 months. Failing to disclose breakpoint opportunities is a sales practice violation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-006","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"12b-1 fees are used primarily to pay for:","choices":{"A":"Portfolio management and research","B":"Distribution, marketing, and shareholder services","C":"Custodial services and safekeeping of assets","D":"Legal compliance and regulatory filings"},"answer":"B","explanation":"12b-1 fees (named after SEC Rule 12b-1) cover distribution costs (marketing, advertising, broker compensation) and service fees (ongoing shareholder services). Management fees separately compensate the investment adviser for portfolio management.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-007","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Unlike mutual funds, ETFs:","choices":{"A":"Are valued once daily at NAV","B":"Cannot be sold short","C":"Trade on exchanges throughout the day at market prices","D":"Must distribute capital gains annually"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ETFs trade on exchanges throughout the day at market prices, while mutual funds are priced once daily at NAV. ETFs can also be sold short and traded using limit orders, stop orders, and other order types not available for mutual funds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-008","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"The primary reason ETFs are generally more tax-efficient than mutual funds is:","choices":{"A":"ETFs pay no dividends to shareholders","B":"ETFs are exempt from capital gains taxes","C":"The in-kind creation/redemption process avoids triggering capital gains","D":"ETFs only invest in tax-free municipal bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ETFs use an in-kind creation/redemption process where Authorized Participants exchange baskets of securities (not cash) with the fund. Since no securities are sold, no capital gains are triggered, unlike mutual funds that must sell securities to meet redemptions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-009","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Leveraged ETFs that provide 2x or 3x daily returns are:","choices":{"A":"Suitable for long-term buy-and-hold investors seeking enhanced returns","B":"Designed for short-term trading due to daily reset and compounding effects","C":"Required to be held for at least one year","D":"Less risky than standard index ETFs"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Leveraged ETFs reset daily, which causes compounding effects that can lead to significant deviation from expected returns over time. They are designed for short-term trading and sophisticated investors, not long-term holding or retirement accounts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-010","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A closed-end fund with a NAV of $25.00 is trading at $22.50. This fund is trading at a:","choices":{"A":"10% premium","B":"10% discount","C":"11.1% premium","D":"11.1% discount"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Discount = (Price - NAV) / NAV = ($22.50 - $25.00) / $25.00 = -$2.50 / $25.00 = -10%. A negative percentage indicates the fund trades at a 10% discount to NAV - investors can buy $1 of assets for $0.90.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["closed-end-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-011","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Unit Investment Trusts (UITs) differ from mutual funds primarily because UITs:","choices":{"A":"Are actively managed by portfolio managers","B":"Have a fixed, unmanaged portfolio with a set termination date","C":"Trade on exchanges throughout the day","D":"Can issue an unlimited number of shares"},"answer":"B","explanation":"UITs hold a fixed portfolio that is not actively managed and have a predetermined termination date when assets are liquidated and proceeds distributed. Mutual funds are typically perpetual with actively managed portfolios that change over time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uits"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-012","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A common feature of closed-end funds that is NOT typically found in open-end mutual funds is:","choices":{"A":"Professional portfolio management","B":"Daily NAV calculation","C":"Significant use of leverage","D":"Diversification across multiple securities"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Closed-end funds commonly use leverage (borrowing or issuing preferred shares) to enhance returns, while open-end mutual funds have strict limits on leverage under the Investment Company Act of 1940. Both types have professional management, daily NAV calculations, and diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["closed-end-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-013","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"The typical hedge fund fee structure of \"2 and 20\" refers to:","choices":{"A":"2% front-end load and 20% back-end load","B":"2% annual management fee and 20% of profits as performance fee","C":"2% expense ratio and 20% distribution fee","D":"2% redemption fee and 20% early withdrawal penalty"},"answer":"B","explanation":"\"2 and 20\" is the traditional hedge fund fee structure: 2% annual management fee on total assets under management plus 20% of profits (performance fee or incentive fee). The management fee is charged regardless of performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-014","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is a requirement to qualify as an accredited investor?","choices":{"A":"Net worth of $500,000 including primary residence","B":"Annual income of $150,000 for the past two years","C":"Net worth exceeding $1 million excluding primary residence","D":"Minimum investment of $100,000 in private placements"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Accredited investor status requires either: (1) net worth exceeding $1 million excluding primary residence, (2) income exceeding $200,000 individually ($300,000 jointly) for the past two years, or (3) holding certain professional licenses (Series 7, 65, or 82) in good standing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch6-015","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Venture capital investments are characterized by:","choices":{"A":"High liquidity and short time horizons","B":"Investment in early-stage companies with long time horizons of 7-10 years","C":"Guaranteed returns with low risk","D":"Daily pricing and redemption like mutual funds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Venture capital involves investing in early-stage companies (startups) with high risk and potentially high returns. Investments are highly illiquid with time horizons of 7-10 years. Most venture investments fail, but successful ones can generate exceptional returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-001","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a call option with a strike price of $45 for a $3 premium. The stock is currently trading at $48. What is the intrinsic value of this option?","choices":{"A":"$0","B":"$3","C":"$3 (same as premium)","D":"$6"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a call option, intrinsic value = Stock Price - Strike Price. Here: $48 - $45 = $3. The option is in the money by $3. The remaining premium above intrinsic value would be time value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-002","section":"Options","stem":"Which of the following describes the maximum loss for a buyer of a put option?","choices":{"A":"Unlimited","B":"Strike price minus premium","C":"The premium paid","D":"Strike price"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The maximum loss for any option buyer (call or put) is limited to the premium paid. If the option expires worthless, the buyer loses the entire premium but nothing more. This defined risk is a key advantage of buying options.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["put-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-003","section":"Options","stem":"A put option with a strike price of $70 when the stock is trading at $65 is:","choices":{"A":"Out of the money by $5","B":"At the money","C":"In the money by $5","D":"In the money by $70"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A put option is in the money when the stock price is BELOW the strike price. Here, the put holder can sell stock worth $65 for $70, a $5 benefit. Remember: \"Put Down\" - puts profit when the stock price goes down below the strike.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["put-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-004","section":"Options","stem":"A covered call strategy involves:","choices":{"A":"Buying a call option without owning the underlying stock","B":"Owning stock and selling a call option against it","C":"Buying both a call and put option on the same stock","D":"Selling stock short and buying a call option"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A covered call means owning the underlying stock and selling (writing) a call option against those shares. The call is \"covered\" because the writer already owns the stock to deliver if the option is exercised. This strategy generates income but caps upside potential.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-005","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a call option with a strike price of $55 for a $4 premium. What is the break-even point for this investment?","choices":{"A":"$51","B":"$55","C":"$59","D":"$63"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a long call, break-even = Strike Price + Premium Paid = $55 + $4 = $59. The stock must rise above $59 for the investor to profit. At exactly $59, the investor would break even (exercise value equals premium paid).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-006","section":"Options","stem":"An investor expecting a stock to make a large move in either direction before earnings would most likely use which strategy?","choices":{"A":"Covered call","B":"Protective put","C":"Long straddle","D":"Bull call spread"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A long straddle (buying both a call and put at the same strike) profits from significant price movement in either direction. It's ideal when expecting volatility but uncertain about direction. The trade-off is paying premiums for both options.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-007","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"The \"2 and 20\" fee structure commonly associated with hedge funds refers to:","choices":{"A":"2% front-end load and 20% back-end load","B":"2% annual management fee and 20% of profits as performance fee","C":"2% redemption fee and 20% early withdrawal penalty","D":"2% expense ratio and 20% distribution fee"},"answer":"B","explanation":"\"2 and 20\" is the traditional hedge fund fee structure: 2% annual management fee on assets under management plus 20% of profits (performance/incentive fee). The management fee is charged regardless of performance, while the performance fee rewards the manager for positive returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-008","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Long-term capital gains on collectibles such as art and rare coins are taxed at a maximum rate of:","choices":{"A":"15%","B":"20%","C":"28%","D":"37%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Collectibles are subject to a maximum long-term capital gains tax rate of 28%, which is higher than the 20% maximum rate for most other capital assets like stocks. This higher rate applies to art, antiques, coins, stamps, and similar collectible items.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-009","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which characteristic is common to most alternative investments?","choices":{"A":"High liquidity and daily pricing","B":"Low fees and transparent structures","C":"Limited liquidity and lower correlation with traditional assets","D":"Full SEC registration and disclosure requirements"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Alternative investments typically feature limited liquidity (lock-up periods, infrequent redemptions) and lower correlation with traditional stocks and bonds. They often have higher fees, less transparency, and many are exempt from full SEC registration requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-011","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor withdraws $20,000 from a non-qualified variable annuity. The account has $50,000 in contributions and $30,000 in earnings. How much of the withdrawal is taxable?","choices":{"A":"$0 - withdrawals are tax-free","B":"$10,000","C":"$20,000","D":"$12,500"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Non-qualified annuity withdrawals are taxed using LIFO (Last In, First Out), meaning earnings are considered withdrawn first. Since the annuity has $30,000 in earnings and the withdrawal is $20,000, the entire $20,000 is taxable as ordinary income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-012","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which of the following is NOT a typical fee associated with variable annuities?","choices":{"A":"Mortality and expense (M&E) charge","B":"Surrender charges for early withdrawal","C":"12b-1 distribution fees","D":"Subaccount management fees"},"answer":"C","explanation":"12b-1 fees are specific to mutual funds, not annuities. Variable annuity fees include mortality & expense (M&E) charges, administrative fees, subaccount expenses, optional rider fees, and surrender charges for early withdrawals.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-013","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which type of life insurance is considered a security?","choices":{"A":"Term life insurance","B":"Whole life insurance","C":"Universal life insurance","D":"Variable universal life insurance"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Variable universal life (VUL) and variable life insurance are securities because the policyholder bears the investment risk - cash value is invested in subaccounts that fluctuate with market performance. Term, whole, and universal life are not securities because the insurance company bears the investment risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-014","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Life insurance death benefits received by a named beneficiary are generally:","choices":{"A":"Taxable as ordinary income","B":"Taxable as capital gains","C":"Received income tax-free","D":"Subject to a 10% early withdrawal penalty"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Life insurance death benefits paid to named beneficiaries are generally received income tax-free. However, they may be included in the deceased's gross estate for estate tax purposes if the deceased owned the policy or had incidents of ownership.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch7-015","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Variable life insurance cash value is held in a separate account rather than the general account because:","choices":{"A":"It reduces the insurance company's administrative costs","B":"It provides higher guaranteed returns to the policyholder","C":"It protects the policyholder's assets from the insurer's creditors","D":"It allows the insurance company to invest more aggressively"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The separate account segregates variable product assets from the insurance company's general assets. This protects policyholders from claims of the insurer's creditors if the company faces financial difficulties. General account assets (used for fixed products) are subject to creditor claims.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-001","section":"Suitability","stem":"A 30-year-old investor has a high income, significant savings, and a 35-year time horizon until retirement, but becomes very anxious when her portfolio drops even 5%. When recommending investments, the adviser should primarily consider:","choices":{"A":"Only the client's long time horizon","B":"Only the client's high income","C":"The client's risk tolerance, which is lower than her risk capacity","D":"The client's age, which suggests aggressive investing"},"answer":"C","explanation":"While the client has high risk capacity (long time horizon, stable income, significant savings), her risk tolerance is low (anxious about small drops). Advisers should use the LOWER of tolerance or capacity, meaning her conservative risk tolerance should guide recommendations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-002","section":"Suitability","stem":"An investor in the consolidation phase of their financial life cycle (ages 45-60) would typically:","choices":{"A":"Focus exclusively on speculation for maximum returns","B":"Have a balanced approach with a gradual shift toward income","C":"Invest entirely in fixed-income securities","D":"Have the highest risk capacity of any life stage"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The consolidation phase represents peak earning years with a moderate but shortening time horizon. A balanced approach that begins shifting toward income is appropriate, not the extremes of all-growth or all-income strategies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-003","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following is a component of a client's FINANCIAL profile rather than their PERSONAL profile?","choices":{"A":"Marital status","B":"Employment status","C":"Tax bracket","D":"Number of dependents"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax bracket is a financial profile component (along with income, net worth, cash flow). Marital status, employment status, and number of dependents are personal/demographic factors that influence financial planning but are not themselves financial metrics.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which business entity provides limited liability protection for ALL owners while also offering pass-through taxation?","choices":{"A":"General Partnership","B":"C Corporation","C":"Limited Liability Company (LLC)","D":"Limited Partnership"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An LLC provides limited liability for ALL members while typically offering pass-through taxation. General partnerships have no limited liability; C-Corps have double taxation; Limited Partnerships only provide limited liability to limited partners, not general partners.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An S Corporation differs from a C Corporation primarily in that an S Corporation:","choices":{"A":"Does not provide limited liability to shareholders","B":"Has pass-through taxation, avoiding double taxation","C":"Can have unlimited shareholders","D":"Can issue multiple classes of stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The primary advantage of S-Corp status is pass-through taxation, avoiding the double taxation of C-Corps. S-Corps maintain limited liability like C-Corps but have restrictions: maximum 100 shareholders and only one class of stock.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"When investing a corporation's operating cash reserves, the investment adviser should prioritize:","choices":{"A":"Maximum growth potential regardless of risk","B":"Long-term capital appreciation","C":"Safety and liquidity above yield","D":"Tax-advantaged growth investments"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Operating cash reserves must be available when needed for business operations. Safety (protecting principal) and liquidity (quick access) are paramount. Yield is a secondary consideration. Suitable investments include money market funds, short-term Treasuries, and CDs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-007","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A revocable living trust provides which of the following benefits during the grantor's lifetime?","choices":{"A":"Immediate reduction in estate taxes","B":"Removal of assets from the grantor's taxable estate","C":"Avoidance of probate at death","D":"Protection from the grantor's creditors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A revocable living trust's primary benefit is probate avoidance - assets pass to beneficiaries without going through probate court. It provides NO estate tax reduction during the grantor's lifetime because the assets are still considered part of the grantor's estate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the Uniform Prudent Investor Act (UPIA), a trustee's investment decisions are evaluated:","choices":{"A":"Based on each individual investment's performance","B":"By the performance of the portfolio as a whole","C":"Only by whether the investments were conservative","D":"Based on hindsight after seeing actual results"},"answer":"B","explanation":"UPIA revolutionized trust investing by requiring evaluation of the portfolio as a whole, not individual investments. A single investment that declines is acceptable if it fits the overall portfolio strategy. Prudence is also judged at the time of decision, not by hindsight.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A trustee's duty of impartiality requires the trustee to:","choices":{"A":"Invest only in bonds to protect principal","B":"Balance the interests of income beneficiaries and remainder beneficiaries","C":"Distribute all income immediately to current beneficiaries","D":"Favor the grantor's designated favorite beneficiary"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The duty of impartiality requires trustees to balance the interests of both income beneficiaries (who want current income) and remainder beneficiaries (who want principal growth). Neither group should be favored at the expense of the other.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"To qualify as an accredited investor under the net worth test, an individual must have:","choices":{"A":"Net worth over $1 million including primary residence","B":"Net worth over $1 million excluding primary residence","C":"Net worth over $2 million excluding primary residence","D":"Net worth over $5 million in investments"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An accredited investor under the net worth test must have net worth exceeding $1 million, EXCLUDING the value of their primary residence. The $2.7 million net-worth threshold is for qualified clients; $5 million in investments is for qualified purchasers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following automatically qualifies an individual as an accredited investor regardless of income or net worth?","choices":{"A":"Having a college degree in finance","B":"Working in the securities industry for 5+ years","C":"Holding a Series 65 license in good standing","D":"Being a client of a registered investment adviser"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Since 2020, holders of Series 7, Series 65, or Series 82 licenses in good standing automatically qualify as accredited investors based on demonstrated financial sophistication, regardless of their income or net worth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-012","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The primary difference between an accredited investor and a qualified purchaser is:","choices":{"A":"Qualified purchasers have more regulatory protection","B":"Accredited investors can invest in 3(c)(7) funds","C":"Qualified purchasers need $5 million in investments vs. $1 million net worth for accredited","D":"There is no meaningful difference between them"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A qualified purchaser must have $5 million or more in investments - a significantly higher bar than the $1 million net worth required for accredited investor status. Qualified purchasers can access 3(c)(7) funds with up to 2,000 investors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec","investment-company-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-013","section":"Suitability","stem":"The fiduciary standard differs from the suitability standard primarily because fiduciary duty:","choices":{"A":"Only applies to recommendations over $100,000","B":"Requires acting in the client's best interest on an ongoing basis","C":"Is a lower standard that only requires disclosure","D":"Only applies to institutional clients"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The fiduciary standard requires investment advisers to act in the client's BEST interest (not just make suitable recommendations) on an ONGOING basis (not just at the time of recommendation). It also requires putting client interests ahead of the adviser's own interests.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-014","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following represents a suitability RED FLAG that an investment adviser should address?","choices":{"A":"Recommending index funds to a long-term investor","B":"Suggesting bonds for a client seeking income","C":"Recommending illiquid private equity to a client who may need cash within 6 months","D":"Diversifying a client's portfolio across multiple asset classes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Recommending illiquid investments to a client with short-term liquidity needs is a major red flag. Private equity typically has a 7-10 year lock-up period. A client who may need cash in 6 months should not have assets in illiquid investments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch8-015","section":"Suitability","stem":"An investment adviser's duty of loyalty requires the adviser to:","choices":{"A":"Recommend only the highest-returning investments","B":"Put the client's interests ahead of the adviser's own interests","C":"Guarantee against investment losses","D":"Provide the lowest-cost investment options available"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The duty of loyalty, a core component of fiduciary duty, requires advisers to put client interests ahead of their own. This means eliminating or fully disclosing conflicts of interest and not letting personal financial interest influence recommendations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-001","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"According to Modern Portfolio Theory, which type of risk can be reduced through diversification?","choices":{"A":"Systematic risk","B":"Market risk","C":"Unsystematic (company-specific) risk","D":"Interest rate risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Unsystematic (company-specific) risk can be reduced or eliminated through diversification. Systematic risk (also called market risk) affects the entire market and cannot be diversified away. Interest rate risk is a form of systematic risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["unsystematic-risk","diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-002","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Two assets with a correlation coefficient of +0.3 would provide:","choices":{"A":"No diversification benefit","B":"Maximum diversification benefit","C":"Some diversification benefit since correlation is less than +1","D":"The same risk as holding just one asset"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Any correlation less than +1.0 provides some diversification benefit. While a correlation of +0.3 is positive (assets tend to move together), it is not perfect, so combining them will reduce overall portfolio volatility compared to holding either alone.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-003","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio that lies BELOW the efficient frontier is considered:","choices":{"A":"Optimal for conservative investors","B":"Inefficient - a better risk/return combination exists","C":"Impossible to construct","D":"The safest possible portfolio"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Portfolios below the efficient frontier are inefficient. This means there exists another portfolio that offers either higher return for the same risk OR lower risk for the same return. Rational investors should only hold portfolios ON the efficient frontier.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-004","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Using CAPM, if the risk-free rate is 3%, the expected market return is 11%, and a stock's beta is 1.5, the expected return is:","choices":{"A":"11%","B":"12%","C":"15%","D":"18%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Using CAPM: E(R) = 3% + 1.5 x (11% - 3%) = 3% + 1.5 x 8% = 3% + 12% = 15%. The market risk premium is 8% (11% - 3%), multiplied by beta of 1.5 equals 12%, plus the risk-free rate of 3%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-005","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A stock plotting ABOVE the Security Market Line (SML) is considered:","choices":{"A":"Overvalued and should be sold","B":"Undervalued and should be bought","C":"Fairly priced","D":"Risk-free"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A security above the SML offers a higher expected return than CAPM suggests for its level of risk - it is undervalued. Investors should buy undervalued securities. Securities below the SML are overvalued and should be sold.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-006","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The primary difference between the Security Market Line (SML) and Capital Market Line (CML) is that the SML:","choices":{"A":"Uses standard deviation as the risk measure","B":"Uses beta as the risk measure","C":"Only plots efficient portfolios","D":"Starts at the market return"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The SML uses beta (systematic risk) as its risk measure and can plot any security or portfolio. The CML uses standard deviation (total risk) and only plots efficient portfolios. Both lines start at the risk-free rate on the Y-axis.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-007","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"According to the semi-strong form of EMH, which type of analysis could potentially produce excess returns?","choices":{"A":"Technical analysis using chart patterns","B":"Fundamental analysis of financial statements","C":"Trading based on insider (non-public) information","D":"Neither technical nor fundamental analysis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Semi-strong EMH states that all publicly available information is already reflected in prices. Therefore, neither technical analysis (past prices) nor fundamental analysis (public information) can produce excess returns. Only non-public (insider) information could theoretically provide an edge under this form.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-008","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"If markets are efficient, an investor's best strategy would be:","choices":{"A":"Active stock selection based on thorough research","B":"Technical analysis to identify undervalued securities","C":"Passive index investing with low fees","D":"Concentrated investments in a few high-conviction stocks"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If markets are efficient, no amount of analysis can consistently beat the market. The logical strategy is passive index investing, which matches market returns while minimizing costs. Active management would just incur fees without adding value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-009","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"Which form of the Efficient Market Hypothesis is generally NOT supported by empirical evidence?","choices":{"A":"Weak form","B":"Semi-strong form","C":"Strong form","D":"All forms are fully supported"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The strong form of EMH claims that even insider information is reflected in prices. This is NOT supported by evidence - the existence of insider trading prosecutions and the fact that insiders earn abnormal returns proves that private information has value and is not fully reflected in prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-010","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A portfolio has a return of 15%, the risk-free rate is 3%, and the portfolio's standard deviation is 24%. What is the Sharpe ratio?","choices":{"A":"0.25","B":"0.50","C":"0.625","D":"1.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sharpe Ratio = (Portfolio Return - Risk-Free Rate) / Standard Deviation = (15% - 3%) / 24% = 12% / 24% = 0.50. The Sharpe ratio measures excess return per unit of total risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-011","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The Treynor ratio differs from the Sharpe ratio in that the Treynor ratio:","choices":{"A":"Uses standard deviation as the risk measure","B":"Uses beta as the risk measure","C":"Measures total risk","D":"Is best for undiversified portfolios"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Treynor ratio uses beta (systematic risk) in its denominator, while the Sharpe ratio uses standard deviation (total risk). Treynor is best for diversified portfolios where unsystematic risk has been eliminated; Sharpe is better for undiversified portfolios.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-012","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A positive alpha indicates that a portfolio manager:","choices":{"A":"Has taken on excessive risk","B":"Has underperformed expectations given the portfolio's risk level","C":"Has outperformed expectations given the portfolio's risk level","D":"Has perfectly matched the benchmark"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Alpha measures the difference between actual return and expected return (based on CAPM). A positive alpha indicates the manager generated returns above what was expected for the portfolio's level of systematic risk - evidence of skill or value added.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-013","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Strategic asset allocation differs from tactical asset allocation in that strategic allocation:","choices":{"A":"Involves frequent trading based on market conditions","B":"Is a long-term policy-based approach that maintains target allocations","C":"Attempts to time the market for additional returns","D":"Requires sophisticated market forecasting"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Strategic asset allocation is a long-term, policy-based approach that sets target allocations based on client risk tolerance, time horizon, and goals. Tactical allocation involves short-term deviations from strategic targets to capitalize on perceived market opportunities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-014","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The primary purpose of portfolio rebalancing is to:","choices":{"A":"Maximize short-term trading profits","B":"Maintain target asset allocation and control risk","C":"Minimize all taxes regardless of allocation","D":"Increase portfolio turnover"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Rebalancing returns a portfolio to its target allocation after market movements cause drift. This maintains the intended risk level and creates a disciplined \"buy low, sell high\" approach. It is NOT about maximizing profits or turnover.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch9-015","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Research suggests that approximately what percentage of portfolio return variability is explained by asset allocation policy?","choices":{"A":"30%","B":"50%","C":"70%","D":"90%"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The landmark Brinson, Hood, and Beebower study found that approximately 90% of portfolio return variability is explained by asset allocation policy, making it the most important investment decision. Security selection and market timing account for relatively small percentages.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-001","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock with a high P/E ratio, low dividend yield, and expected earnings growth of 20% per year would most likely be classified as a:","choices":{"A":"Value stock","B":"Growth stock","C":"Income stock","D":"Defensive stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Growth stocks are characterized by high P/E ratios (investors pay a premium for expected growth), low or no dividends (earnings are reinvested for growth), and above-average expected earnings growth. Value stocks have the opposite characteristics - low P/E and higher dividends.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-002","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Over a 15-year period, approximately what percentage of actively managed large-cap funds underperform the S&P 500 index?","choices":{"A":"50%","B":"65%","C":"75%","D":"90%"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Research consistently shows that approximately 85-90% of actively managed large-cap funds underperform the S&P 500 index over 15-year periods. This is a key argument for passive index investing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-003","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The primary advantage of passive index investing over active management is:","choices":{"A":"Higher potential returns in all market conditions","B":"Lower costs and greater tax efficiency","C":"Better performance in bear markets","D":"More flexibility to respond to market changes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Passive investing's main advantages are lower expense ratios (typically 0.03%-0.20% vs. 0.5%-1.5% for active) and greater tax efficiency (less trading means fewer taxable events). These cost savings compound significantly over time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds","etfs"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-004","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Dollar-cost averaging results in a lower average cost per share than the average market price because:","choices":{"A":"Transaction costs are eliminated","B":"More shares are purchased when prices are high","C":"More shares are purchased when prices are low","D":"It guarantees profits in all market conditions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"With DCA, a fixed dollar amount buys MORE shares when prices are low and FEWER shares when prices are high. This mathematical effect results in an average cost per share that is lower than the simple average of market prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-005","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Research shows that lump sum investing outperforms dollar-cost averaging approximately:","choices":{"A":"50% of the time","B":"66-75% of the time","C":"90% of the time","D":"100% of the time"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Historical research shows lump sum investing outperforms DCA about 66-75% of the time because markets generally rise over time, and lump sum investing puts money to work immediately. However, DCA reduces timing risk and may be psychologically easier.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-006","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The core-satellite investment approach combines:","choices":{"A":"Only growth and value stocks","B":"A passive index core with active satellite positions","C":"Only bonds of different maturities","D":"Exclusively international investments"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Core-satellite combines a passive core (typically 60-80% in low-cost index funds) with satellite positions (20-40%) using active strategies or specialized investments. This provides market exposure at low cost while allowing for active management opportunities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond ladder reduces interest rate risk by:","choices":{"A":"Investing all funds in short-term bonds","B":"Concentrating maturities at one date","C":"Staggering maturities so bonds mature at regular intervals","D":"Investing only in floating-rate bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A bond ladder staggers maturities evenly (e.g., bonds maturing each year for 10 years). This reduces interest rate risk because maturing bonds can be reinvested at current rates, smoothing out rate changes over time rather than being locked into a single rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"If an investor expects interest rates to rise, they should:","choices":{"A":"Extend portfolio duration","B":"Shorten portfolio duration","C":"Buy more long-term bonds","D":"Ignore duration entirely"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When interest rates rise, bond prices fall. Duration measures sensitivity to rate changes. Shortening duration (buying shorter-term bonds) reduces the portfolio's sensitivity to rate changes, limiting potential losses when rates increase.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bullet strategy is most appropriate for an investor who:","choices":{"A":"Wants maximum liquidity at all times","B":"Has a specific future cash need, such as a college tuition payment","C":"Expects interest rates to be highly volatile","D":"Wants to avoid all interest rate risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A bullet strategy purchases bonds that all mature at approximately the same date, generating a large cash inflow at that target time. This is ideal for matching a specific future liability, such as college tuition, a home purchase, or a retirement date.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-010","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor buys a stock for $80, receives $2 in dividends, and sells it for $92. The holding period return is:","choices":{"A":"15.0%","B":"17.5%","C":"12.5%","D":"14.0%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"HPR = (Ending Value - Beginning Value + Income) / Beginning Value = ($92 - $80 + $2) / $80 = $14 / $80 = 17.5%. The total return includes both capital appreciation ($12) and dividend income ($2).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-011","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Time-weighted return differs from money-weighted return because time-weighted return:","choices":{"A":"Includes the impact of cash flow timing","B":"Eliminates the impact of external cash flows","C":"Always produces a higher return number","D":"Is only used for individual investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Time-weighted return eliminates the impact of external cash flows (contributions and withdrawals). This makes it appropriate for comparing investment managers who don't control the timing of client cash flows. Money-weighted return (IRR) includes cash flow timing and reflects the actual investor experience.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch10-012","section":"Risk Return","stem":"According to GIPS (Global Investment Performance Standards), which return calculation method is required for reporting most fund performance?","choices":{"A":"Money-weighted return (IRR)","B":"Time-weighted return","C":"Simple arithmetic return","D":"Holding period return only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"GIPS requires time-weighted returns for reporting most fund performance because it eliminates the effect of cash flows that managers cannot control, allowing fair comparisons between managers. Money-weighted returns are required only for certain asset classes like private equity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-001","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Long-term capital gains treatment requires holding an asset for:","choices":{"A":"At least 6 months","B":"Exactly 1 year","C":"More than 1 year","D":"At least 2 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Long-term capital gains treatment requires holding an asset for MORE than one year (at least one year and one day). Assets held for one year or less are taxed as short-term gains at ordinary income rates, which can be as high as 37%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-002","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"If an investor has $20,000 in capital losses and no capital gains this year, they may deduct:","choices":{"A":"The full $20,000 against ordinary income","B":"Up to $3,000 against ordinary income, with the remainder carried forward","C":"Nothing - capital losses can only offset capital gains","D":"$10,000 this year and $10,000 next year"},"answer":"B","explanation":"After offsetting capital gains (none in this case), excess capital losses can offset up to $3,000 of ordinary income per year. The remaining $17,000 carries forward indefinitely to future tax years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The wash sale rule prevents claiming a loss if substantially identical securities are purchased within:","choices":{"A":"30 days after the sale only","B":"60 days before or after the sale","C":"30 days before or after the sale (61-day window)","D":"90 days after the sale only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The wash sale rule applies if you buy substantially identical securities within 30 days BEFORE or 30 days AFTER the sale - a total 61-day window (30 + sale day + 30). This includes purchases by your spouse or IRA.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In a defined benefit plan, investment risk is borne by:","choices":{"A":"The employee","B":"The employer","C":"The government","D":"Both equally"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a defined benefit (pension) plan, the employer bears the investment risk because they promise a specific benefit at retirement regardless of investment performance. If investments perform poorly, the employer must contribute more to meet the promised benefit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The 2025 employee elective deferral limit for a 401(k) plan for someone under age 50 is:","choices":{"A":"$7,000","B":"$23,500","C":"$31,000","D":"$70,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The 2025 employee elective deferral limit for 401(k) plans is $23,500 for those under age 50. Those ages 50-59 or 64+ can add $7,500 catch-up ($31,000 total), and those ages 60-63 can add $11,250 super catch-up ($34,750 total).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 457(b) plan differs from a 401(k) plan in that the 457(b):","choices":{"A":"Has lower contribution limits","B":"Has a separate contribution limit from 401(k) and no 10% early withdrawal penalty","C":"Is only available to private sector employees","D":"Does not allow catch-up contributions"},"answer":"B","explanation":"457(b) plans have a separate contribution limit from 401(k)/403(b) plans (allowing dual contributions) and do NOT have the 10% early withdrawal penalty before age 59 1/2. They are available to government and certain nonprofit employees.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-007","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A qualified distribution from a Roth IRA requires the account to be open for at least:","choices":{"A":"1 year","B":"3 years","C":"5 years","D":"10 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a Roth IRA distribution to be tax-free and penalty-free, the 5-year rule must be met (account open at least 5 years) AND a qualifying event must occur (age 59 1/2, disability, death, or first-time home purchase up to $10,000).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which type of IRA does NOT require RMDs during the owner's lifetime?","choices":{"A":"Traditional IRA","B":"SEP IRA","C":"SIMPLE IRA","D":"Roth IRA"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Roth IRAs do NOT require RMDs during the owner's lifetime. Traditional IRAs, SEP IRAs, and SIMPLE IRAs all require RMDs beginning at age 73. This is a significant advantage of Roth IRAs for tax and estate planning.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In 2025, a married couple filing jointly with MAGI of $250,000 who wants to contribute to a Roth IRA:","choices":{"A":"Can make a full contribution","B":"Can make a partial contribution (in the phase-out range)","C":"Cannot contribute directly but can use backdoor Roth strategy","D":"Is prohibited from any Roth contributions, including conversions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For 2025, the Roth IRA phase-out range for married filing jointly is $236,000-$246,000. With MAGI of $250,000, they are above the full phase-out and cannot contribute directly. However, they can still do a backdoor Roth (non-deductible Traditional IRA contribution followed by Roth conversion).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Qualified withdrawals from a 529 plan are:","choices":{"A":"Taxed as ordinary income","B":"Taxed as capital gains","C":"Tax-free when used for qualified education expenses","D":"Subject to a 10% penalty regardless of use"},"answer":"C","explanation":"529 plan qualified withdrawals are completely tax-free when used for qualified education expenses including tuition, fees, books, room and board, computers, and up to $10,000/year for K-12 tuition. Non-qualified withdrawals have earnings taxed plus a 10% penalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the 529 to Roth IRA rollover provision, the maximum lifetime amount that can be rolled over is:","choices":{"A":"$7,000","B":"$10,000","C":"$35,000","D":"Unlimited"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The lifetime limit for 529 to Roth IRA rollovers is $35,000 per beneficiary. The rollover is also subject to annual Roth IRA contribution limits ($7,000 in 2025) and requires the 529 account to be open for at least 15 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The annual contribution limit for a Coverdell Education Savings Account is:","choices":{"A":"$2,000 per beneficiary","B":"$7,000 per beneficiary","C":"$19,000 per beneficiary","D":"No federal limit"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Coverdell ESA contributions are limited to $2,000 per year per beneficiary. Unlike 529 plans, Coverdell accounts also have contributor income limits. Contributions must be made before the beneficiary turns 18, and funds must be used by age 30.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-013","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under SECURE 2.0, the penalty for failing to take a Required Minimum Distribution is:","choices":{"A":"10% of the shortfall","B":"25% of the shortfall","C":"50% of the shortfall","D":"No penalty"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SECURE 2.0 reduced the penalty for failing to take an RMD from 50% to 25% of the shortfall. The penalty can be further reduced to 10% if the error is corrected within a specified correction period (generally by the end of the second year following the year the RMD was due).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-014","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 401(k) participant who separates from service at age 56 and takes a distribution:","choices":{"A":"Must pay a 10% early withdrawal penalty","B":"May avoid the 10% penalty under the age 55 separation rule","C":"Must roll the funds to an IRA first","D":"Cannot take any distribution until age 59 1/2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The age 55 separation rule allows 401(k) participants who leave their employer at age 55 or older to take distributions without the 10% early withdrawal penalty. This exception does NOT apply to IRAs - it only applies to employer plans.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch11-015","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the SECURE Act, most non-spouse beneficiaries who inherit an IRA must:","choices":{"A":"Take distributions over their life expectancy","B":"Take a lump sum distribution immediately","C":"Deplete the entire account within 10 years","D":"Leave the account untouched until age 59 1/2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the SECURE Act's 10-year rule, most non-spouse beneficiaries must fully deplete an inherited IRA within 10 years of the original owner's death. Exceptions exist for surviving spouses, minor children, disabled/chronically ill individuals, and beneficiaries not more than 10 years younger than the deceased.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-001","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under ERISA, the \"prudent expert\" rule requires fiduciaries to:","choices":{"A":"Act as any reasonable person would under the circumstances","B":"Act with the care and skill of someone familiar with such matters","C":"Guarantee positive investment returns","D":"Only invest in government securities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The prudent expert rule requires fiduciaries to act with the care, skill, prudence, and diligence that a prudent person acting in a like capacity and familiar with such matters would use. This is a higher standard than ordinary prudence because it assumes specialized knowledge.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-002","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following plans is subject to ERISA?","choices":{"A":"A state government pension plan","B":"A church retirement plan","C":"A private employer 401(k) plan","D":"An individual retirement account (IRA)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ERISA applies to private sector employer-sponsored retirement plans like 401(k) plans. Government plans, church plans, and individual plans like IRAs are not subject to ERISA.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiduciary-duty","retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A prohibited transaction under ERISA includes:","choices":{"A":"Investing plan assets in diversified mutual funds","B":"Hiring a third-party administrator for the plan","C":"A fiduciary selling their own property to the plan","D":"Providing participants with multiple investment options"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Selling property between the plan and a party in interest (including fiduciaries) is a prohibited transaction under ERISA Section 406. Such transactions create conflicts of interest and potential for self-dealing at the expense of plan participants.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The Federal Reserve's Regulation T requires an initial margin of:","choices":{"A":"25% of the purchase price","B":"50% of the purchase price","C":"75% of the purchase price","D":"100% of the purchase price"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Regulation T, set by the Federal Reserve Board, requires an initial margin of 50% for most equity securities purchased on margin. This means investors can borrow up to half of the purchase price. The 25% figure is the FINRA maintenance margin minimum.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A wrap fee account would be MOST suitable for:","choices":{"A":"A buy-and-hold investor who rarely trades","B":"An active trader who wants bundled services and predictable fees","C":"An investor who only buys Treasury securities","D":"A self-directed investor who needs no advice"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Wrap fee accounts, which bundle investment advice, trading, and custody for a single fee (typically 1-3% of assets), are most suitable for active traders who value bundled services and fee predictability. Buy-and-hold investors may pay for services they don't use.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Discretionary authority in an investment account allows the adviser to:","choices":{"A":"Withdraw funds from the client's account","B":"Change the account's beneficiary designations","C":"Make investment decisions without prior approval for each trade","D":"Guarantee the client's investment returns"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Discretionary authority allows the adviser to make investment decisions - determining what, when, and how much to buy or sell - without obtaining prior client approval for each transaction. It does NOT authorize withdrawals or beneficiary changes, which require separate authorization.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-007","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Time-weighted return (TWR) is required by GIPS because it:","choices":{"A":"Reflects the investor's actual experience","B":"Eliminates the impact of cash flows to measure manager performance","C":"Is easier to calculate than money-weighted return","D":"Always shows higher returns than other methods"},"answer":"B","explanation":"GIPS requires time-weighted return because it eliminates the effect of client cash flows (contributions and withdrawals), isolating the pure investment performance that the manager can control. This allows fair comparison between managers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-008","section":"Risk Return","stem":"The Treynor ratio differs from the Sharpe ratio because Treynor:","choices":{"A":"Uses standard deviation as the risk measure","B":"Uses beta (systematic risk) as the risk measure","C":"Does not subtract the risk-free rate","D":"Can only be used for bond portfolios"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Treynor ratio uses beta (systematic risk) in the denominator, while the Sharpe ratio uses standard deviation (total risk). Treynor is more appropriate for well-diversified portfolios where unsystematic risk has been diversified away.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-009","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A portfolio manager has a Jensen's alpha of +2.5%. This means:","choices":{"A":"The portfolio underperformed expectations by 2.5%","B":"The portfolio outperformed its risk-adjusted expected return by 2.5%","C":"The portfolio had 2.5% less risk than the market","D":"The portfolio's beta was 2.5"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A positive Jensen's alpha indicates the portfolio earned 2.5% more than what CAPM predicted based on its beta. This suggests manager skill in generating returns above what would be expected for the level of systematic risk taken.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A QDRO distribution to a former spouse from a 401(k) plan:","choices":{"A":"Is subject to the 10% early withdrawal penalty","B":"Is exempt from the 10% early withdrawal penalty but subject to income tax","C":"Is completely tax-free","D":"Must be rolled into the plan participant's IRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"QDRO distributions to an alternate payee (such as a former spouse) are exempt from the 10% early withdrawal penalty, even if the recipient is under age 59 1/2. However, if taken as a lump sum rather than rolled over, the distribution is still subject to ordinary income tax.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the SECURE Act, most non-spouse beneficiaries who inherit an IRA after 2019 must:","choices":{"A":"Take annual distributions based on their life expectancy","B":"Take a lump sum distribution immediately","C":"Empty the account within 10 years of the owner's death","D":"Roll the account into their own IRA"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SECURE Act's 10-year rule requires most non-spouse beneficiaries to fully distribute an inherited IRA within 10 years of the owner's death. Exceptions exist for eligible designated beneficiaries (surviving spouse, minor children, disabled individuals, etc.).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch12-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is NOT required to use a QDRO for division in divorce?","choices":{"A":"401(k) plan","B":"Traditional IRA","C":"Defined benefit pension","D":"403(b) plan"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Traditional IRAs do not require a QDRO for division in divorce. IRAs can be divided through a \"transfer incident to divorce\" as specified in the divorce decree. QDROs are required only for employer-sponsored qualified plans like 401(k)s, pensions, and 403(b)s.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-001","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, a person is an \"investment adviser\" if they:","choices":{"A":"Provide advice about securities for any purpose","B":"Meet all three elements: advice about securities, as a business, for compensation","C":"Are registered with the SEC","D":"Have at least 5 clients"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The \"ABC Test\" requires all three elements: providing Advice about securities, doing so as a regular Business activity, and receiving Compensation (direct or indirect). All three must be present to meet the definition.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-002","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A CPA who provides investment advice as part of financial planning services, charges separately for this advice, and advertises these services is:","choices":{"A":"Excluded from the investment adviser definition","B":"Subject to the Investment Advisers Act and must register or qualify for an exemption","C":"Automatically registered as a broker-dealer","D":"Exempt from all securities regulation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The LATE exclusion (Lawyers, Accountants, Teachers, Engineers) requires advice to be \"solely incidental\" to the profession with no separate compensation. Charging separately for advice and advertising investment services means the CPA does not qualify for the exclusion.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A broker-dealer qualifies for the exclusion from the investment adviser definition if:","choices":{"A":"They provide any investment advice to customers","B":"Their advice is solely incidental to brokerage AND they receive no special compensation for advice","C":"They are registered with FINRA","D":"They have fewer than 15 clients"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The broker-dealer exclusion has two conjunctive requirements: advice must be solely incidental to the brokerage business AND the broker-dealer must not receive special (separate) compensation for the advice. Both conditions must be met.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-004","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser with $120 million in regulatory AUM must:","choices":{"A":"Register with the state where the principal office is located","B":"Register with the SEC","C":"Register with both the SEC and all 50 states","D":"Choose between SEC or state registration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Advisers with $110 million or more in AUM must register with the SEC. At $120 million, the adviser is above this threshold and is a federal covered adviser, meaning SEC registration is required.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-005","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Form ADV Part 2A must be delivered to clients:","choices":{"A":"Only upon client request","B":"Before or at the time of entering into an advisory contract","C":"Within 30 days after opening an account","D":"Only if the client is a retail investor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The brochure (Form ADV Part 2A) must be delivered before or at the time the client enters into an advisory contract. This ensures clients have disclosure information before committing to the advisory relationship.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-006","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An SEC-registered adviser must file an annual updating amendment to Form ADV:","choices":{"A":"Within 30 days of the calendar year-end","B":"Within 90 days of the adviser's fiscal year-end","C":"Within 120 days of the calendar year-end","D":"Only when there are material changes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investment advisers must file an annual updating amendment to Form ADV within 90 days of their fiscal year-end. For an adviser with a December 31 fiscal year-end, this means filing by March 31.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Investment adviser records must generally be maintained for:","choices":{"A":"3 years, all in the principal office","B":"5 years, with the first 2 years in an easily accessible location","C":"7 years, with the first 5 years in the principal office","D":"10 years, all in electronic format"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Most investment adviser records must be maintained for 5 years. The first 2 years must be kept in an easily accessible location (an \"appropriate office\"), and the remaining 3 years may be stored elsewhere as long as they can be retrieved.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-008","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The SEC or state administrator may examine investment adviser records:","choices":{"A":"Only with 30 days advance written notice","B":"Only with a court order","C":"Without prior notice at any time","D":"Only during regular business hours with 24-hour notice"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Regulators have broad examination authority and may examine investment adviser books and records without prior notice. This \"surprise\" examination authority helps ensure compliance and prevents destruction of records.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-009","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following must be included in an investment adviser's records?","choices":{"A":"Only executed trade confirmations","B":"Written recommendations, client correspondence, and advertisements to 10+ persons","C":"Only records of discretionary accounts","D":"Only financial statements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investment advisers must maintain extensive records including all written recommendations, client correspondence, advertisements distributed to 10 or more persons, and many other categories of business and compliance documents.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser is deemed to have \"custody\" of client assets if the adviser:","choices":{"A":"Only provides investment recommendations","B":"Has authority to deduct advisory fees directly from client accounts","C":"Sends trade confirmations to clients","D":"Uses a third-party custodian for client assets"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Having authority to deduct advisory fees directly from client accounts constitutes \"constructive custody\" because the adviser can access and withdraw client funds. This triggers custody rule requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The annual surprise examination of an adviser with custody must be conducted by:","choices":{"A":"The SEC or state administrator","B":"An independent public accountant registered with the PCAOB","C":"The adviser's compliance officer","D":"A FINRA examiner"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The surprise examination must be conducted by an independent public accountant registered with the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB). The timing must be irregular and without advance notice to the adviser.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A state-registered investment adviser with custody of client assets must maintain minimum net worth of:","choices":{"A":"$10,000","B":"$25,000","C":"$35,000","D":"$50,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under NASAA model rules adopted by most states, advisers with custody must maintain $35,000 minimum net worth. If they have discretionary authority but not custody, the requirement is $10,000. Alternatively, a surety bond can be posted.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-013","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An Exempt Reporting Adviser (ERA) must:","choices":{"A":"Register fully with the SEC and all states","B":"File an abbreviated Form ADV and remain subject to SEC examination","C":"Have no regulatory requirements whatsoever","D":"Register only with the state of its principal office"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Exempt Reporting Advisers are exempt from SEC registration but must file an abbreviated Form ADV through IARD, maintain books and records, and remain subject to SEC examination authority and antifraud provisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-014","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The private fund adviser exemption is available to advisers who:","choices":{"A":"Advise any type of fund with less than $100 million AUM","B":"Advise only private funds and have less than $150 million in U.S. private fund AUM","C":"Advise only venture capital funds","D":"Have fewer than 15 clients regardless of fund type"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The private fund adviser exemption applies to advisers who advise only private funds (3(c)(1) or 3(c)(7) funds) and have less than $150 million in regulatory assets under management in the United States.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch13-015","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The state de minimis exemption typically applies when an adviser has:","choices":{"A":"Less than $100 million AUM in the state","B":"No place of business in the state and 5 or fewer clients in the past 12 months","C":"Only institutional clients in the state","D":"A valid SEC registration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The de minimis exemption generally applies when an adviser has no place of business in a state, has 5 or fewer clients in that state during the past 12 months, and does not hold itself out as an adviser in that state.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-001","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an Investment Adviser Representative is defined as an individual who:","choices":{"A":"Only owns shares in an investment advisory firm","B":"Provides investment advice, manages accounts, or solicits advisory business","C":"Only performs clerical functions for an adviser","D":"Is registered with the SEC as a broker-dealer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An IAR is defined as an individual who provides investment advice, manages client accounts, determines recommendations, solicits advisory services, or supervises persons performing these functions on behalf of an investment adviser.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The Series 65 exam consists of how many scored questions with what passing score?","choices":{"A":"100 questions, 70% to pass","B":"130 questions, approximately 70% to pass (72 correct)","C":"150 questions, 75% to pass","D":"125 questions, 72% to pass"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Series 65 exam has 130 scored questions (plus 10 unscored pretest questions). Candidates must answer at least 72 questions correctly (approximately 70%) to pass. The exam is 180 minutes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which professional designation may waive the Series 65 exam requirement?","choices":{"A":"CPA (Certified Public Accountant)","B":"MBA (Master of Business Administration)","C":"CFP (Certified Financial Planner)","D":"Series 7 license alone"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The CFP designation, along with CFA, ChFC, PFS, and CIMA (replacing CIC), may waive the Series 65 exam requirement in most states. The designation must be current and in good standing. CPA and MBA do not qualify for the waiver.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-004","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The annual continuing education requirement for IARs under the NASAA model rule is:","choices":{"A":"6 credits in any category","B":"12 credits: 6 in Products & Practice and 6 in Ethics","C":"20 credits in any category","D":"15 credits: 10 in Products and 5 in Ethics"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The NASAA IAR CE model rule requires 12 credits annually, split evenly between 6 credits of Products & Practice and 6 credits of Ethics & Professional Responsibility. The split is mandatory--credits cannot be substituted between categories.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-005","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When an IAR is terminated, the investment adviser must file Form U5:","choices":{"A":"Within 10 days","B":"Within 30 days","C":"Within 60 days","D":"Within 90 days"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Form U5 (Uniform Termination Notice) must be filed within 30 days of an IAR's termination. The form includes the reason for termination and becomes part of the individual's public record.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An IAR who has been terminated for 18 months wishes to re-register. They must:","choices":{"A":"Re-take the Series 65 exam","B":"Re-register without re-taking the exam (exam valid for 2 years)","C":"Wait until the 2-year period expires","D":"Obtain a new professional designation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Exam validity continues for 2 years from the termination date. Since 18 months is within the 2-year window, the individual can re-register without re-taking the qualifying exam.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An IAR who works for an SEC-registered (federal covered) adviser must register with states where:","choices":{"A":"They have any clients","B":"They have a place of business","C":"The SEC directs them to register","D":"They were born or educated"},"answer":"B","explanation":"IARs of federal covered advisers must register only in states where they have a \"place of business\" (physical office, meet clients, or hold themselves out as available). This is more limited than IARs of state-registered advisers, who must register wherever they have clients.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which statement about state authority over IARs of SEC-registered advisers is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"States have no authority over these IARs","B":"States can require the SEC-registered adviser to also register with the state","C":"States can require IAR registration, qualification exams, and can discipline IARs","D":"States can only collect fees but cannot investigate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"While states cannot require the federal covered adviser itself to register, they retain full authority over IARs--including requiring registration, qualification exams, collecting fees, investigating misconduct, and taking disciplinary action.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch14-009","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An IAR of a federal covered adviser has an office in Texas and calls clients in Oklahoma and Kansas. The IAR must register in:","choices":{"A":"Texas, Oklahoma, and Kansas","B":"Texas only (where the place of business is located)","C":"Oklahoma and Kansas only (where the clients are)","D":"No state registration is required"},"answer":"B","explanation":"IARs of federal covered advisers must register only in states where they have a place of business. Since the office is in Texas, only Texas registration is required--not Oklahoma or Kansas, even though clients are there. This differs from IARs of state-registered advisers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-001","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When a broker-dealer acts as a dealer in a transaction, it:","choices":{"A":"Earns a commission for executing the customer's order","B":"Acts as principal, trading from its own inventory and earning a markup or markdown","C":"Provides investment advice for a fee","D":"Acts only as an intermediary without taking any risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When acting as a dealer (principal), the firm buys or sells securities from its own inventory and earns a markup (when selling) or markdown (when buying). When acting as a broker (agent), the firm earns commissions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-002","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Broker-dealers must register with:","choices":{"A":"Only the SEC","B":"Only FINRA","C":"The SEC and FINRA, and with each state where they conduct business","D":"Only the states where they have a physical office"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Broker-dealers must register at the federal level with the SEC using Form BD, become FINRA members, and register with each state where they conduct securities business. The CRD system facilitates filing with multiple jurisdictions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1934","finra"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A \"carrying firm\" (one that holds customer funds and securities) must maintain minimum net capital of:","choices":{"A":"$5,000","B":"$50,000","C":"$100,000","D":"$250,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Under SEC Rule 15c3-1, a carrying firm that holds customer funds and securities must maintain minimum net capital of $250,000. This higher requirement reflects the greater risk associated with custody of customer assets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-004","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The Securities Industry Essentials (SIE) exam:","choices":{"A":"Requires broker-dealer sponsorship to take","B":"Can be taken by anyone 18 or older without firm sponsorship","C":"Is only available to investment advisers","D":"Must be taken after the Series 7"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The SIE exam can be taken by anyone 18 or older without broker-dealer sponsorship. It covers foundational securities knowledge and is valid for 4 years, giving candidates time to join a firm and complete role-specific exams like the Series 7 or Series 6.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-005","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent's state registration:","choices":{"A":"Continues indefinitely once obtained","B":"Is only valid while associated with a registered broker-dealer","C":"Transfers automatically to any new employer","D":"Expires after 4 years regardless of employment"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An agent's registration is only effective while associated with a registered broker-dealer. When the association ends (termination, resignation), the registration terminates. The individual must re-register through a new broker-dealer to continue conducting securities business.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-006","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The Series 7 exam allows a registered representative to:","choices":{"A":"Only sell mutual funds and variable annuities","B":"Sell virtually all types of securities products","C":"Provide investment advice as an IAR","D":"Supervise other registered representatives"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Series 7 is the broadest representative license, allowing the sale of virtually all types of securities including stocks, bonds, options, mutual funds, and variable contracts. The Series 6 is limited to investment company products and variable contracts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under Regulation Best Interest, the Care Obligation requires broker-dealers to:","choices":{"A":"Guarantee positive investment returns","B":"Only recommend the cheapest investment products","C":"Exercise reasonable diligence, care, and skill in making recommendations","D":"Avoid making any recommendations that involve conflicts of interest"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Care Obligation requires broker-dealers to exercise reasonable diligence, care, and skill, including understanding the product, having a reasonable basis for the recommendation, considering costs, and ensuring the recommendation is in the particular customer's best interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reg-bi"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-008","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Form CRS must be:","choices":{"A":"A maximum of 10 pages and filed annually","B":"A maximum of 2 pages (4 for dual registrants) and delivered before or at the earliest recommendation","C":"Filed only with state regulators","D":"Provided only to institutional investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Form CRS is limited to 2 pages for standalone broker-dealers or investment advisers (4 pages for dual registrants). It must be delivered before or at the earliest of: making a recommendation, placing an order, or opening an account.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reg-bi"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch15-009","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Conflict of Interest Obligation, broker-dealers must:","choices":{"A":"Avoid all conflicts of interest completely","B":"Establish policies to identify, disclose, and mitigate conflicts, and eliminate sales contests for specific products","C":"Only disclose conflicts that result in higher compensation","D":"Allow sales contests as long as they are disclosed"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Conflict of Interest Obligation requires establishing written policies to identify, disclose, and mitigate conflicts. Broker-dealers must eliminate sales contests, quotas, and bonuses tied to specific products--not just disclose them.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["reg-bi"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-001","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, a state administrator can issue a cease and desist order:","choices":{"A":"Only after a full hearing","B":"Only with court approval","C":"Without prior notice or hearing","D":"Only against registered persons"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A state administrator can issue a cease and desist order without prior notice or hearing if they believe a violation has occurred or is about to occur. However, a hearing must be provided upon request, typically within 15 days.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The state administrator has subpoena power that:","choices":{"A":"Can only be used within the administrator's state","B":"Can be used to compel production in any state","C":"Can force testimony that may be self-incriminating","D":"Requires prior court approval"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The state administrator's subpoena power extends across state lines--they can compel production of documents and witnesses in any state. However, they cannot compel testimony that would be self-incriminating under the Fifth Amendment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the USA, securities registration becomes effective:","choices":{"A":"Immediately upon filing","B":"At noon on the 30th day after filing, unless otherwise ordered","C":"Only after a public hearing","D":"When the administrator personally approves it"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, securities registration becomes effective at noon on the 30th day after filing, unless the administrator grants an earlier effective date or issues a stop order to delay or deny the registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-004","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Registration by coordination is used when:","choices":{"A":"The security is only sold within one state","B":"The security is being registered with the SEC and state simultaneously","C":"The security is exempt from all registration","D":"The issuer is a government entity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Registration by coordination is used when a security is being registered with both the SEC (under the Securities Act of 1933) and the state at the same time. The state registration becomes effective when the SEC registration becomes effective.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-005","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Federal covered securities:","choices":{"A":"Must complete full registration in each state","B":"Are exempt from all state requirements including antifraud laws","C":"May require notice filing but are exempt from state registration requirements","D":"Cannot be sold in any state"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under NSMIA, federal covered securities are exempt from state registration requirements but may still be subject to state notice filing and fee requirements. States retain full antifraud authority over these securities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Registration by qualification:","choices":{"A":"Is the simplest registration method","B":"Requires SEC registration first","C":"Is the most detailed method, often used for intrastate offerings","D":"Cannot be used for any securities"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Registration by qualification is the most detailed registration method. It is primarily used for securities not registered with the SEC, such as intrastate offerings. The administrator sets the effective date and may impose conditions including escrow requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Securities issued by the U.S. Treasury are:","choices":{"A":"Subject to full state registration","B":"Exempt from state registration but subject to antifraud provisions","C":"Exempt from all federal and state laws","D":"Only available to institutional investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"U.S. Treasury securities are exempt from state registration requirements. However, like all securities, they remain subject to antifraud provisions. Exempt from registration does NOT mean exempt from fraud laws.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Commercial paper qualifies for exemption when it:","choices":{"A":"Has a maturity of 1 year or less","B":"Has a maturity of 9 months or less, minimum $50,000 denomination, and is investment grade","C":"Is issued by any corporation","D":"Is sold to retail investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Commercial paper is exempt when it has a maturity of 9 months or less (270 days), a minimum denomination of $50,000, is rated in the top three credit categories (investment grade), and is not advertised to the general public.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-009","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A security listed on the New York Stock Exchange is considered:","choices":{"A":"Exempt from all federal and state requirements","B":"A federal covered security requiring only notice filing at the state level","C":"Subject to full state registration in each state","D":"Not a security under the Uniform Securities Act"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Securities listed on national exchanges like NYSE are federal covered securities under NSMIA. They are exempt from state registration but may be subject to state notice filing requirements and remain subject to state antifraud provisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-010","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An isolated non-issuer transaction is exempt because:","choices":{"A":"The issuer is selling the securities","B":"It is not part of a regular securities business","C":"Only institutional investors are involved","D":"The securities are listed on an exchange"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Isolated non-issuer transactions are exempt because they are not part of a regular securities business. The seller is not the issuer and is not engaged in the business of selling securities--it is an occasional, isolated sale.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A private placement under Regulation D Rule 506:","choices":{"A":"Requires full registration in each state","B":"Is a federal covered security requiring only notice filing at the state level","C":"Is completely exempt from all federal and state requirements","D":"Can only be sold to accredited investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Securities offered under Regulation D Rule 506 are federal covered securities under NSMIA. States cannot require registration but may require notice filing (typically Form D) and fees. The offering remains subject to state antifraud provisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch16-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Transaction exemptions differ from securities exemptions in that:","choices":{"A":"Transaction exemptions are permanent for the security","B":"Transaction exemptions apply only to the specific transaction, not the security","C":"Transaction exemptions also exempt from antifraud provisions","D":"Securities exemptions require registration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Transaction exemptions apply only to the specific transaction, not to the security itself. A security acquired through an exempt transaction may require registration if resold. Both transaction and securities exemptions remain subject to antifraud provisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-001","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the SEC Marketing Rule, testimonials in investment adviser advertising are:","choices":{"A":"Completely prohibited under all circumstances","B":"Allowed only for institutional clients with over $100 million","C":"Permitted with required disclosures about compensation and conflicts","D":"Only allowed for advisers registered with the SEC"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SEC Marketing Rule (mandatory compliance November 2022) now permits testimonials and endorsements, provided they include required disclosures about whether the promoter is a client, compensation arrangements, and material conflicts of interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-002","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Performance advertising by investment advisers must:","choices":{"A":"Show only gross-of-fees returns for clarity","B":"Show returns net of fees, with gross allowed only if accompanied by net","C":"Never include any performance data for retail clients","D":"Only show the most recent calendar year"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investment advisers must show performance net of fees. Gross performance may be shown, but only if accompanied by net-of-fees performance. Showing gross performance alone is prohibited as it would be misleading about actual client returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A written agreement is required for a testimonial or endorsement when compensation exceeds:","choices":{"A":"$500","B":"$1,000 (de minimis threshold)","C":"$5,000","D":"No written agreement is ever required"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The SEC Marketing Rule includes a de minimis exception--a written agreement is not required when compensation is $1,000 or less. For compensation exceeding $1,000, the adviser must enter into a written agreement with the promoter outlining the terms.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-004","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser's social media posts are:","choices":{"A":"Not subject to advertising rules since they are informal","B":"Subject to the same advertising and recordkeeping rules as traditional communications","C":"Only regulated if they specifically recommend securities","D":"Exempt from compliance requirements if clearly personal"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Social media communications are subject to the same advertising rules, recordkeeping requirements, and supervisory obligations as traditional marketing and advertising materials. The medium of communication does not change the regulatory requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-005","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Electronic communications by investment advisers must be retained for:","choices":{"A":"1 year from the date of creation","B":"3 years, all in an accessible location","C":"5 years, with the first 2 years in an accessible location","D":"7 years, same as tax records"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Investment advisers must retain electronic communications for at least 5 years from their creation. The first 2 years must be maintained in an easily accessible location, meaning the adviser can produce them promptly if requested by regulators.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-006","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When an investment adviser \"likes\" a client's positive review on social media, the adviser has:","choices":{"A":"No regulatory responsibility for the content","B":"Adopted the content and is responsible for its compliance","C":"Only incurred liability if the review is false","D":"Violated the prohibition on testimonials"},"answer":"B","explanation":"By \"liking\" or sharing third-party content, an adviser has \"adopted\" that content and becomes responsible for ensuring it complies with advertising rules, including prohibitions on misleading statements and requirements for testimonial disclosures.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser must deliver Form ADV Part 2A to clients:","choices":{"A":"Only upon specific written request from the client","B":"Before or at the time of entering into an advisory contract","C":"Only after one year of continuous service","D":"Only if the client is classified as a retail investor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Form ADV Part 2A (the firm brochure) must be delivered before or at the time of entering into an advisory contract. It must also be updated annually within 120 days of fiscal year-end, with a summary of material changes or the full updated brochure.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-008","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser cannot assign an advisory contract without:","choices":{"A":"SEC prior approval and 30-day waiting period","B":"FINRA approval and registration amendment","C":"Client consent","D":"State administrator approval and public notice"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Investment advisory contracts cannot be assigned to another person without the client's consent. A change in controlling ownership of the adviser (more than 25%) may constitute an assignment requiring client consent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-009","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The annual summary of material changes to Form ADV Part 2A must be delivered to existing clients within:","choices":{"A":"30 days of fiscal year-end","B":"60 days of fiscal year-end","C":"90 days of fiscal year-end","D":"120 days of fiscal year-end"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Investment advisers must deliver either a summary of material changes or a full updated Form ADV Part 2A brochure to existing clients annually within 120 days of the adviser's fiscal year-end.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"If an investment adviser has authority to vote client proxies, they must:","choices":{"A":"Always vote in accordance with management recommendations","B":"Adopt written policies and vote in the client's best interest","C":"Abstain from voting to avoid conflicts","D":"Allow clients to vote their own proxies instead"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Advisers with proxy voting authority must adopt written policies and procedures that are reasonably designed to ensure votes are cast in clients' best interests. They must also disclose their policies, address conflicts of interest, and maintain voting records for 5 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The Section 28(e) safe harbor for soft dollar arrangements requires:","choices":{"A":"That only hard dollars be used for research","B":"That services be eligible, assist investment decisions, and commissions be reasonable","C":"SEC pre-approval of all arrangements","D":"That no client commissions be used for any research"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Section 28(e) provides a safe harbor if: (1) the services are eligible brokerage or research services, (2) they provide lawful and appropriate assistance in investment decision-making, and (3) the adviser makes a good faith determination that commissions are reasonable relative to the value of services received.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch17-012","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When aggregating (bunching) client orders, an adviser must:","choices":{"A":"Allocate all shares to the account with the lowest fees","B":"Give priority to accounts that have been waiting longest","C":"Allocate at the same average price with fair, pro-rata distribution","D":"Execute proprietary orders first before client orders"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When aggregating orders, all participating accounts must receive the same average price, and shares must be allocated fairly (typically pro-rata). Favoring any account--whether based on fees, relationship, or proprietary status--is prohibited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-001","section":"Suitability","stem":"The duty of loyalty requires an investment adviser to:","choices":{"A":"Only recommend securities the adviser personally owns","B":"Put client interests ahead of their own and disclose material conflicts","C":"Always recommend the highest-yielding investments available","D":"Charge the lowest fees in the industry"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The duty of loyalty requires advisers to put client interests first, avoid conflicts of interest where possible, and disclose all material conflicts that cannot be eliminated. The client's interests must always take priority over the adviser's interests.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-002","section":"Suitability","stem":"The fiduciary standard differs from the suitability standard because the fiduciary duty:","choices":{"A":"Only applies to institutional clients with over $1 million","B":"Is an ongoing obligation to act in the client's best interest","C":"Does not require any disclosure of conflicts","D":"Is a lower standard of care than suitability"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The fiduciary standard is higher than suitability. It requires ongoing action in the client's best interest throughout the relationship, not just suitable recommendations at the time of advice. Fiduciary duty also requires avoiding (not just disclosing) conflicts where possible.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-003","section":"Suitability","stem":"Under the duty of care, an investment adviser must:","choices":{"A":"Guarantee client accounts against loss","B":"Understand the client's situation and make suitable recommendations with ongoing monitoring","C":"Only recommend investments with no risk of loss","D":"Provide the same recommendations to all clients regardless of circumstances"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The duty of care requires advisers to understand each client's financial situation, objectives, and risk tolerance, make suitable recommendations based on that understanding, and provide ongoing monitoring. Guaranteeing against loss is prohibited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-004","section":"Suitability","stem":"Front-running is:","choices":{"A":"Executing client orders as quickly as possible for best execution","B":"Trading ahead of client orders based on advance knowledge of those orders","C":"Placing orders at the front of the order queue","D":"A legitimate trading strategy for improving execution prices"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Front-running is the prohibited practice of trading ahead of client orders based on advance knowledge of those pending orders. For example, buying stock personally before executing a large client buy order that would drive up the price. It violates the adviser's duty of loyalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-005","section":"Suitability","stem":"Churning is prohibited because it:","choices":{"A":"Always results in client losses","B":"Involves excessive trading primarily to generate commissions for the adviser","C":"Provides too much diversification for client portfolios","D":"Violates margin requirements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Churning involves excessive trading in a client's account primarily to generate commissions for the adviser, disregarding the client's investment objectives and interests. It requires (1) excessive trading, (2) adviser control, and (3) intent or reckless disregard.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser guarantees a client that they will not lose money. This is:","choices":{"A":"Permitted if the guarantee is in writing","B":"Permitted for clients over age 65","C":"Absolutely prohibited under all circumstances","D":"Permitted if the adviser has sufficient capital"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Guaranteeing against loss is absolutely prohibited under the NASAA Model Rule and securities regulations. Advisers cannot guarantee returns or promise to make clients whole after losses. This prohibition has no exceptions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A \"trusted contact\" for a senior client:","choices":{"A":"Has power of attorney to make trading decisions","B":"May be contacted if financial exploitation or diminished capacity is suspected","C":"Must approve all transactions in the account","D":"Can only be a family member or attorney"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A trusted contact is someone the firm may contact if there is concern about potential financial exploitation or diminished capacity. This is separate from a power of attorney--the trusted contact has no authority over the account and cannot make trading decisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the NASAA Model Act, an initial temporary hold on a suspicious disbursement can last up to:","choices":{"A":"5 business days","B":"10 business days","C":"15 business days","D":"30 business days"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the NASAA Model Act, a firm may place an initial temporary hold on a disbursement for up to 15 business days when financial exploitation is reasonably suspected. An additional 10 business days may be granted upon request by a regulator or Adult Protective Services.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-009","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following is a red flag for potential financial exploitation of a senior client?","choices":{"A":"Making regular monthly withdrawals consistent with past behavior","B":"Sudden large withdrawals to unfamiliar recipients with client appearing confused","C":"Investing in a diversified portfolio appropriate for their age","D":"Requesting account statements be mailed to their home address"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Red flags for exploitation include sudden changes in financial behavior, unusual or large transactions to unfamiliar recipients, client confusion about their transactions, and the involvement of new third parties in financial decisions. Consistent patterns of normal activity are not red flags.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A Suspicious Activity Report (SAR) must be filed with FinCEN when:","choices":{"A":"Any transaction over $1,000 occurs","B":"A transaction of $5,000 or more involves suspected criminal activity","C":"All wire transfers are executed","D":"A client opens a new account"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A SAR must be filed with FinCEN for transactions involving $5,000 or more in funds or assets when there is reasonable suspicion of illegal activity such as money laundering, terrorist financing, or fraud. SARs are confidential and cannot be disclosed to the subject.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser's compliance program must include:","choices":{"A":"Only a written code of ethics filed with the SEC","B":"Written policies, a designated CCO, and an annual review of effectiveness","C":"Only annual client notification letters","D":"Only quarterly reports to state regulators"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SEC Rule 206(4)-7 requires all registered investment advisers to adopt written compliance policies and procedures, designate a Chief Compliance Officer to administer the program, and conduct an annual review of the program's effectiveness.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-series65-ch18-012","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Regarding SAR filings, an investment adviser:","choices":{"A":"Must notify the client that a SAR has been filed","B":"Cannot disclose the SAR filing to the subject of the report","C":"Must obtain client consent before filing","D":"May only file with state regulators, not FinCEN"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SARs are confidential documents. An adviser cannot disclose to the client (or anyone outside the firm except regulators and law enforcement) that a SAR has been filed. This confidentiality requirement is a critical aspect of the AML framework, and firms have \"safe harbor\" protection for good-faith filings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-001","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Using the Rule of 72, approximately how many years will it take for an investment earning 8% annually to double in value?","choices":{"A":"6 years","B":"9 years","C":"12 years","D":"18 years"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Rule of 72 states that to find the approximate time for an investment to double, divide 72 by the annual interest rate. At 8%: 72 / 8 = 9 years to double.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under current SEC rules, when can an investment adviser use client testimonials in advertising?","choices":{"A":"Testimonials are always prohibited","B":"Only if the client is a qualified purchaser","C":"When proper disclosures are provided","D":"Only for institutional clients"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the SEC Marketing Rule (amended in 2020), investment advisers may use testimonials and endorsements in advertising provided they include required disclosures about whether compensation was paid, material conflicts of interest, and that the testimonial may not be representative of other clients' experiences.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-003","section":"Economics","stem":"Which of the following would NOT be classified as a current asset on a balance sheet?","choices":{"A":"Cash and cash equivalents","B":"Accounts receivable","C":"Intellectual property","D":"Inventory"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Intellectual property (patents, trademarks, copyrights) is classified as an intangible long-term asset, not a current asset. Current assets are those expected to be converted to cash within one year, such as cash, receivables, and inventory.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-004","section":"Economics","stem":"A corporation owns 25% of the common stock of another domestic corporation. What percentage of dividends received can it exclude from taxable income under the dividends received deduction?","choices":{"A":"50%","B":"65%","C":"80%","D":"100%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For corporate shareholders owning between 20% and 79.99% of another domestic corporation, the dividends received deduction is 65%. This reduces the effective tax on intercompany dividends to avoid triple taxation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-005","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A client with moderate risk tolerance and objectives of both growth and income would be BEST suited for a portfolio consisting of:","choices":{"A":"100% high-yield bonds","B":"100% speculative growth stocks","C":"A balanced mix of stocks and bonds","D":"100% Treasury bills"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A balanced portfolio of stocks and bonds is appropriate for moderate risk tolerance with growth and income objectives. Stocks provide growth potential while bonds provide income and stability, creating diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-006","section":"Suitability","stem":"An 80-year-old client states their primary investment objective is income. Which ADDITIONAL objective is MOST likely appropriate for this client?","choices":{"A":"Maximum capital appreciation","B":"Preservation of capital","C":"Aggressive growth","D":"Speculation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For elderly clients seeking income, preservation of capital is typically the most appropriate additional objective. At age 80, there is limited time to recover from losses, making capital preservation crucial alongside income generation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-007","section":"Annuities","stem":"The mortality risk assumed by an insurance company in a variable annuity contract refers to the risk that:","choices":{"A":"The annuitant will die during the accumulation phase","B":"The annuitant will live longer than expected","C":"Investment returns will be negative","D":"Interest rates will rise"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mortality risk for the insurance company is the risk that the annuitant lives longer than actuarially expected. During the annuity phase, the company must continue making payments as long as the annuitant lives, so longevity increases the company's liability.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When an investment adviser executes an agency cross transaction between two advisory clients, which of the following is required?","choices":{"A":"SEC pre-approval of the transaction","B":"Prior written consent and disclosure of conflicts","C":"A minimum 30-day waiting period","D":"Only verbal consent from one client"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Agency cross transactions require prior written disclosure and consent from both clients. The adviser must disclose the capacity in which they are acting and any potential conflicts of interest, including that they may receive compensation from both sides.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-009","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A bond bullet strategy involves purchasing bonds that:","choices":{"A":"Mature at staggered intervals over many years","B":"All mature at approximately the same date","C":"Are split between short-term and long-term only","D":"Are all zero-coupon bonds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A bullet strategy concentrates bond maturities around a single target date. All bonds mature at approximately the same time, which is useful when an investor has a specific future liability or cash need at that date.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-010","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Churning occurs when a representative engages in:","choices":{"A":"Trading only in suitable securities","B":"Excessive trading to generate commissions regardless of client objectives","C":"Unauthorized trading that results in profits","D":"Trading only when market conditions are favorable"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Churning is excessive trading in a client's account primarily to generate commissions for the representative, without regard to the client's investment objectives. It is a prohibited practice under securities laws and fiduciary standards.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiduciary-duty","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-011","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A firm that buys and sells securities for its own account and risk is acting as a:","choices":{"A":"Broker","B":"Dealer","C":"Agent","D":"Investment adviser"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A dealer trades securities for its own account (as principal), buying from and selling to customers from its own inventory. This is distinguished from a broker, who acts as an agent facilitating trades between other parties.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which of the following has NO minimum net capital or net worth requirement?","choices":{"A":"Broker-dealers","B":"Investment advisers with custody","C":"Agents","D":"Investment advisers with discretion"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Agents (individual representatives of broker-dealers or issuers) have no minimum net capital or net worth requirements. Financial requirements apply to the firms they represent (broker-dealers and investment advisers), not to individual agents.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-013","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser charges a fee that might be considered excessive. Under what circumstances could this be permissible?","choices":{"A":"Never - excessive fees are always prohibited","B":"If the fee is fully disclosed and the client consents","C":"Only if the client is an accredited investor","D":"Only if approved by the state administrator"},"answer":"B","explanation":"While advisers should charge reasonable fees, fees that might seem high can be permissible if they are fully disclosed to the client and the client provides informed consent. Full disclosure allows clients to make educated decisions about whether to pay the fee.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-014","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When an investment adviser uses third-party research in making recommendations, the adviser must:","choices":{"A":"Never use outside research","B":"Disclose that the research is from a third party","C":"Obtain SEC approval for each research report","D":"Only use research from affiliated companies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investment advisers using third-party research must disclose this fact to clients. Clients have the right to know whether recommendations are based on the adviser's own analysis or on external research sources.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-015","section":"Economics","stem":"A product with elastic demand would experience which effect when its price increases?","choices":{"A":"Demand increases proportionally","B":"Demand decreases more than proportionally to the price increase","C":"Demand remains unchanged","D":"Supply decreases"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Elastic demand means that quantity demanded is highly sensitive to price changes. When price increases, demand falls by a greater percentage than the price increase. Luxury items and goods with many substitutes typically have elastic demand.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-016","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 62-year-old takes a distribution from their traditional IRA. How is this distribution taxed?","choices":{"A":"Tax-free","B":"As ordinary income only","C":"As capital gains","D":"As ordinary income plus 10% penalty"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Distributions from a traditional IRA after age 59 1/2 are taxed as ordinary income. There is no 10% early withdrawal penalty since the account holder is past the penalty age threshold. The distribution is not tax-free because contributions were made with pre-tax dollars.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-017","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"When a broker-dealer purchases securities from a customer at a price below the prevailing market price, the difference is called a:","choices":{"A":"Commission","B":"Markup","C":"Markdown","D":"Spread"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A markdown occurs when a dealer buys securities from a customer at a price below the current market price. The dealer profits by later selling at the higher market price. This is the opposite of a markup, which is charged when a dealer sells to a customer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["market-makers"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-018","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"The calculation of yield to maturity (YTM) considers all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Current market price","B":"Coupon payments","C":"Call price and call date","D":"Par value at maturity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Yield to maturity calculation uses the current market price, coupon payments, years to maturity, and par (redemption) value at maturity. Call price and call date are used to calculate yield to call (YTC), not YTM.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-019","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Variable life insurance is often recommended for clients seeking protection against which risk?","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Inflation risk","C":"Liquidity risk","D":"Political risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Variable life insurance offers protection against inflation risk because the cash value is invested in separate accounts (similar to mutual funds) that can grow with the market. Unlike whole life with fixed returns, variable life has growth potential that may outpace inflation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-020","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"In a limited partnership, which party has unlimited liability for the debts and obligations of the partnership?","choices":{"A":"Limited partners","B":"General partner","C":"All partners equally","D":"No partner has unlimited liability"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The general partner in a limited partnership has unlimited liability, meaning they are personally responsible for all partnership debts and obligations. Limited partners risk only their capital contributions and have no personal liability beyond that.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-021","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an investment adviser representative's registration automatically transfers with the adviser when:","choices":{"A":"The IAR moves to any new firm","B":"The IAR is a manager or supervisor at the new firm","C":"The state administrator approves the transfer","D":"Registration never transfers automatically"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the USA, automatic registration transfer occurs only for investment adviser representatives who will be managers or supervisors at the new advisory firm. Others must re-register separately.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-022","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, an investment adviser may charge performance-based fees to a client who:","choices":{"A":"Has any amount invested with the adviser","B":"Has at least $500,000 in assets under management","C":"Has at least $1.4 million invested with the adviser","D":"Is over 65 years old"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SEC permits performance-based fees only for a qualified client. Effective June 29, 2026 a qualified client is an individual with at least $1.4 million in assets under management with the adviser, OR a net worth exceeding $2.7 million (excluding primary residence). These thresholds are adjusted for inflation every five years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-023","section":"Economics","stem":"According to demand-side (Keynesian) economic theory, what action should the government take during a recession?","choices":{"A":"Decrease government spending","B":"Increase government spending","C":"Raise interest rates","D":"Increase taxes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Demand-side (Keynesian) economics advocates increasing government spending during recessions to stimulate aggregate demand. This creates jobs, puts money in consumers' pockets, and helps restart economic growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-024","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"American Depositary Receipts (ADRs) that trade on major U.S. exchanges must:","choices":{"A":"Be exempt from all U.S. securities regulations","B":"Be registered with the SEC","C":"Only trade in the foreign company's home country","D":"Be sponsored by the Federal Reserve"},"answer":"B","explanation":"ADRs traded on major U.S. exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ) must be registered with the SEC and comply with U.S. securities laws, including periodic reporting requirements. This provides American investors with regulatory protections.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-025","section":"Economics","stem":"Real GDP is measured in constant dollars in order to:","choices":{"A":"Include the effects of inflation","B":"Remove the effects of inflation","C":"Measure only government spending","D":"Track stock market performance"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Real GDP uses constant dollars (a fixed base year) to remove the effects of inflation, allowing for accurate comparison of economic output across different time periods. Nominal GDP includes inflation and can be misleading.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-026","section":"Suitability","stem":"Common stock investments are MOST suitable for investors with:","choices":{"A":"Short-term time horizons of less than one year","B":"Immediate liquidity needs","C":"Longer time horizons to ride out market volatility","D":"No tolerance for any risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Common stocks are subject to market volatility and short-term price fluctuations. Investors with longer time horizons can ride out market downturns and benefit from the historical long-term growth potential of equities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-027","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investor realizes a capital gain when:","choices":{"A":"The market value of a security increases while still held","B":"Sales proceeds exceed the cost basis upon sale","C":"Dividends are received from a stock holding","D":"Interest is received from a bond holding"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A capital gain is realized when an investor sells a security for more than its cost basis (original purchase price plus adjustments). Unrealized gains (price appreciation while still holding) are not taxable until the security is sold.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-028","section":"Options","stem":"A call option with a strike price of $50 when the stock is trading at $58 has an intrinsic value of:","choices":{"A":"$0","B":"$8","C":"$50","D":"$58"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Intrinsic value for a call option equals the stock price minus the strike price, when positive. With a $50 strike and $58 stock price: $58 - $50 = $8 intrinsic value. The call is $8 in-the-money.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing","call-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-029","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Information Filed with the SEC through EDGAR is available to:","choices":{"A":"Only SEC enforcement staff","B":"Only institutional investors","C":"The general public","D":"Only the issuing company's officers"},"answer":"C","explanation":"EDGAR (Electronic Data Gathering, Analysis, and Retrieval) is the SEC's public database where company filings are made available to the general public. Anyone can access SEC filings through EDGAR at no cost.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec","securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-030","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A high-income investor in the 37% federal tax bracket seeking diversified tax-advantaged income would be BEST served by:","choices":{"A":"Corporate bond fund","B":"Treasury bond fund","C":"Municipal bond fund","D":"High-yield bond fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Municipal bond funds provide tax-exempt income at the federal level (and often state level for in-state bonds), making them most beneficial for high-income investors in high tax brackets. The tax savings are worth more when the investor's marginal rate is higher.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-031","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A broker-dealer must register in a state if it:","choices":{"A":"Has its headquarters in that state only","B":"Has any place of business in that state","C":"Only trades government securities in that state","D":"Only serves institutional clients in that state"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, a broker-dealer must register in any state where it has a place of business. Having an office location triggers registration requirements, regardless of the types of securities traded or clients served.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-032","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Liquidity risk is generally NOT a major concern for:","choices":{"A":"Real estate investments","B":"Private placement securities","C":"Exchange-listed securities","D":"Limited partnership interests"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Exchange-listed securities trade on public markets with many buyers and sellers, providing high liquidity. Investors can typically buy or sell quickly at prices close to the quoted market price. Other investments like real estate, private placements, and LPs have limited secondary markets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-033","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A stock with a beta of 1.2 relative to the S&P 500 would be expected to:","choices":{"A":"Move in the opposite direction of the market","B":"Move in the same direction as the market, but with greater volatility","C":"Be unaffected by market movements","D":"Always outperform the market"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A positive beta indicates the stock moves in the same direction as the market. A beta of 1.2 means the stock is 20% more volatile than the market - if the market rises 10%, the stock would be expected to rise 12%; if the market falls 10%, the stock would fall 12%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-034","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"According to Modern Portfolio Theory, diversification is effective at reducing:","choices":{"A":"Systematic risk (market risk)","B":"Non-systematic risk (unsystematic risk)","C":"All investment risk","D":"Interest rate risk only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Modern Portfolio Theory holds that diversification reduces non-systematic (unsystematic) risk, which is company-specific or industry-specific risk. Systematic risk (market risk) cannot be eliminated through diversification because it affects all securities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-035","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investor seeking to benchmark their international equity portfolio would MOST appropriately use the:","choices":{"A":"S&P 500 Index","B":"MSCI EAFE Index","C":"Dow Jones Industrial Average","D":"Russell 2000 Index"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The MSCI EAFE (Europe, Australasia, Far East) Index is the standard benchmark for international developed market equities, excluding the U.S. and Canada. It is appropriate for measuring international equity portfolio performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-036","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following investments would be MOST suitable for a speculative investor with high risk tolerance?","choices":{"A":"U.S. Treasury bonds","B":"Investment-grade corporate bonds","C":"Leveraged ETFs","D":"Money market funds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Leveraged ETFs use derivatives and debt to amplify returns (and losses), making them highly speculative instruments suitable only for investors with high risk tolerance and short-term trading objectives.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","etfs"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-037","section":"Economics","stem":"A balance sheet presents a company's:","choices":{"A":"Revenue and expenses for a period","B":"Cash inflows and outflows for a period","C":"Assets, liabilities, and shareholders' equity at a point in time","D":"Projected future earnings"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A balance sheet is a snapshot showing a company's financial position at a specific point in time, listing assets, liabilities, and shareholders' equity (net worth). The fundamental equation is: Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-038","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company has earnings per share of $4.00 and pays an annual dividend of $1.00 per share. What is the dividend payout ratio?","choices":{"A":"4%","B":"25%","C":"75%","D":"400%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The dividend payout ratio is calculated as annual dividend per share divided by earnings per share: $1.00 / $4.00 = 0.25 or 25%. This means the company pays out 25% of its earnings as dividends.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-039","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"The PRIMARY risk of investing in bonds issued by a start-up company is:","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Reinvestment risk","C":"Credit/default risk","D":"Currency risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The primary risk of start-up company bonds is credit or default risk - the risk that the company will be unable to make interest payments or repay principal. Start-ups have unproven business models and uncertain cash flows.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-040","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Active portfolio management would be MOST appropriate for an investor who believes:","choices":{"A":"Markets are perfectly efficient","B":"It is impossible to outperform the market consistently","C":"Skilled managers can identify mispriced securities","D":"Index funds are always the best choice"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Active management is based on the belief that skilled managers can identify mispriced securities and generate returns exceeding the market (alpha). Investors who believe in market inefficiencies and manager skill would prefer active management.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-041","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Using discounted cash flow analysis, which investment is MOST attractive?","choices":{"A":"Project A with NPV of -$10,000","B":"Project B with NPV of $0","C":"Project C with NPV of $25,000","D":"Project D with NPV of $15,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In discounted cash flow analysis, the investment with the highest positive Net Present Value (NPV) is most attractive because it creates the most value above the required return. Project C with $25,000 NPV creates the most value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-042","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under securities laws, which securities may be legally offered to the public?","choices":{"A":"Only securities registered with the SEC","B":"Only exempt securities","C":"Securities that are either registered or exempt","D":"Any security regardless of registration status"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Securities laws require that securities offered to the public must either be registered with the SEC or qualify for an exemption from registration. Offering unregistered, non-exempt securities is a violation of securities laws.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-043","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"When interest rates rise, what happens to the value of both individual bonds and bond mutual funds?","choices":{"A":"Both increase in value","B":"Individual bonds decrease, but fund values increase","C":"Both decrease in value","D":"Neither is affected by interest rate changes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When interest rates rise, bond prices fall (inverse relationship). This affects both individual bonds and bond mutual funds because fund NAV is based on the market value of the bonds held. Rising rates reduce the value of existing bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["interest-rates","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-044","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"When a firm executes a securities transaction as a broker, it earns:","choices":{"A":"A markup","B":"A markdown","C":"A commission","D":"A spread"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When acting as a broker (agent), a firm facilitates transactions between buyers and sellers without taking ownership of the securities. Brokers earn commissions for their agency services. Markups and markdowns are earned when acting as dealer (principal).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p-045","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock with a low price-to-book ratio may indicate that the stock is:","choices":{"A":"Overvalued relative to its assets","B":"Undervalued relative to its assets","C":"A growth stock with high expectations","D":"Trading at a premium to net asset value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A low price-to-book ratio suggests the stock is trading at a low price relative to the company's book value (net assets). This may indicate the stock is undervalued, making it potentially attractive to value investors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-003","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A credit spread measures the difference between yields on:","choices":{"A":"Short-term and long-term Treasury securities","B":"Corporate bonds and comparable-maturity government securities","C":"Municipal bonds and federal tax rates","D":"Preferred stock dividends and common stock dividends"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A credit spread (yield spread) measures the difference between the yield on a corporate bond and a risk-free government security of similar maturity. It represents the additional yield investors demand for taking on credit risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields","corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-009","section":"Economics","stem":"Under accrual accounting, revenue is recognized when:","choices":{"A":"Cash is received","B":"The goods or services are delivered","C":"The invoice is sent","D":"The contract is signed"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Accrual accounting recognizes revenue when it is earned (goods delivered or services performed), regardless of when cash is received. This differs from cash-basis accounting, which records revenue when cash is actually received.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-013","section":"Economics","stem":"The MOST favorable audit opinion a company can receive on its financial statements is:","choices":{"A":"Qualified opinion","B":"Unqualified (clean) opinion","C":"Adverse opinion","D":"Disclaimer of opinion"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An unqualified (clean) opinion is the best audit opinion, indicating the financial statements present fairly, in all material respects, the company's financial position in accordance with GAAP.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-014","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under SEC recordkeeping rules, which storage medium is generally NOT acceptable for books and records?","choices":{"A":"Write-once, read-many (WORM) technology","B":"Rewritable optical discs","C":"Microfilm","D":"Magnetic tape with proper controls"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Rewritable media is generally not acceptable because records could be altered without detection. SEC Rule 17a-4 requires non-rewritable, non-erasable storage (WORM technology) to ensure record integrity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-021","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A Canadian broker-dealer may obtain limited registration in the United States primarily to serve:","choices":{"A":"Any U.S. resident","B":"Canadian citizens temporarily residing in the U.S.","C":"Institutional investors only","D":"State government pension plans"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SEC Rule 15a-6 and related provisions allow Canadian broker-dealers to obtain limited registration to continue servicing Canadian clients who temporarily relocate to the United States, facilitating cross-border continuity of service.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-025","section":"Suitability","stem":"When presenting a high-risk investment strategy to a client, a solicitor MUST ensure the client:","choices":{"A":"Has at least $1 million in assets","B":"Understands and can tolerate the risks involved","C":"Is an accredited investor","D":"Signs a waiver of liability"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Solicitors (and all securities professionals) must ensure that high-risk strategies are appropriate for the client's risk tolerance, investment objectives, and financial situation. The client must understand and be willing to accept the risks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-028","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An interval fund that offers to repurchase shares from investors may charge a maximum repurchase fee of:","choices":{"A":"1%","B":"2%","C":"3%","D":"5%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Interval funds may charge a repurchase fee of up to 2% to cover the costs of the repurchase offer. This fee compensates the fund for providing periodic liquidity in otherwise illiquid investments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["closed-end-funds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-030","section":"Risk Return","stem":"According to the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), the expected return of a security is determined by:","choices":{"A":"Only the security's total risk","B":"The risk-free rate plus a premium for systematic risk (beta)","C":"Historical returns and volatility","D":"The company's dividend yield"},"answer":"B","explanation":"CAPM calculates expected return as: Risk-free rate + Beta x (Market return - Risk-free rate). It uses systematic risk (beta) only, assuming unsystematic risk can be diversified away.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-035","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Before a state securities administrator can revoke a registration, they MUST provide:","choices":{"A":"Only written notice","B":"A public announcement","C":"Prior notice, opportunity for hearing, and written findings of fact","D":"Approval from the SEC"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Due process requires that before taking punitive action (like revocation), the administrator must provide prior notice, an opportunity for a hearing, and written findings of fact and conclusions of law.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-036","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A private foundation differs from a public charity primarily in that it:","choices":{"A":"Cannot make charitable donations","B":"Is typically funded by a single source and controlled by a board","C":"Is exempt from all IRS regulations","D":"Must distribute 100% of assets annually"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Private foundations are typically funded by a single individual, family, or corporation and controlled by a board that makes grants to other charitable organizations. Public charities receive funding from multiple sources.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-038","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an agent must be registered in:","choices":{"A":"Only the state where the broker-dealer is headquartered","B":"The state where the client resides","C":"All 50 states regardless of where they do business","D":"Only the state where the agent resides"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the USA, an agent must be registered in any state where they conduct business, which includes the state where the client resides. Registration follows where the client is located.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-039","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Net Present Value (NPV) is calculated as:","choices":{"A":"Future value minus present value","B":"Present value of cash flows minus initial investment cost","C":"Initial investment divided by annual cash flows","D":"Total cash flows divided by discount rate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"NPV equals the present value of all future cash flows (discounted at the required rate of return) minus the initial investment cost. A positive NPV indicates the investment exceeds the required return.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p2-042","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"To receive long-term capital gains treatment on incentive stock options (ISOs), the shares must be held for at least:","choices":{"A":"6 months after the grant date","B":"1 year after exercise and 2 years after grant","C":"1 year after the grant date only","D":"2 years after exercise"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For ISOs to qualify for long-term capital gains treatment, shares must be held for at least 1 year after the exercise date AND 2 years after the grant date. If sold earlier, the gain is taxed as ordinary income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-001","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor's fixed annuity pays $2,000 monthly. Over the past year, the Consumer Price Index (CPI) has increased by 5%. What type of risk has most significantly impacted this investor?","choices":{"A":"Credit risk","B":"Purchasing power risk","C":"Liquidity risk","D":"Reinvestment risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Purchasing power risk (inflation risk) occurs when rising prices erode the real value of fixed payments. A 5% CPI increase means the investor's $2,000 payment now buys approximately 5% less goods and services than it did a year ago. Fixed income investments are particularly vulnerable to this risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-002","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A company has current assets of $500,000 and current liabilities of $300,000. What is the company's net working capital?","choices":{"A":"$100,000","B":"$200,000","C":"$300,000","D":"$800,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Net working capital is calculated as Current Assets minus Current Liabilities. $500,000 - $300,000 = $200,000. This metric measures a company's short-term liquidity and its ability to meet near-term obligations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser representative wants to receive commissions on mutual fund sales in addition to providing investment advice for fees. What registration is required?","choices":{"A":"Only IAR registration is needed","B":"Only agent registration is needed","C":"Both IAR registration and agent registration with a broker-dealer","D":"No registration is required for commission-based sales"},"answer":"C","explanation":"To receive advice-based fees, a person must be registered as an IAR. To receive transaction-based commissions, a person must also be registered as an agent of a broker-dealer. Dual registration allows the individual to receive both types of compensation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is a limitation of S corporation status?","choices":{"A":"S corporations face double taxation","B":"S corporations are limited to a maximum of 100 shareholders","C":"S corporations cannot distribute dividends","D":"S corporations must have at least 25 shareholders"},"answer":"B","explanation":"S corporations are limited to a maximum of 100 shareholders. This limitation distinguishes them from C corporations, which can have unlimited shareholders. S corps benefit from pass-through taxation but must meet strict eligibility requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-005","section":"Options","stem":"A customer opened an options account and received the Options Disclosure Document (ODD). The signed options agreement has not been returned within 15 days. What trading activity is permitted?","choices":{"A":"All options trading activity is permitted","B":"Only closing transactions are permitted","C":"No options trading is permitted","D":"Only covered call writing is permitted"},"answer":"B","explanation":"If the signed options agreement is not returned within 15 days of account approval, only closing transactions are permitted. The customer cannot open new options positions until the agreement is returned. This protects both the customer and the firm.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under a bank networking arrangement with a broker-dealer, which disclosure is NOT required?","choices":{"A":"Securities sold are not FDIC insured","B":"Securities may lose value","C":"The broker-dealer will hedge all customer positions","D":"Securities are not bank deposits"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Networking arrangements require disclosure that securities are not FDIC insured, not bank deposits, and may lose value. There is no requirement to disclose that positions will be hedged - in fact, broker-dealers typically do not hedge retail customer positions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Commercial paper is typically NOT sold to which type of investor?","choices":{"A":"Money market mutual funds","B":"Corporate treasurers","C":"Individual retail investors","D":"Pension funds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Commercial paper is a short-term debt instrument typically sold in high denominations ($100,000+) to institutional investors such as money market funds, pension funds, and corporate treasurers. Individual retail investors are generally excluded due to the high minimum investment requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-008","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which characteristic distinguishes forward contracts from exchange-traded futures?","choices":{"A":"Forward contracts trade on centralized exchanges","B":"Forward contracts have standardized terms","C":"Forward contracts are customized OTC agreements with counterparty risk","D":"Forward contracts require daily margin settlement"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Forward contracts are customized over-the-counter (OTC) agreements between two parties with specific terms negotiated for each contract. Unlike futures, forwards are not standardized, do not trade on exchanges, and carry counterparty risk since there is no clearinghouse guarantee.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-009","section":"Economics","stem":"The Federal Reserve wants to stimulate economic growth during a recession. Which action would the Fed MOST likely take?","choices":{"A":"Raise the discount rate","B":"Sell Treasury securities in open market operations","C":"Lower reserve requirements for banks","D":"Increase margin requirements"},"answer":"C","explanation":"To stimulate growth, the Fed uses expansionary monetary policy by loosening the money supply. Lowering reserve requirements allows banks to lend more money, increasing the money supply and stimulating economic activity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","frb"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under current law (SECURE 2.0), which retirement account is subject to required minimum distributions (RMDs) during the owner's lifetime?","choices":{"A":"Roth IRA","B":"Roth 401(k)","C":"Neither Roth IRA nor Roth 401(k)","D":"Both Roth IRA and Roth 401(k)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Neither. Roth IRAs have never required lifetime RMDs, and beginning in 2024 SECURE 2.0 eliminated lifetime RMDs from designated Roth accounts in employer plans (Roth 401(k), Roth 403(b), governmental Roth 457(b)). Before 2024, Roth 401(k)s were subject to RMDs unless rolled to a Roth IRA; that is no longer the case.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-011","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"When analyzing a company's balance sheet, accounts payable is classified as a:","choices":{"A":"Current asset","B":"Long-term liability","C":"Current liability","D":"Stockholders' equity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Accounts payable represents money owed to suppliers and vendors for goods and services received but not yet paid for. Since these are typically due within one year, accounts payable is classified as a current liability on the balance sheet.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser wants to charge performance-based (fulcrum) fees to a client. What qualification must the client meet?","choices":{"A":"Net worth of at least $500,000","B":"Assets under management of at least $1.4 million OR net worth of at least $2.7 million","C":"Annual income of at least $200,000","D":"At least 5 years of investment experience"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under SEC and NASAA rules, performance-based (fulcrum) fees may be charged only to a qualified client. Effective June 29, 2026 the inflation-adjusted thresholds are at least $1.4 million in assets under management with the adviser OR a net worth of at least $2.7 million (excluding primary residence). The prior thresholds were $1.1 million / $2.2 million.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-013","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is NOT required to be disclosed on Form U-4?","choices":{"A":"Residential history for the past 5 years","B":"Employment history for the past 10 years","C":"Education history and degrees obtained","D":"Criminal history and regulatory actions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Form U-4 does not require education history or degrees. It requires disclosure of residential history, employment history, criminal history, regulatory actions, customer complaints, bankruptcies, and other financial/regulatory matters.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-014","section":"Options","stem":"What is the correct sequence for opening an options account?","choices":{"A":"Options agreement, ODD delivery, new account form, principal approval","B":"New account form, ODD delivery, principal approval, options agreement","C":"Principal approval, new account form, options agreement, ODD delivery","D":"ODD delivery, options agreement, new account form, principal approval"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct sequence is: (1) New account form completed, (2) Options Disclosure Document (ODD) delivered, (3) Principal/supervisor approves account for options trading, (4) Options agreement signed and returned by customer. This sequence ensures proper documentation and approval.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-015","section":"Economics","stem":"Which type of tax is the federal estate tax?","choices":{"A":"Regressive tax","B":"Flat tax","C":"Progressive tax","D":"Proportional tax"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The federal estate tax is a progressive tax. Larger estates face higher marginal tax rates, and there is an exemption amount below which no estate tax is owed. This means the tax burden increases disproportionately as estate value increases.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-016","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A person solicits pre-organization subscriptions for securities that will be offered to 15 retail investors. Is this person required to register as an agent?","choices":{"A":"No, pre-organization subscriptions are always exempt","B":"No, if no commissions are received","C":"Yes, because offers are being made to more than 10 non-institutional persons","D":"Yes, but only if the total offering exceeds $5 million"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The agent exclusion for pre-organization subscriptions only applies when offers are made to 10 or fewer persons. Since 15 retail investors are being solicited, this exclusion does not apply, and the person must register as an agent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-018","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"When opening a trust account, which additional documentation is required beyond standard new account forms?","choices":{"A":"Only the trustee's personal financial statement","B":"A copy of the trust document or certification of trust","C":"Letters of testamentary from probate court","D":"Beneficiary death certificates"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Trust accounts require a copy of the trust document or a certification of trust that specifies the trustee's powers, the beneficiaries, and any restrictions on investments. This supplemental documentation verifies the trustee's authority to act.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-019","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Congress passes new legislation that significantly increases taxes on a specific industry. Investors in that industry face which type of risk?","choices":{"A":"Market risk","B":"Interest rate risk","C":"Legislative risk","D":"Currency risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Legislative risk is the risk that government actions, such as new laws or regulations, will negatively impact investments. When Congress passes laws affecting a specific industry, investors in that industry face legislative risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-020","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which entity meets the definition of a broker-dealer?","choices":{"A":"A bank offering deposit accounts","B":"A person engaged in effecting securities transactions for its own account or for others","C":"An issuer selling only its own securities","D":"An agent selling securities for a single broker-dealer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A broker-dealer is any person engaged in the business of effecting securities transactions for its own account (dealer) or for the accounts of others (broker). Banks are excluded from this definition, and issuers selling their own securities are not considered broker-dealers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-021","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A retired client's primary investment objective is safety of principal. Which portfolio allocation is MOST appropriate?","choices":{"A":"80% growth stocks, 20% bonds","B":"60% small-cap stocks, 40% commodities","C":"70% Treasury securities and high-grade bonds, 30% blue-chip stocks","D":"100% sector-specific ETFs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Safety of principal requires focusing on conservative investments that preserve capital. A portfolio weighted toward Treasury securities and high-grade bonds (70%) with some blue-chip stocks (30%) for modest growth and inflation protection provides the appropriate balance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-022","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"According to modern portfolio theory, portfolio risk is most effectively reduced by adding assets that have:","choices":{"A":"High positive correlation with existing holdings","B":"Low or negative correlation with existing holdings","C":"The highest expected returns","D":"The lowest individual volatility"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Modern portfolio theory emphasizes that diversification benefits come from combining assets with low or negative correlation. When assets move independently or in opposite directions, the overall portfolio volatility is reduced more than with highly correlated assets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-023","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which document describes the terms of a margin loan including interest charges and collateral requirements?","choices":{"A":"New account form","B":"Customer agreement","C":"Credit agreement","D":"Options disclosure document"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The credit agreement (also called the margin agreement) describes the terms under which the broker-dealer extends credit, including interest rates, how interest is calculated, collateral requirements, and the firm's right to sell securities if equity falls below maintenance levels.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-024","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A financial professional executes securities transactions on behalf of clients and is compensated through commissions on each trade. This person is acting as a:","choices":{"A":"Dealer","B":"Broker","C":"Investment adviser","D":"Issuer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A broker executes transactions for the accounts of others and is typically compensated through commissions charged on each transaction. Unlike a dealer who trades for their own account, a broker acts as an intermediary between buyers and sellers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-025","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Using the Rule of 72, approximately how many years will it take an investment earning 8% annually to double in value?","choices":{"A":"6 years","B":"8 years","C":"9 years","D":"12 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Rule of 72 estimates doubling time by dividing 72 by the annual interest rate. At 8% annually: 72 / 8 = 9 years. This quick calculation helps estimate compound growth without complex mathematics.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-026","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which statement about Roth IRA eligibility is correct?","choices":{"A":"There are no income limits for Roth IRA contributions","B":"Only self-employed individuals can contribute to Roth IRAs","C":"Contributors must have earned income, and contribution limits phase out at higher income levels","D":"Roth IRAs are only available to those age 50 and older"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Roth IRA contributions require earned income (wages, self-employment income), and contribution eligibility phases out at higher modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) levels. High earners may be completely ineligible or face reduced contribution limits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-027","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"What document formally establishes a limited partnership as a legal business entity?","choices":{"A":"Subscription agreement","B":"Certificate of limited partnership","C":"Partnership prospectus","D":"Operating agreement"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The certificate of limited partnership is filed with the state to formally establish the limited partnership as a legal entity. It contains basic information about the partnership, including its name, address, and the identity of the general partner.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-028","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which risk is MOST significant for investors in Ginnie Mae (GNMA) pass-through securities?","choices":{"A":"Credit risk","B":"Currency risk","C":"Reinvestment risk","D":"Liquidity risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"GNMA pass-through securities have significant reinvestment risk because homeowners can prepay their mortgages at any time, especially when interest rates fall. This returns principal early, forcing investors to reinvest at lower prevailing rates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-029","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is NOT required to be disclosed to clients of a fee-based advisory account?","choices":{"A":"The advisory fee schedule","B":"Any conflicts of interest","C":"Disciplinary history of the adviser","D":"Guaranteed investment performance"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Investment advisers cannot guarantee performance and thus cannot disclose \"guaranteed performance.\" Required disclosures include fee schedules, conflicts of interest, disciplinary history, and investment strategies. Guaranteeing returns is prohibited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-030","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under Regulation D private placement rules, how many accredited investors may participate in an offering?","choices":{"A":"Maximum of 35 accredited investors","B":"Maximum of 100 accredited investors","C":"Unlimited accredited investors","D":"Maximum of 500 accredited investors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Regulation D allows unlimited accredited investors to participate in a private placement. The limit of 35 applies only to non-accredited sophisticated investors (under Rule 506(b)). Accredited investors are presumed capable of evaluating investment risks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-031","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, an investment adviser representative can charge performance-based compensation if they have been employed by the adviser for at least:","choices":{"A":"6 months","B":"1 year","C":"2 years","D":"5 years"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To charge performance-based fees, an IAR must have been employed by the investment adviser for at least 12 months (1 year), in addition to meeting other requirements such as the client qualifying as a \"qualified client.\"","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-032","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio manager temporarily overweights technology stocks based on short-term market expectations while maintaining a long-term target allocation. This strategy is called:","choices":{"A":"Strategic asset allocation","B":"Tactical asset allocation","C":"Constant ratio allocation","D":"Buy and hold"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Tactical asset allocation involves making short-term deviations from the strategic (long-term) asset allocation to capitalize on market opportunities. The manager maintains a long-term target but temporarily adjusts weights based on market conditions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-033","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A subsidiary company issues bonds that are guaranteed by its parent company. How are these bonds typically rated by credit agencies?","choices":{"A":"Based on the subsidiary's standalone credit quality","B":"Based on the credit quality of the parent company (guarantor)","C":"Based on the average of both companies' ratings","D":"Guaranteed bonds are not rated"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When bonds are guaranteed by a parent company, credit rating agencies typically rate the bonds based on the credit quality of the guarantor (parent company), since the parent is responsible for payment if the subsidiary defaults.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-034","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An adviser states to a client: \"This bond is guaranteed by the parent company, which means the parent will make principal and interest payments if the issuer defaults.\" Is this statement prohibited?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because guaranteeing any security performance is prohibited","B":"Yes, because only government securities can be guaranteed","C":"No, this accurately describes a guaranteed bond structure","D":"No, but only if the parent company is investment-grade rated"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Stating that a bond is guaranteed by another entity is not prohibited when it accurately describes the bond's structure. The prohibition is against guaranteeing investment returns or protecting against losses. A parent company guarantee is a factual feature of certain bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-035","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A broker-dealer files for initial state registration on October 1. Which statements are TRUE? I. A consent to service of process must be filed. II. Only a prorated fee is required. III. Registration is effective until December 31 of that year.","choices":{"A":"I and II only","B":"I and III only","C":"II and III only","D":"I, II, and III"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Initial BD registration requires a consent to service of process and is effective until December 31. However, a FULL year fee is typically required regardless of when during the year registration occurs - there is no prorated fee for initial registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-036","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer grants a non-durable power of attorney to their financial adviser. Under what circumstances does this authorization terminate?","choices":{"A":"Only upon the customer's death","B":"Upon the customer's death OR incapacitation","C":"Only after 5 years","D":"Only if revoked in writing by the customer"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A non-durable power of attorney terminates upon the principal's death OR incapacitation. \"Non-durable\" means it does not survive incapacity. A durable POA would continue despite incapacitation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-037","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A mutual fund prospectus must include performance returns for which time periods?","choices":{"A":"Only the most recent year","B":"1, 5, and 10 years (or since inception if shorter)","C":"Only 3 and 5 years","D":"Monthly returns for the past 12 months"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SEC regulations require mutual fund prospectuses to show standardized performance for 1, 5, and 10 year periods. If the fund has not existed for the full period, returns since inception are shown instead.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-039","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under NASAA Model Rules, a solicitor who receives compensation for referring clients to an investment adviser:","choices":{"A":"Must be registered as an IAR in all states where they solicit","B":"Must obtain administrator approval before soliciting","C":"Is not required to register as an IAR but must comply with solicitor disclosure requirements","D":"Must be an employee of the investment adviser"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Solicitors who refer clients for compensation are not required to register as IARs solely for referral activities. However, they must comply with solicitor rules including providing disclosures about their compensation arrangement and any conflicts of interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65p3-040","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under NASAA Model Rules, when must a person who solicits clients for an investment adviser register as an IAR?","choices":{"A":"Never - solicitors are always exempt from registration","B":"When the solicitor provides investment advice or has a place of business in the state","C":"Only if the solicitor receives more than $500 per referral","D":"Only if the investment adviser is SEC-registered"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under NASAA rules, a solicitor must register as an IAR if they provide any investment advice beyond mere referrals or if they have a place of business in the state. Simple referral activity without advice does not require IAR registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-001","section":"Options","stem":"The intrinsic value of a call option is calculated as:","choices":{"A":"Strike price minus market price of the underlying stock","B":"Market price of the underlying stock minus strike price","C":"Premium paid minus time value","D":"Time value plus extrinsic value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The intrinsic value of a call option is the amount by which the market price of the underlying stock exceeds the strike price (Market Price - Strike Price). If XYZ stock is trading at $55 and the call has a $50 strike, the intrinsic value is $5. Intrinsic value can never be negative; if the calculation results in a negative number, the intrinsic value is zero.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-pricing","call-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-002","section":"Options","stem":"Time value of an option is highest when the option is:","choices":{"A":"Deep in-the-money with little time to expiration","B":"At-the-money with significant time to expiration","C":"Deep out-of-the-money with little time to expiration","D":"In-the-money at expiration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Time value is highest for at-the-money options with significant time remaining until expiration. At-the-money options have the greatest uncertainty about whether they will expire in or out of the money, which creates the highest time value. More time until expiration means more opportunities for favorable price movement, increasing time value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-003","section":"Options","stem":"A covered call strategy is BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"Buying a call option without owning the underlying stock","B":"Selling a call option while owning the underlying stock","C":"Buying both a call and a put on the same stock","D":"Selling a put option on a stock you want to purchase"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A covered call involves owning shares of the underlying stock while simultaneously selling (writing) a call option on those shares. The position is \"covered\" because if the call is exercised, the investor already owns the shares to deliver. This strategy generates income from the premium received while limiting upside potential.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-strategies","call-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-004","section":"Options","stem":"Delta measures an option's sensitivity to changes in:","choices":{"A":"Time decay","B":"Implied volatility","C":"The price of the underlying asset","D":"Interest rates"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Delta measures how much an option's price will change for a $1 move in the underlying asset. A call with a delta of 0.50 will increase by $0.50 for every $1 increase in the stock price. Delta also approximates the probability that the option will expire in-the-money. Call options have positive deltas (0 to 1), while puts have negative deltas (0 to -1).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-005","section":"Options","stem":"Theta is negative for option buyers because:","choices":{"A":"Options become more valuable as expiration approaches","B":"Time decay erodes the option premium over time","C":"Volatility tends to decrease near expiration","D":"Interest rates typically fall during the option's life"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Theta represents time decay - the amount an option loses in value each day, all else being equal. For option buyers, theta is the \"enemy\" because it constantly erodes the value of their position. As expiration approaches, time decay accelerates. Option sellers benefit from positive theta because they profit from the premium decay.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-006","section":"Options","stem":"An investment adviser recommends a protective put strategy to a client. The primary purpose of this strategy is to:","choices":{"A":"Generate additional income from the stock position","B":"Limit downside risk while maintaining upside potential","C":"Reduce the cost basis of the stock position","D":"Take advantage of expected volatility increases"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A protective put involves buying a put option on a stock you own. It acts like insurance, establishing a floor price at which you can sell the stock regardless of how far it falls. Unlike a covered call, a protective put preserves unlimited upside potential while limiting downside risk to the difference between the current price and the strike price, plus the premium paid.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-007","section":"Options","stem":"A collar strategy combines:","choices":{"A":"A long call and a long put with the same strike price","B":"A short call and a short put with the same strike price","C":"A protective put and a covered call on the same stock position","D":"Two long calls at different strike prices"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A collar strategy involves owning the underlying stock, buying a protective put (to limit downside), and selling a covered call (to generate income that offsets the put cost). The put establishes a floor price while the call caps the upside. A \"zero-cost collar\" occurs when the call premium received equals the put premium paid.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-008","section":"Options","stem":"Vega is highest for options that are:","choices":{"A":"Deep in-the-money with short time to expiration","B":"At-the-money with long time to expiration","C":"Deep out-of-the-money regardless of time","D":"At expiration with high intrinsic value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Vega measures sensitivity to changes in implied volatility. At-the-money options with more time to expiration have the highest vega because they have the most time value, which is most affected by volatility changes. Deep in-the-money or out-of-the-money options have lower vega because their prices are dominated by intrinsic value or are near worthless.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-009","section":"Options","stem":"An investment adviser is considering covered call writing for a client's portfolio. This strategy would be MOST appropriate for a client who:","choices":{"A":"Expects the stock to appreciate significantly in the near term","B":"Seeks additional income and is willing to cap upside potential","C":"Wants maximum protection against a market decline","D":"Has a very aggressive risk tolerance and short time horizon"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Covered call writing is appropriate for investors seeking income generation who are willing to sacrifice some upside potential. The strategy works best when the stock is expected to remain relatively flat or rise modestly. The premium received provides some downside cushion but does not provide significant protection against major declines.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies","call-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-010","section":"Options","stem":"Gamma measures the rate of change in:","choices":{"A":"An option's price relative to time","B":"Delta relative to the underlying asset's price movement","C":"Implied volatility relative to market conditions","D":"The option's theta decay rate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Gamma measures how much an option's delta will change for a $1 move in the underlying asset. It is the \"delta of delta.\" Gamma is highest for at-the-money options near expiration. High gamma means delta can change rapidly, making the option's price movement less predictable. Gamma is always positive for long option positions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-011","section":"Options","stem":"A client holds 1,000 shares of XYZ stock currently trading at $50. The investment adviser recommends a zero-cost collar using a $45 put and a $55 call, both expiring in three months. If XYZ rises to $60 at expiration, what is the client's effective selling price per share?","choices":{"A":"$45","B":"$50","C":"$55","D":"$60"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a collar strategy, the short call caps the upside. If XYZ rises to $60, the $55 call will be exercised, requiring the client to sell at $55 per share. The put expires worthless (stock is above $45). Since this is a zero-cost collar, there is no net premium paid or received to adjust the effective price. The maximum profit is limited to the call strike price of $55.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","call-options","put-options"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-012","section":"Options","stem":"An investment adviser is evaluating options for a risk-averse client's portfolio. Which of the following positions has a risk/reward profile MOST suitable for this client?","choices":{"A":"Naked call writing on a volatile stock","B":"Protective put on an existing stock position","C":"Short straddle on an index","D":"Uncovered put writing on speculative stocks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A protective put is the most suitable strategy for a risk-averse client because it provides defined maximum loss (the put premium plus any loss down to the strike price) while preserving unlimited upside potential. It functions like insurance on the stock position. Naked call writing has unlimited risk, short straddles have substantial risk from large moves in either direction, and uncovered put writing exposes the client to significant losses if the stock drops substantially.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-opt-013","section":"Options","stem":"An option has a delta of 0.40, gamma of 0.05, and the underlying stock increases by $2. Assuming no other changes, the new delta will be approximately:","choices":{"A":"0.35","B":"0.45","C":"0.50","D":"0.80"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Gamma measures the change in delta for each $1 move in the underlying. With gamma of 0.05 and a $2 stock price increase, delta changes by 0.05 x 2 = 0.10. Starting with delta of 0.40 and adding 0.10 gives a new delta of approximately 0.50. This calculation assumes gamma remains constant, which is a simplification since gamma itself changes as the stock price moves.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-001","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock with a beta of 1.0 would be expected to:","choices":{"A":"Move twice as much as the overall market","B":"Move in the same direction and magnitude as the overall market","C":"Move in the opposite direction of the market","D":"Remain stable regardless of market movements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Beta measures a stock's volatility relative to the overall market. A beta of 1.0 means the stock is expected to move in the same direction and by the same percentage as the market. A beta greater than 1.0 indicates higher volatility than the market, while a beta less than 1.0 indicates lower volatility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-002","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following is a characteristic of common stock?","choices":{"A":"Guaranteed fixed dividend payments","B":"Voting rights on corporate matters","C":"Priority over bondholders in liquidation","D":"A fixed maturity date"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Common stockholders have voting rights, typically one vote per share, on major corporate matters such as electing the board of directors and approving mergers. Common stock dividends are not guaranteed, stockholders are last in liquidation priority, and stock has no maturity date.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-003","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"After a 2-for-1 stock split, an investor who owned 100 shares at $80 per share would have:","choices":{"A":"50 shares at $160 per share","B":"100 shares at $40 per share","C":"200 shares at $40 per share","D":"200 shares at $80 per share"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a 2-for-1 stock split, the number of shares doubles while the price per share is cut in half. The investor's total position value remains the same: 100 shares x $80 = $8,000 before split; 200 shares x $40 = $8,000 after split. Stock splits do not change the proportionate ownership or total value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-004","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company with a market capitalization between $2 billion and $10 billion would typically be classified as:","choices":{"A":"Large-cap","B":"Mid-cap","C":"Small-cap","D":"Micro-cap"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Market capitalization categories are generally defined as: Large-cap (over $10 billion), Mid-cap ($2-10 billion), Small-cap ($300 million to $2 billion), and Micro-cap (under $300 million). Mid-cap companies offer a balance between the stability of large-caps and the growth potential of small-caps.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-005","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE regarding American Depositary Receipts (ADRs)?","choices":{"A":"ADRs eliminate currency exchange risk for U.S. investors","B":"ADRs represent shares of foreign companies trading in U.S. markets","C":"Only sponsored ADRs can trade in the over-the-counter market","D":"ADRs always provide the same voting rights as the underlying shares"},"answer":"B","explanation":"ADRs are certificates issued by U.S. depositary banks representing shares of foreign companies. They allow U.S. investors to easily invest in foreign companies through U.S. exchanges. Although ADRs are denominated in U.S. dollars, they are still subject to currency exchange risk. Most ADRs do not provide voting rights, and unsponsored ADRs typically trade OTC while sponsored ADRs can be exchange-listed.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-006","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A fundamental analyst would be MOST likely to examine which of the following?","choices":{"A":"Trading volume patterns and moving averages","B":"Support and resistance levels on price charts","C":"Company earnings reports and balance sheets","D":"Short interest ratios and put/call ratios"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fundamental analysis focuses on evaluating a company's intrinsic value by examining financial statements, earnings, revenue, management quality, competitive position, and economic factors. Technical analysts, in contrast, focus on price patterns, volume, and market indicators like moving averages, support/resistance levels, and sentiment indicators like put/call ratios.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-007","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock has earnings per share of $4.00 and a current market price of $60. What is the price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio?","choices":{"A":"6.67","B":"15","C":"24","D":"240"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The P/E ratio is calculated by dividing the current stock price by earnings per share: $60 / $4.00 = 15. A P/E of 15 means investors are willing to pay $15 for every $1 of earnings. P/E ratios are commonly used to compare valuations between companies and assess whether a stock is over or undervalued relative to its peers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-008","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which type of preferred stock must pay all missed dividends before common stockholders receive any dividends?","choices":{"A":"Participating preferred","B":"Callable preferred","C":"Cumulative preferred","D":"Convertible preferred"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Cumulative preferred stock accumulates any unpaid dividends (called dividends in arrears). All accumulated dividends must be paid to cumulative preferred shareholders before any dividends can be paid to common stockholders. This provides additional protection for preferred shareholders.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-009","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A growth investor would MOST likely be attracted to a company that:","choices":{"A":"Pays high dividends and has a low P/E ratio","B":"Reinvests earnings for expansion and has above-average earnings growth","C":"Has a high dividend yield and trades below book value","D":"Has stable earnings and pays consistent dividends"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Growth investors seek companies with above-average earnings growth potential. These companies typically reinvest profits for expansion rather than paying dividends, often have higher P/E ratios reflecting growth expectations, and are found in rapidly expanding industries. Value investors, in contrast, seek undervalued stocks with lower P/E ratios and higher dividends.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-010","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Standard deviation measures which aspect of an investment?","choices":{"A":"The investment's correlation with the market","B":"The total volatility of returns around the average return","C":"The investment's sensitivity to interest rate changes","D":"The expected return based on systematic risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Standard deviation measures the total volatility (variability) of an investment's returns around its average return. A higher standard deviation indicates greater volatility and risk. Unlike beta, which measures systematic risk relative to the market, standard deviation captures total risk including both systematic and unsystematic risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-011","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"The dividend payout ratio is calculated by dividing:","choices":{"A":"Stock price by dividends per share","B":"Dividends per share by earnings per share","C":"Earnings per share by stock price","D":"Total dividends by total revenue"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The dividend payout ratio is calculated by dividing dividends per share by earnings per share (DPS/EPS). For example, if a company has EPS of $2.00 and pays $0.50 in dividends, the payout ratio is 25%. This ratio shows what percentage of earnings is distributed to shareholders versus retained for reinvestment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-012","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investment adviser is using the PEG ratio to evaluate stocks. A stock with a P/E of 20 and expected earnings growth of 10% would have a PEG ratio of:","choices":{"A":"0.5","B":"2.0","C":"30","D":"200"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The PEG (Price/Earnings-to-Growth) ratio is calculated by dividing the P/E ratio by the expected earnings growth rate: 20 / 10 = 2.0. A PEG ratio of 1.0 suggests fair valuation relative to growth. A PEG above 1.0 may indicate overvaluation, while below 1.0 may suggest undervaluation relative to the company's growth rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-013","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A technical analyst observes that the advance-decline line is declining while the major market index is making new highs. This divergence typically indicates:","choices":{"A":"Strong market breadth confirming the uptrend","B":"A potential market reversal or weakness ahead","C":"Institutional investors are heavily buying","D":"The market is oversold and due for a rally"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The advance-decline line measures market breadth by tracking the cumulative difference between advancing and declining stocks. When the market index rises but the advance-decline line falls, it indicates that fewer stocks are participating in the rally - a bearish divergence. This suggests the rally is narrow and may be unsustainable, often foreshadowing a market reversal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-014","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"When using discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis to value a stock, which factor would cause the present value to DECREASE?","choices":{"A":"An increase in expected future dividends","B":"A decrease in the discount rate used","C":"An increase in the discount rate used","D":"A longer holding period with the same cash flows"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In DCF analysis, present value equals future cash flows divided by (1 + discount rate)^n. An increase in the discount rate reduces the present value because future cash flows are discounted more heavily. Higher discount rates reflect greater risk or opportunity cost, making future cash flows worth less today. Conversely, higher expected cash flows or lower discount rates increase present value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s65-eq-015","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor holds floating rate preferred stock paying LIBOR + 2%. If LIBOR increases from 3% to 5%, what happens to the dividend and market price of this security?","choices":{"A":"Dividend increases; market price significantly decreases","B":"Dividend increases; market price remains relatively stable","C":"Dividend stays the same; market price decreases","D":"Dividend decreases; market price increases"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Floating rate preferred stock has dividends that adjust with a reference rate like LIBOR. When LIBOR rises from 3% to 5%, the dividend increases from 5% (3%+2%) to 7% (5%+2%). Because the dividend adjusts to market rates, the market price remains relatively stable - the security's yield automatically adjusts, so there's no need for price depreciation to raise yield. This is the key advantage of floating rate securities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv4","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An analyst is screening stocks and finds four companies with the following P/E ratios: Company A: 8.25, Company B: 18.50, Company C: 32.75, Company D: 45.20. Which company would MOST likely be considered a value stock?","choices":{"A":"Company A","B":"Company B","C":"Company C","D":"Company D"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Value stocks typically have lower P/E ratios, indicating the market is paying less per dollar of earnings. Company A with a P/E of 8.25 is trading at the lowest multiple of earnings, suggesting it may be undervalued relative to its earnings power.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv5","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A trustee governed by the Uniform Prudent Investor Act (UPIA) invests 5% of a trust's assets into a high-volatility emerging markets fund. The trust's overall risk profile remains consistent with its stated objectives. This action is:","choices":{"A":"Always prohibited under UPIA","B":"Permitted only with court approval","C":"Ethical, as the investment is evaluated in context of the total portfolio","D":"Unethical regardless of portfolio context"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under UPIA, the prudence of individual investments is evaluated in the context of the entire portfolio, not in isolation. A volatile investment may be appropriate if it represents a small portion of the portfolio and the overall risk level remains suitable for the trust's objectives.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["fiduciary-duty","diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv7","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following changes at an investment advisory firm would NOT constitute an assignment of an advisory contract requiring client consent?","choices":{"A":"Merger with another advisory firm","B":"Sale of the firm's assets to a new owner","C":"One of eight partners retiring from the firm","D":"Change in control to a new majority owner"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the Investment Advisers Act, a minority partner leaving a firm does not typically constitute an assignment requiring client consent, as it does not represent a change in control. Mergers, asset sales, and changes in majority ownership do require consent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv9","section":"Economics","stem":"When analyzing a company's balance sheet, which of the following would be classified as a current liability?","choices":{"A":"30-year mortgage payable","B":"Deferred tax liability due in 5 years","C":"Long-term bonds payable","D":"Accounts payable"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Current liabilities are obligations due within one year. Accounts payable (amounts owed to suppliers for goods/services) is typically due within 30-90 days, making it a current liability. Long-term debt and deferred taxes beyond one year are non-current liabilities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv10","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which statements about digital assets are TRUE? I. They may be subject to securities laws if they meet the Howey Test. II. All digital assets are guaranteed by the FDIC. III. They are traded on decentralized platforms without traditional intermediaries.","choices":{"A":"I and III only","B":"II only","C":"I, II, and III","D":"II and III only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Digital assets that meet the Howey Test (investment of money in common enterprise with expectation of profits from others' efforts) are subject to securities laws. Many digital assets trade on decentralized platforms. However, digital assets are NOT FDIC insured - this is a key risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv13","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which statement about American Depositary Receipts (ADRs) is accurate?","choices":{"A":"ADRs eliminate all currency risk","B":"ADRs always pay dividends in foreign currency","C":"ADRs represent ownership in foreign company shares held by a depositary bank","D":"ADRs are exempt from SEC registration requirements"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ADRs are receipts representing shares of foreign companies held by a U.S. depositary bank. They facilitate U.S. trading of foreign stocks. ADRs do NOT eliminate currency risk, pay dividends in U.S. dollars, and exchange-listed ADRs must be SEC registered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv14","section":"Suitability","stem":"A 28-year-old investor in the 32% federal tax bracket seeks current income with growth potential. An allocation of 25% to high-yield bonds and 75% to dividend growth stocks would be:","choices":{"A":"Unsuitable due to the client's age","B":"Unsuitable due to the tax bracket","C":"Suitable given the objectives and time horizon","D":"Unsuitable because high-yield bonds are too risky"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a young investor seeking income with growth potential, a blend of high-yield bonds (income) and dividend growth stocks (income + growth) is suitable. The long time horizon allows for recovery from volatility, and the allocation matches stated objectives.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv16","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An IAR wants to open a joint account with their adult nephew. What is required under securities regulations?","choices":{"A":"Written approval from the firm, signed agreement, and proportional profit/loss sharing","B":"Only verbal notification to the supervisor","C":"SEC pre-approval for all family joint accounts","D":"No special requirements for family members"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When an IAR opens a joint account with any person, including family members, they must obtain written approval from the employing firm, have a signed agreement with the family member, and share profits/losses proportionally to their contributions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv17","section":"Suitability","stem":"A 33-year-old moderate risk client has a balanced portfolio of growth stocks and investment-grade bonds. Which recommendation would be UNSUITABLE?","choices":{"A":"Maintaining the current allocation","B":"Adding international diversification","C":"Selling growth stocks to purchase speculative-grade bonds","D":"Increasing equity allocation slightly given age"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Selling growth stocks to buy speculative bonds concentrates risk in credit-sensitive assets while reducing growth potential. This increases portfolio risk inappropriately for a moderate-risk investor and reduces diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv18","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Investment advisers must provide clients with holdings reports that include all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Security names and quantities","B":"Current market values","C":"Projected future returns","D":"Account positions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Holdings reports must show actual positions including security names, quantities, and current market values. Projected future returns are speculative forecasts and are not required (and would be misleading) in holdings reports.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv20","section":"Suitability","stem":"A married couple receives an inheritance and plans to use the funds for a home down payment in 3-6 months. The MOST suitable investment for these funds is:","choices":{"A":"Aggressive growth mutual fund","B":"Money market fund","C":"Long-term corporate bonds","D":"Emerging market stocks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For funds needed within 3-6 months, capital preservation and liquidity are paramount. A money market fund provides stability, liquidity, and modest returns without risking the principal needed for the down payment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv22","section":"Economics","stem":"Which statements about S-Corporations are TRUE? I. Income passes through to shareholders. II. Limited to 100 shareholders. III. Subject to double taxation. IV. Can only have one class of stock.","choices":{"A":"I and III only","B":"II and III only","C":"I, II, and III only","D":"I, II, and IV only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"S-Corps have pass-through taxation (I), are limited to 100 shareholders (II), and can only have one class of stock (IV). They are NOT subject to double taxation - that's a C-Corp characteristic. S-Corps avoid corporate-level tax.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv24","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which statement about price ratios is CORRECT?","choices":{"A":"Price-to-book ratio is primarily used by fundamental analysts","B":"P/E ratio measures a company's debt levels","C":"Technical analysts rely heavily on P/B ratios","D":"P/E ratio has no relationship to earnings"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Price-to-book ratio is a fundamental analysis tool used to assess whether a stock is trading below or above its book value. P/E measures price relative to earnings (not debt), technical analysts focus on price patterns (not ratios), and P/E is directly tied to earnings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv25","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A self-employed consultant with no employees wants to maximize retirement contributions. Which plan allows the highest contribution limits?","choices":{"A":"Traditional IRA","B":"Solo 401(k)","C":"SEP-IRA with 10% contribution","D":"SIMPLE IRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A Solo 401(k) allows self-employed individuals to contribute as both employee (elective deferrals up to $23,000 in 2024, plus catch-up) AND employer (up to 25% of compensation), potentially exceeding $60,000 annually. This typically exceeds IRA, SEP, and SIMPLE limits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv26","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser representative makes an incorrect statement to a client regarding a security's past performance. Although the client subsequently earns a profit on the investment, this conduct is:","choices":{"A":"Acceptable because the client profited from the transaction","B":"Acceptable because no actual harm occurred","C":"Unethical and may expose the representative to civil and criminal liability","D":"Only a minor violation requiring a verbal warning"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Making false statements about securities is unethical and potentially illegal regardless of the outcome for the client. A profit does not excuse the misrepresentation. The adviser may face civil liability for fraud and criminal charges for willful violations of securities laws.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv27","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under securities laws, an exemption is BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"An ongoing, specific legal exception from certain regulatory requirements","B":"A temporary waiver granted by the SEC","C":"A one-time exclusion for first-time issuers","D":"A reduction in filing fees for small businesses"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An exemption is a legal exception that relieves certain securities, transactions, or persons from registration or other regulatory requirements. Once established, exemptions are ongoing (not temporary) and apply when specific criteria are met.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv28","section":"Risk Return","stem":"An investor wants to double their $20,000 investment over the next 12 years. Using the Rule of 72, what approximate annual rate of return is needed?","choices":{"A":"5%","B":"6%","C":"7%","D":"8%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using the Rule of 72: Years to double = 72 / Interest Rate. To find the rate: 72 / 12 years = 6% annual return needed to double the investment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv33","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, which of the following would be considered an advertisement by an investment adviser?","choices":{"A":"A website describing services and investment philosophy","B":"A bulk email sent to prospective clients","C":"A social media post highlighting past performance","D":"All of the above are considered advertisements"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Under SEC rules, advertisements include any communication addressed to more than one person that promotes advisory services or solicits clients. This includes websites, mass emails, social media posts, brochures, and any other broadly distributed materials.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","sec"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv34","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser may disclose confidential client information to a third party WITHOUT client consent when:","choices":{"A":"The third party is a potential business partner","B":"Compelled by legal process such as a subpoena or court order","C":"The information would benefit the client financially","D":"The third party has signed a confidentiality agreement"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Confidential client information may only be disclosed without consent when required by law, such as in response to a subpoena, court order, or regulatory examination. Business relationships, potential benefits, or third-party agreements do not override the duty of confidentiality.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv35","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under NASAA model rules for continuing education, investment adviser representatives must complete how many hours of CE annually?","choices":{"A":"6 credits annually","B":"10 credits annually","C":"12 credits annually with specific content requirements","D":"15 credits over a 3-year cycle"},"answer":"C","explanation":"NASAA model rules require IARs to complete 12 hours of continuing education annually, including specific hours on ethics, products and practices, and regulatory compliance. This ensures IARs maintain current knowledge.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv39","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an investment adviser with custody of client assets must maintain a minimum net worth OR post a surety bond in the amount of:","choices":{"A":"$35,000 net worth or a surety bond","B":"$25,000 net worth or a surety bond","C":"$10,000 net worth or a surety bond","D":"$5,000 net worth or a surety bond"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under the USA, investment advisers with custody of client assets must maintain a minimum net worth of $35,000. If net worth requirements are not met, a surety bond in an appropriate amount may be required instead.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv43","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A client purchased an unregistered security that should have been registered. Under rescission, the client is entitled to recover:","choices":{"A":"Only the original purchase price","B":"The current market value of the security","C":"The original purchase price plus potential profits","D":"The original purchase price plus interest, minus any income received"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Rescission remedies require the seller to return the purchase price plus interest (typically the legal rate), reduced by any income the buyer received from the security (dividends, interest). This makes the buyer whole for the time value of money.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv47","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which statement about Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is FALSE?","choices":{"A":"IRR is the discount rate that makes NPV equal to zero","B":"A project should be accepted if IRR exceeds the required rate of return","C":"IRR can be used to compare investment alternatives","D":"IRR is calculated by dividing annual dividends by stock price"},"answer":"D","explanation":"IRR is NOT calculated by dividing dividends by price (that formula describes dividend yield). IRR is the discount rate that equates the present value of cash inflows with the initial investment, making NPV equal to zero.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv48","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Investment Advisers Act, access persons must file quarterly transaction reports no later than:","choices":{"A":"10 days after each transaction","B":"10 days after the end of each quarter","C":"30 days after the end of each quarter","D":"45 days after the end of each quarter"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Access persons (those with access to nonpublic information about client transactions or portfolio holdings) must file quarterly transaction reports within 30 days after the end of each calendar quarter. Initial and annual holdings reports have different deadlines.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","sec"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv50","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Which statement about Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) analysis is FALSE?","choices":{"A":"When NPV equals zero, the discount rate used is less than the IRR","B":"A positive NPV indicates the investment exceeds the required return","C":"DCF accounts for the time value of money","D":"Higher discount rates result in lower present values"},"answer":"A","explanation":"This statement is FALSE. When NPV equals zero, the discount rate used IS the IRR (they are equal, not less than). By definition, IRR is the discount rate that makes NPV equal to zero.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv52","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio manager decides to temporarily increase the equity allocation from 60% to 75% based on a belief that stocks will outperform in the near term, while maintaining a long-term strategic allocation of 60% equity. This approach is best described as:","choices":{"A":"Strategic asset allocation","B":"Passive management","C":"Tactical asset allocation","D":"Dollar cost averaging"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tactical asset allocation involves making short-term adjustments to portfolio weights based on market conditions or expectations, while maintaining a long-term strategic allocation target. The manager is temporarily overweighting equities to capitalize on expected near-term performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv54","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investor wants to evaluate a portfolio manager's performance independent of the timing of cash flows into and out of the portfolio. Which return measurement should be used?","choices":{"A":"Time-weighted return because it eliminates the impact of additions and withdrawals","B":"Dollar-weighted return because it includes all cash flows","C":"Holding period return because it is simplest to calculate","D":"Internal rate of return because it accounts for compounding"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Time-weighted return (TWR) is the appropriate measure for evaluating portfolio manager performance because it eliminates the impact of external cash flows (deposits and withdrawals) that are typically outside the manager's control. TWR shows what $1 invested at the beginning would be worth at the end.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv55","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following corporate bonds would typically carry the LOWEST coupon rate due to its secured status?","choices":{"A":"Debentures","B":"Equipment trust certificates","C":"Subordinated debentures","D":"Income bonds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Equipment trust certificates are secured by specific equipment (such as railroad cars or aircraft) and are considered among the safest corporate bonds. Because of this collateral backing, they carry lower interest rates than unsecured debt. Debentures and subordinated debentures are unsecured.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv56","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An affiliate of XYZ Corporation wants to sell restricted stock under Rule 144. XYZ has average weekly trading volume of 50,000 shares and 2,000,000 shares outstanding. What is the maximum number of shares the affiliate can sell in a 90-day period?","choices":{"A":"50,000 shares","B":"20,000 shares","C":"200,000 shares","D":"12,500 shares"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under Rule 144, the volume limit is the greater of: (1) 1% of outstanding shares (2,000,000 x 1% = 20,000), or (2) average weekly trading volume (50,000). Since 50,000 is greater than 20,000, the affiliate can sell up to 50,000 shares in a 90-day period.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv57","section":"Suitability","stem":"A 45-year-old client with moderate risk tolerance seeks long-term capital appreciation for retirement in 20 years. Which investment is MOST suitable?","choices":{"A":"Money market fund","B":"High-yield bond fund","C":"Large cap growth fund","D":"Sector-specific ETF"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A large cap growth fund is appropriate for a moderate growth investor with a 20-year time horizon. Large cap stocks provide growth potential with less volatility than small caps or sector funds. The long time horizon allows recovery from market downturns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv59","section":"Options","stem":"After a customer's options account is approved and the Options Disclosure Document is delivered, within how many days must the signed options agreement be returned?","choices":{"A":"5 days","B":"10 days","C":"30 days","D":"15 days"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The signed options agreement must be returned within 15 days of account approval. If the agreement is not returned within this timeframe, the customer is limited to closing transactions only until the signed agreement is received.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv60","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is permitted in investment adviser advertising under SEC rules?","choices":{"A":"Net of fees performance returns over a 2-year period with appropriate disclosures","B":"Client testimonials guaranteeing future performance","C":"Past performance implying future results will be similar","D":"Cherry-picked profitable trade examples without showing overall performance"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Investment adviser advertising may show net-of-fees performance returns over various periods, provided appropriate disclosures are included. The SEC Marketing Rule allows performance advertising when presented fairly with required disclosures. Testimonials, guarantees, and misleading presentations are prohibited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv61","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A client wants to invest $12,000 in a volatile growth fund but is concerned about market timing. Which strategy would you recommend to reduce the risk of investing at an inopportune time?","choices":{"A":"Invest $1,000 monthly using dollar cost averaging","B":"Wait for market pullback before investing the full amount","C":"Invest the entire amount immediately in a single transaction","D":"Place a limit order at 10% below current price"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Dollar cost averaging involves investing fixed amounts at regular intervals, reducing the impact of market volatility and timing risk. By investing $1,000 monthly, the client will buy more shares when prices are low and fewer when prices are high, achieving an average cost over time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv62","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which mutual fund share class typically has the longest contingent deferred sales charge (CDSC) schedule?","choices":{"A":"Class A shares","B":"Class C shares","C":"Institutional shares","D":"Class B shares"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Class B shares typically have the longest CDSC schedule, often lasting 6-8 years before declining to zero. Class C shares usually have a shorter CDSC period (1-2 years), while Class A shares have front-end loads rather than CDSCs. Institutional shares typically have no sales charges.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv64","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor concerned about reinvestment risk should consider which of the following Treasury securities?","choices":{"A":"Treasury notes paying semi-annual coupons","B":"Treasury STRIPS (zero-coupon bonds)","C":"Treasury bonds with 30-year maturities","D":"Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Treasury STRIPS (zero-coupon bonds) have no reinvestment risk because they make no periodic interest payments. The investor receives only the face value at maturity, eliminating the need to reinvest coupon payments at potentially lower rates. All coupon-paying securities have reinvestment risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv65","section":"Suitability","stem":"A client's primary investment objective is capital appreciation. Which investment would be MOST appropriate?","choices":{"A":"Investment-grade corporate bond fund","B":"Money market fund","C":"Mid-cap growth fund","D":"Treasury bill ladder"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A mid-cap growth fund is most appropriate for capital appreciation. Growth funds invest in companies expected to grow faster than the market, and mid-cap stocks offer a balance of growth potential and stability. Bond and money market investments prioritize income and capital preservation over growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv66","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which statement is TRUE about both exchange-traded notes (ETNs) and exchange-traded funds (ETFs)?","choices":{"A":"Both provide direct ownership of underlying assets","B":"Both trade on stock exchanges throughout the day","C":"Both are backed by the credit of the issuing institution","D":"Both must distribute capital gains annually"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Both ETNs and ETFs trade on exchanges throughout the trading day like stocks. However, they differ significantly: ETFs provide ownership of underlying assets, while ETNs are debt obligations backed by the issuer's credit. ETFs are not credit-dependent, and their capital gains treatment differs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv67","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A client instructs their investment adviser: \"Use your judgment to adjust my portfolio as you see fit to improve diversification.\" What is required before the adviser can act on this instruction?","choices":{"A":"Verbal confirmation from the client","B":"A prospectus for each new investment","C":"Approval from the state administrator","D":"Written discretionary authority from the client"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Before exercising discretion over a client's account, an investment adviser must obtain written discretionary authority. Verbal instructions are not sufficient for ongoing discretionary management. The client must sign a written authorization specifying the scope of discretion granted.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv68","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An employee exercises incentive stock options (ISOs) and immediately sells the shares in the same year. The exercise price was $20, grant price was $20, and sale price was $45. The employee held 1,000 shares. What are the tax consequences?","choices":{"A":"$25,000 ordinary income","B":"$25,000 long-term capital gain","C":"$25,000 short-term capital gain","D":"No taxable event until the shares are held for more than one year"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When ISOs are exercised and sold in the same year (disqualifying disposition), the gain is taxed as ordinary income, not capital gain. The gain is $45 - $20 = $25 per share x 1,000 shares = $25,000 ordinary income. To receive capital gains treatment, shares must be held 1 year after exercise and 2 years after grant.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv69","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Before transferring assets from a deceased customer's individual account, the firm must receive which document?","choices":{"A":"New account application from the estate","B":"Notarized affidavit from family members","C":"Letter of authorization from the attorney","D":"Death certificate"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A death certificate is required to verify the customer's death before any assets can be transferred from an individual account. Additional documents such as letters testamentary or letters of administration from probate court may also be required depending on the circumstances.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv71","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following statements about duration are TRUE? I. Duration measures a bond's sensitivity to interest rate changes. II. Higher coupon bonds have shorter duration than lower coupon bonds. III. Zero-coupon bonds have duration equal to their maturity.","choices":{"A":"I only","B":"I and II only","C":"I and III only","D":"I, II, and III"},"answer":"D","explanation":"All three statements are true. Duration measures interest rate sensitivity (I). Higher coupon bonds return cash faster, reducing duration (II). Zero-coupon bonds have no intermediate cash flows, so duration equals maturity (III). Duration is a key concept for managing bond portfolio risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv72","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an investment adviser representative (IAR) is best defined as:","choices":{"A":"An individual who represents an investment adviser in providing securities advice, managing portfolios, or soliciting advisory services","B":"Any employee of an investment adviser regardless of duties","C":"A firm registered to provide investment advice","D":"An individual who only performs clerical functions for an adviser"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An IAR is an individual associated with an investment adviser who provides investment advice, manages client accounts, determines recommendations, or solicits advisory services. Not all employees are IARs - only those performing these specific advisory functions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv73","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following activities constitutes a prohibited manipulative practice?","choices":{"A":"Wash trading","B":"A broker-dealer executing a customer order ahead of publishing research (trading ahead)","C":"Matched orders","D":"Painting the tape"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Trading ahead (front-running research) is a prohibited practice but is a violation of fair dealing rules, not market manipulation per se. Wash trading, matched orders, and painting the tape are all forms of market manipulation designed to create a false appearance of trading activity or artificially affect prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv74","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A client wants to grant an adviser authority to buy and sell securities on their behalf but NOT to withdraw funds from the account. What type of authorization is appropriate?","choices":{"A":"Full power of attorney","B":"Durable power of attorney","C":"Non-discretionary authorization","D":"Limited power of attorney (trading authorization)"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A limited power of attorney (also called trading authorization or limited trading authority) allows an adviser to make investment decisions and execute trades but does not permit withdrawing funds or securities from the account. This is the appropriate authorization for trading-only discretion.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series65-qb-s66-pv75","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which statements about discounted cash flow (DCF) analysis are TRUE? I. DCF determines intrinsic value based on future cash flows. II. A higher discount rate results in a lower present value. III. DCF requires estimation of future cash flows and an appropriate discount rate. IV. DCF is used to evaluate whether a security is overvalued or undervalued.","choices":{"A":"I and II only","B":"II and III only","C":"I, II, III, and IV","D":"I, III, and IV only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"All four statements are true. DCF determines intrinsic value by discounting expected future cash flows (I). Higher discount rates reduce present value mathematically (II). DCF requires cash flow projections and a discount rate (III). Comparing DCF value to market price identifies over/undervaluation (IV).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-119","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"By what age must all assets in a Coverdell Education Savings Account be distributed to avoid tax penalties?","choices":{"A":"Age 18","B":"Age 21","C":"Age 30","D":"Age 591/2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Coverdell ESA assets must be distributed by the time the beneficiary reaches age 30. If not used for qualified education expenses by then, the remaining balance is subject to income tax plus a 10% penalty on earnings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-127","section":"Economics","stem":"A company has current assets of $500,000 and current liabilities of $250,000. What is its current ratio?","choices":{"A":"0.5 to 1","B":"1.5 to 1","C":"2 to 1","D":"2.5 to 1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Current ratio = current assets / current liabilities = $500,000 / $250,000 = 2 to 1. A ratio of 2:1 indicates the company has twice the current assets needed to cover its short-term obligations, a common benchmark for adequate liquidity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","liquidity-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-128","section":"Economics","stem":"The quick ratio (acid-test ratio) differs from the current ratio in that it:","choices":{"A":"Includes long-term debt in the calculation","B":"Excludes inventory from current assets","C":"Adds inventory to current assets","D":"Uses total assets instead of current assets"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The quick ratio excludes inventory (and prepaid expenses) from current assets because inventory is the least liquid current asset. Quick ratio = (current assets - inventory) / current liabilities. It is a more conservative liquidity measure than the current ratio.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","liquidity-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-129","section":"Economics","stem":"Working capital is calculated as:","choices":{"A":"Total assets minus total liabilities","B":"Current assets minus current liabilities","C":"Current assets divided by current liabilities","D":"Net income minus dividends"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Working capital = current assets - current liabilities. It measures the dollar amount of liquid resources available to fund day-to-day operations. (Current assets DIVIDED BY current liabilities is the current ratio, a different metric.)","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","balance-sheet"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-130","section":"Economics","stem":"A company's debt-to-equity ratio is BEST described as a measure of:","choices":{"A":"Short-term liquidity","B":"Profitability","C":"Financial leverage","D":"Inventory efficiency"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The debt-to-equity ratio (total liabilities / shareholders' equity) measures financial leverage - how much of the company's capital comes from borrowing versus owners' equity. A high ratio indicates greater reliance on debt and higher financial risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","leverage-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-131","section":"Economics","stem":"Return on equity (ROE) is calculated as:","choices":{"A":"Net income divided by total assets","B":"Net income divided by shareholders' equity","C":"Revenue divided by shareholders' equity","D":"Operating income divided by total liabilities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Return on equity = net income / shareholders' equity. ROE measures how efficiently a company generates profit from each dollar of shareholders' investment. (Net income / total assets is return on assets, a related but distinct ratio.)","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","profitability-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-132","section":"Economics","stem":"A company reports net income of $2,000,000 and has 1,000,000 shares of common stock outstanding. Its earnings per share (EPS) is:","choices":{"A":"$0.50","B":"$2.00","C":"$5.00","D":"$20.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Basic EPS = net income available to common shareholders / weighted average shares outstanding = $2,000,000 / 1,000,000 = $2.00 per share. EPS is a key input for the price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","equity-valuation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-133","section":"Economics","stem":"The price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio of a stock is calculated by:","choices":{"A":"Dividing the dividend by the stock price","B":"Dividing the market price per share by earnings per share","C":"Dividing earnings per share by the market price","D":"Multiplying the dividend yield by EPS"},"answer":"B","explanation":"P/E ratio = market price per share / earnings per share. It indicates how much investors are willing to pay for each dollar of earnings. A high P/E may signal growth expectations or overvaluation; a low P/E may signal value or weak prospects.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","equity-valuation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-134","section":"Economics","stem":"Which financial statement reports a company's revenues, expenses, and net income over a period of time?","choices":{"A":"Balance sheet","B":"Income statement","C":"Statement of cash flows","D":"Statement of shareholders' equity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The income statement (profit and loss statement) reports revenues, expenses, and resulting net income over a period such as a quarter or year. The balance sheet, by contrast, is a snapshot at a single point in time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","income-statement"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-135","section":"Economics","stem":"The statement of cash flows classifies cash flows into three categories. Which is NOT one of them?","choices":{"A":"Operating activities","B":"Investing activities","C":"Financing activities","D":"Speculative activities"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The statement of cash flows is divided into operating, investing, and financing activities. There is no 'speculative activities' category. Operating reflects core business cash; investing reflects asset purchases/sales; financing reflects debt and equity transactions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","cash-flow"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-136","section":"Economics","stem":"On a balance sheet, the basic accounting equation states that:","choices":{"A":"Assets = Liabilities - Equity","B":"Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity","C":"Equity = Assets + Liabilities","D":"Liabilities = Assets + Equity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The fundamental accounting equation is Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity. The balance sheet must always 'balance' - everything a company owns is financed either by what it owes (liabilities) or by owners' capital (equity).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["financial-analysis","balance-sheet"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-137","section":"Economics","stem":"Which item would appear under shareholders' equity on a corporate balance sheet?","choices":{"A":"Accounts payable","B":"Retained earnings","C":"Accounts receivable","D":"Bonds payable"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Retained earnings - cumulative profits not paid out as dividends - is a component of shareholders' equity. Accounts payable and bonds payable are liabilities; accounts receivable is a current asset.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","balance-sheet"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-138","section":"Economics","stem":"The price-to-book (P/B) ratio compares a stock's market price to its:","choices":{"A":"Earnings per share","B":"Dividend per share","C":"Book value (net asset value) per share","D":"Cash flow per share"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The price-to-book ratio = market price per share / book value per share, where book value = (total assets - total liabilities) / shares outstanding. A P/B below 1 may indicate the stock trades below the accounting value of its net assets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","equity-valuation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-139","section":"Economics","stem":"Stagflation is an economic condition characterized by:","choices":{"A":"Rising GDP and falling unemployment","B":"High inflation combined with stagnant growth and high unemployment","C":"Deflation and rapid economic expansion","D":"Stable prices and full employment"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Stagflation is the simultaneous occurrence of high inflation, stagnant or shrinking economic output, and high unemployment. It is difficult for policymakers because actions to fight inflation (tightening) can worsen unemployment, and vice versa.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","inflation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-140","section":"Economics","stem":"Deflation is BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"A slowdown in the rate of inflation","B":"A general decline in the price level of goods and services","C":"An increase in the money supply","D":"A rise in interest rates"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Deflation is a sustained decline in the general price level (negative inflation). Note this differs from disinflation, which is merely a slowing in the RATE of inflation. Deflation can be harmful by encouraging consumers to delay spending and increasing the real burden of debt.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","inflation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-141","section":"Economics","stem":"The four phases of the business cycle, in order, are:","choices":{"A":"Expansion, peak, contraction, trough","B":"Peak, expansion, trough, contraction","C":"Trough, contraction, peak, expansion","D":"Contraction, trough, peak, expansion"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The business cycle moves through expansion (growth), peak (top), contraction/recession (decline), and trough (bottom), then begins expanding again. Recognizing the current phase helps advisers position portfolios (e.g., favoring defensive sectors in a contraction).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","business-cycle"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-142","section":"Economics","stem":"Which sector typically performs BEST during the early expansion phase of the business cycle?","choices":{"A":"Consumer staples and utilities","B":"Cyclical stocks such as technology and consumer discretionary","C":"Precious metals only","D":"Long-term Treasury bonds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Cyclical stocks (technology, consumer discretionary, industrials) tend to outperform during economic expansion because their earnings rise with consumer and business spending. Defensive sectors (consumer staples, utilities) tend to hold up better during contractions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","business-cycle"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-143","section":"Economics","stem":"Gross Domestic Product (GDP) measures:","choices":{"A":"The total income of all U.S. citizens worldwide","B":"The market value of all final goods and services produced within a country in a period","C":"The total value of a country's exports only","D":"Government spending plus business investment only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"GDP is the total market value of all final goods and services produced within a nation's borders during a specific period. Its expenditure components are consumption + investment + government spending + net exports (C + I + G + NX).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","gdp"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-144","section":"Economics","stem":"Which of the following is the LARGEST component of U.S. GDP?","choices":{"A":"Government spending","B":"Business investment","C":"Personal consumption expenditures","D":"Net exports"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Personal consumption expenditures (consumer spending) is the largest component of U.S. GDP, typically around two-thirds of total output. This is why consumer confidence and spending data are closely watched economic indicators.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","gdp"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-145","section":"Economics","stem":"Demand-pull inflation occurs when:","choices":{"A":"Production costs such as wages and raw materials rise","B":"Aggregate demand exceeds the economy's productive capacity","C":"The money supply contracts sharply","D":"Unemployment rises rapidly"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Demand-pull inflation results from aggregate demand outpacing the economy's ability to produce goods and services - 'too many dollars chasing too few goods.' This contrasts with cost-push inflation, driven by rising input costs such as labor and materials.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["macroeconomics","inflation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-146","section":"Economics","stem":"The Federal Reserve's primary tool for conducting monetary policy on a day-to-day basis is:","choices":{"A":"Changing the reserve requirement","B":"Open market operations","C":"Adjusting the federal estate tax","D":"Setting fiscal spending levels"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Open market operations - the buying and selling of U.S. government securities by the FOMC - is the Fed's most frequently used and flexible monetary policy tool. Buying securities injects reserves and lowers rates; selling securities drains reserves and raises rates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","frb"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-147","section":"Economics","stem":"When the Federal Reserve sells U.S. government securities in the open market, the effect is generally to:","choices":{"A":"Increase the money supply and lower interest rates","B":"Decrease the money supply and raise interest rates","C":"Have no effect on interest rates","D":"Increase the federal deficit"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the Fed SELLS securities, it removes reserves from the banking system, shrinking the money supply and putting upward pressure on interest rates. This is contractionary (tightening) monetary policy used to combat inflation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","frb"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-148","section":"Economics","stem":"The discount rate is:","choices":{"A":"The rate banks charge each other for overnight loans","B":"The rate the Federal Reserve charges banks for short-term loans through its discount window","C":"The Fed's target inflation rate","D":"The rate on long-term Treasury bonds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The discount rate is the interest rate the Federal Reserve charges commercial banks for short-term loans obtained directly from the Fed (the discount window). It differs from the federal funds rate, which is the rate banks charge EACH OTHER for overnight loans.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-149","section":"Economics","stem":"The federal funds rate is the interest rate:","choices":{"A":"The Fed charges banks at the discount window","B":"Banks charge each other for overnight loans of reserves","C":"Charged on 10-year Treasury notes","D":"Banks charge their most creditworthy corporate customers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The federal funds rate is the rate banks charge one another for overnight loans of reserve balances. The FOMC sets a target range for this rate as its primary monetary policy lever. (The rate banks charge their best corporate customers is the prime rate.)","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-150","section":"Economics","stem":"The prime rate is BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"The rate the Fed pays on bank reserves","B":"The base rate that banks charge their most creditworthy commercial customers","C":"The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond","D":"The rate charged on subprime mortgages"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The prime rate is the benchmark interest rate that commercial banks charge their most creditworthy (prime) corporate borrowers. Many consumer and business loan rates are set as the prime rate plus a margin. The prime rate generally moves with the federal funds rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["interest-rates","monetary-policy"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-151","section":"Economics","stem":"If the Federal Reserve RAISES the reserve requirement, the most likely effect is to:","choices":{"A":"Increase the amount banks can lend and expand the money supply","B":"Decrease the amount banks can lend and contract the money supply","C":"Lower interest rates immediately","D":"Increase the federal budget deficit"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Raising the reserve requirement forces banks to hold more deposits in reserve, leaving less available to lend. This contracts the money supply and tends to raise interest rates - a contractionary policy. (The Fed has rarely changed reserve requirements in practice; it set them to zero in 2020.)","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["monetary-policy","frb"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-152","section":"Economics","stem":"M1 and M2 are measures of:","choices":{"A":"Gross domestic product","B":"The money supply","C":"Inflation rates","D":"Federal tax revenue"},"answer":"B","explanation":"M1 and M2 are measures of the money supply. M1 includes the most liquid forms (currency, demand deposits, other checkable deposits); M2 includes M1 plus savings deposits, small time deposits, and retail money market funds. The Fed monitors these aggregates when assessing monetary conditions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["monetary-policy","money-supply"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-153","section":"Economics","stem":"Cost-push inflation is typically caused by:","choices":{"A":"Excessive consumer demand","B":"Rising production costs such as wages and raw materials","C":"An increase in the reserve requirement","D":"A decline in the money supply"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Cost-push inflation occurs when rising input costs (wages, energy, raw materials) push producers to raise prices, reducing supply at each price level. It contrasts with demand-pull inflation, which is driven by excess aggregate demand.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["macroeconomics","inflation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-154","section":"Economics","stem":"A normal (upward-sloping) yield curve indicates that:","choices":{"A":"Short-term rates are higher than long-term rates","B":"Long-term interest rates are higher than short-term rates","C":"All maturities have the same yield","D":"The economy is entering a recession"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A normal yield curve slopes upward, meaning longer-maturity bonds offer higher yields than shorter-maturity bonds. This compensates investors for greater interest-rate and inflation risk over time and typically signals expectations of continued economic growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["interest-rates","yield-curve"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-155","section":"Economics","stem":"A 'flat' yield curve generally suggests that investors expect:","choices":{"A":"Strong, accelerating economic growth","B":"Uncertainty or a transition in the economy, with little difference between short- and long-term rates","C":"Immediate deflation","D":"Rapidly rising inflation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A flat yield curve - where short- and long-term yields are nearly equal - often reflects economic uncertainty or a transition period, frequently appearing as the curve shifts between a normal (upward) and inverted (downward) shape.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["interest-rates","yield-curve"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-156","section":"Economics","stem":"Expansionary FISCAL policy involves:","choices":{"A":"The Federal Reserve buying securities","B":"Increased government spending and/or tax cuts","C":"Raising the discount rate","D":"Selling Treasury securities to banks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fiscal policy is conducted by Congress and the President through taxation and spending. Expansionary fiscal policy - increased government spending and/or tax cuts - aims to stimulate demand. Monetary policy (buying securities, changing rates) is conducted by the Federal Reserve.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiscal-policy","macroeconomics"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-157","section":"Economics","stem":"Which government body is responsible for FISCAL policy in the United States?","choices":{"A":"The Federal Reserve Board","B":"The Congress and the President","C":"The Securities and Exchange Commission","D":"The Federal Open Market Committee"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fiscal policy - decisions about government taxation and spending - is set by Congress and the President. Monetary policy - control of the money supply and interest rates - is conducted by the Federal Reserve (through the FOMC). Series 65 candidates must distinguish these two.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiscal-policy","macroeconomics"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-158","section":"Economics","stem":"The balance of payments deficit means a country:","choices":{"A":"Has a balanced federal budget","B":"Sends more money abroad than it receives from foreign sources","C":"Has a budget surplus","D":"Collects more in taxes than it spends"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A balance of payments deficit means more money is flowing OUT of the country (for imports, foreign investment, etc.) than is flowing IN. This is distinct from a federal budget deficit, which concerns government spending exceeding tax revenue.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["macroeconomics","international"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-159","section":"Economics","stem":"A WEAKENING U.S. dollar tends to:","choices":{"A":"Make U.S. exports more expensive abroad","B":"Make U.S. exports cheaper and more competitive abroad","C":"Reduce the cost of imported goods","D":"Have no effect on trade"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the dollar weakens, U.S. goods become cheaper for foreign buyers, boosting exports, while imported goods become more expensive for U.S. consumers. A weak dollar generally helps U.S. exporters and multinational firms with overseas revenue.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","currency"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-160","section":"Economics","stem":"The Coincident Economic Index includes indicators that:","choices":{"A":"Change before the overall economy changes","B":"Move at roughly the same time as the overall economy","C":"Change after the economy has already turned","D":"Predict inflation two years out"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Coincident indicators (such as nonfarm payroll employment, industrial production, and personal income) move at approximately the same time as the broad economy and confirm the current phase of the business cycle. Leading indicators change in advance; lagging indicators change afterward.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators","business-cycle"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-161","section":"Economics","stem":"Which of the following is a LAGGING economic indicator?","choices":{"A":"Building permits","B":"Stock prices (S&P 500)","C":"The average duration of unemployment","D":"New orders for consumer goods"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The average duration of unemployment is a lagging indicator - it tends to change after the economy has already turned. Building permits, stock prices, and new orders for consumer goods are all leading indicators that change ahead of the broad economy.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["economic-indicators","business-cycle"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-162","section":"Economics","stem":"The unemployment rate is considered which type of economic indicator?","choices":{"A":"Leading","B":"Coincident","C":"Lagging","D":"It is not an economic indicator"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The unemployment rate is a lagging indicator. Employers are typically slow to lay off workers when a downturn begins and slow to hire when recovery starts, so changes in unemployment generally trail changes in the broad economy.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators","business-cycle"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-163","section":"Economics","stem":"The Producer Price Index (PPI) measures:","choices":{"A":"Prices paid by consumers at the retail level","B":"The average change in selling prices received by domestic producers","C":"Wage growth in manufacturing","D":"The unemployment rate among producers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The PPI measures the average change over time in selling prices received by domestic producers (wholesale level). It is watched as an early signal of inflation that may later pass through to consumer prices, which are tracked by the Consumer Price Index (CPI).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators","inflation"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-164","section":"Economics","stem":"Real GDP differs from nominal GDP in that real GDP:","choices":{"A":"Includes government spending while nominal GDP does not","B":"Is adjusted for inflation using constant dollars","C":"Counts only exported goods","D":"Is always larger than nominal GDP"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Real GDP is adjusted for inflation and expressed in constant (base-year) dollars, allowing meaningful comparison of output across time. Nominal GDP is measured in current dollars and can rise simply because prices increased, not because more was produced.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["macroeconomics","gdp"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-165","section":"Economics","stem":"In a market with PERFECTLY INELASTIC demand, a price increase will:","choices":{"A":"Cause quantity demanded to fall sharply","B":"Leave quantity demanded essentially unchanged","C":"Cause demand to disappear entirely","D":"Increase the quantity demanded"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Perfectly inelastic demand means quantity demanded does not change when price changes (e.g., a life-saving medication). A price increase therefore leaves the quantity purchased essentially unchanged and increases total revenue for the seller.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["microeconomics","elasticity"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-166","section":"Economics","stem":"A company's net profit margin is calculated as:","choices":{"A":"Net income divided by total assets","B":"Net income divided by net sales (revenue)","C":"Gross profit divided by net income","D":"Operating income divided by shareholders' equity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Net profit margin = net income / net sales (revenue). It measures how many cents of profit a company generates for each dollar of sales. A higher margin indicates more efficient conversion of revenue into profit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["financial-analysis","profitability-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-167","section":"Economics","stem":"A bond's interest coverage ratio measures a company's ability to:","choices":{"A":"Repay the principal of its bonds at maturity","B":"Pay the interest on its debt out of operating earnings","C":"Convert bonds into common stock","D":"Pay dividends to preferred shareholders"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The interest coverage ratio (times-interest-earned) = EBIT / interest expense. It measures how many times a company's operating earnings can cover its interest obligations. A higher ratio indicates a greater margin of safety for bondholders.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["financial-analysis","leverage-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-168","section":"Economics","stem":"An adviser reviewing a company notes a rising inventory turnover ratio. This generally indicates the company is:","choices":{"A":"Holding inventory longer before selling it","B":"Selling its inventory more quickly and efficiently","C":"Increasing its long-term debt","D":"Reducing its accounts receivable collection period"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Inventory turnover = cost of goods sold / average inventory. A rising turnover ratio means inventory is being sold and replaced more frequently, generally a sign of efficient operations and strong demand. A falling ratio may signal overstocking or weak sales.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["financial-analysis","efficiency-ratios"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-169","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, the definition of an 'investment adviser' EXCLUDES which of the following?","choices":{"A":"A person who manages client portfolios for a fee","B":"A bank or bank holding company","C":"A financial planner who charges fees for investment advice","D":"A money manager with discretionary authority"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Uniform Securities Act excludes banks, savings institutions, and trust companies from the definition of investment adviser. Also excluded are certain professionals (lawyers, accountants, engineers, teachers) whose advice is incidental, and broker-dealers whose advice is incidental with no special compensation (the LATE/BANS exclusions).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-170","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser representative (IAR) must register in a state when the IAR:","choices":{"A":"Has a place of business in the state, regardless of client type","B":"Only manages institutional money","C":"Has fewer than 5 clients nationwide","D":"Works only for an SEC-registered adviser, in all cases"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An IAR with a place of business in a state must register there. For federal covered (SEC-registered) advisers, IARs still register at the state level if they have a place of business in the state. The de minimis exemption (no place of business, 5 or fewer retail clients) can exempt an IAR with no in-state office.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["iar-registration","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-171","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, an adviser owes clients a fiduciary duty that consists of:","choices":{"A":"A duty of loyalty and a duty of care","B":"Only a duty to avoid fraud","C":"A duty to guarantee positive returns","D":"A duty to outperform the market"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An investment adviser's fiduciary duty comprises a duty of loyalty (act in the client's best interest, avoid or disclose conflicts) and a duty of care (provide suitable advice and seek best execution). It does NOT include guaranteeing returns or beating the market.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-172","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under NASAA rules, an investment adviser with discretionary authority over client accounts but WITHOUT custody must generally maintain a minimum net worth of:","choices":{"A":"$5,000","B":"$10,000","C":"$35,000","D":"$100,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"NASAA's Model Rule requires a minimum net worth of $10,000 for a state-registered adviser with discretionary authority but no custody. Advisers who maintain custody of client assets face the higher $35,000 net worth requirement (or a surety bond).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["ia-registration","net-worth-requirements"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-173","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser is generally deemed to have CUSTODY of client funds or securities when the adviser:","choices":{"A":"Has discretionary trading authority only","B":"Holds client funds/securities or can withdraw assets from the client's account","C":"Recommends specific securities to clients","D":"Receives an advisory fee billed quarterly in arrears"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Custody means holding client funds or securities, directly or indirectly, or having authority to obtain possession of them - for example, the ability to deduct fees beyond a normal arrangement or to withdraw assets via a power of attorney. Mere discretionary trading authority alone is not custody.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["custody","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-174","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which of the following is a 'federal covered security' that is EXEMPT from state registration?","choices":{"A":"A security issued by a small intrastate company","B":"A security listed on the New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq","C":"A non-exempt private placement","D":"A municipal bond issued in another state"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Federal covered securities - including securities listed on national exchanges such as the NYSE and Nasdaq, and investment company (mutual fund) shares registered under the Investment Company Act of 1940 - are exempt from state registration under the National Securities Markets Improvement Act (NSMIA).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act","securities-registration"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-175","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the brochure rule (Form ADV Part 2), an investment adviser must deliver its disclosure brochure to a client:","choices":{"A":"Only after the client complains","B":"No later than at the time of entering into the advisory contract","C":"Within 30 days after the contract ends","D":"Only if requested in writing"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The brochure rule requires advisers to deliver Form ADV Part 2 (the disclosure brochure) at or before entering into an advisory agreement, and to deliver an updated brochure or summary of material changes annually. This ensures clients receive material information about the adviser's services, fees, and conflicts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["form-adv","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-176","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following practices by an investment adviser would be considered an UNETHICAL business practice under NASAA's Model Rule?","choices":{"A":"Disclosing all material conflicts of interest","B":"Borrowing money from a client who is not in the business of lending","C":"Recommending suitable investments based on a client profile","D":"Charging a reasonable advisory fee"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Borrowing money or securities from a client (unless the client is a broker-dealer, affiliate, or financial institution in the business of lending) is a prohibited, unethical practice under NASAA rules. Lending to clients is likewise prohibited. These rules guard against exploitation of the advisory relationship.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["unethical-practices","nasaa-rules"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-177","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, an advisory contract must generally provide that:","choices":{"A":"The adviser guarantees against loss","B":"Assignment of the contract requires client consent","C":"Performance fees may always be charged","D":"The adviser may share in client profits and losses"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Uniform Securities Act requires that an advisory contract not be assigned without client consent, prohibit profit-sharing/performance fees except for qualified clients, and require notice to clients of any change in the membership of an advisory partnership. Guaranteeing against loss is a prohibited practice.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["advisory-contracts","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-178","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The Administrator under the Uniform Securities Act has the authority to:","choices":{"A":"Set federal income tax rates","B":"Issue cease and desist orders, deny/suspend/revoke registrations, and conduct investigations","C":"Approve the merits of every security as a good investment","D":"Guarantee the accuracy of a registration statement"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The state Administrator may conduct investigations, issue cease-and-desist orders, deny/suspend/revoke registrations, and pursue civil/criminal referrals. The Administrator does NOT approve the merits of securities; registration never implies that the Administrator has passed on the investment's quality.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-administrator","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-179","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, the statute of limitations for civil liability in a securities sale is generally the EARLIER of:","choices":{"A":"1 year after discovery or 2 years after the sale","B":"2 years after discovery or 3 years after the sale","C":"3 years after discovery or 5 years after the sale","D":"There is no statute of limitations"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, a civil suit must be brought within the earlier of two years after discovery of the violation or three years after the sale (the '2-and-3' rule). Candidates should not confuse this with criminal statutes of limitations or federal time limits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["civil-liability","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-180","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent (registered representative) under the Uniform Securities Act is defined as an individual who:","choices":{"A":"Represents a broker-dealer or issuer in effecting securities transactions","B":"Only provides investment advice for a fee","C":"Is always exempt from registration","D":"Manages a mutual fund's portfolio"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under the USA, an 'agent' is an individual (a natural person) who represents a broker-dealer or issuer in effecting or attempting to effect securities transactions. Note that only individuals can be agents - a broker-dealer itself is not an agent. A person giving advice for a fee is an investment adviser representative, not an agent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["agent-registration","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series65-s65-q-181","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Selling away - an agent effecting securities transactions not recorded on the broker-dealer's books without the firm's authorization - is:","choices":{"A":"Permitted if the client consents","B":"A prohibited and unethical practice","C":"Required for held-away assets","D":"Allowed for accredited investors only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Selling away (executing private securities transactions outside the firm without written authorization) is a prohibited, unethical practice. All securities business an agent conducts must be supervised and recorded by the employing broker-dealer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 65)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["unethical-practices","agent-registration"]}];
